My 20th year Anniversary @mercedesbenz

As a young boy I dreamed to work for @mercedesamg
I was fascinated from the Brand, the passion the two founders (Aufrecht and Melcher) had and the pure strength to get their dream come true! It had a huge impact on me to see nothing can stop you in life if you really want it!

As a young kid I wanted to follow into the footsteps of my great grandfather, grandfather and especially my dad who all worked 45 years for Daimler. But I never forgot my personal goal and this was AMG. On the weekends I drove to Affalterbach only to admire the cars and feel the the atmosphere there.

After years of working for Mercedes-Benz
I grabbed the chance and started working for AMG. I want to share here on Instagram how it feels to work for the Best Performance and Sports Car Brand in the world as an engine builder.

Sometimes it‚Äôs time to reflect how things can turn out in your life if you are ready to do it and work hard for it!
To be an engine builder for Mercedes-AMG is not only a job for me. It was my dream and now I can truly say, I am able to live my dream everyday. I really put all my heart and soul into my work.

It is a big honor for me to see the love, the passion for my work and the love for Mercedes-AMG you all share here with me.

Thank you to all the Ladies and Gentlemans all over the world with an engine handcrafted from me, to all AMG, Pagani customers and fans worldwide that share the passion and love for my work here on Instagram.

You all here make this Brand as special as it is to me. We all share so many moments together and became a big family. 
Thank you to all of you for that!

AMG GT Black Series ‚ÄûThe Endgame‚Äú.

Back in the days, the most powerful AMG V8 series engine of all time, the most expressive design, the most elaborate aerodynamics, the most intelligent material mix, the most distinctive driving dynamics: For the new Mercedes-AMG GT Black Series (combined fuel consumption 12.8 l/100 km, combined CO2 emissions 292 g/km)[1], the Affalterbach designers have pulled out all the stops when it comes to the art of vehicle design.

The super sports car perfectly embodies the brand‚Äôs rich tradition in motorsport, as well its many years of expertise in developing complete vehicles which impress in every respect. The result is an output of 537 kW (730 hp) from a V8 engine with a ‚Äöflat‚Äò crankshaft, combined with active aerodynamics and a design which stems directly from the current AMG GT3 racing car.

Different designs of V8 engines.

The design of a V8 engine gives designers plenty of room to play with in one key element: the crank arrangement on the crankshaft.
The result is the most powerful V8 series engine from Mercedes-AMG.

The GT Black Series engine may be based on the AMG 4.0-litre V8 biturbo engine with dry sump lubrication, but it has been given the new internal code M178 LS2 due to the numerous modifications. It achieves 730hp at 6700-6900 rpm and delivers a maximum torque of 800Nm at 2000-6000 rpm. New camshafts and exhaust manifolds are adapted to the new firing order and further improve the gas cycle.

Both twin scroll exhaust turbochargers are mounted in anti-friction bearings, as in the top-of-the-range four-door AMG GT CoupeÃÅ, which optimises their throttle response even further. However, in the Black Series, the turbochargers have been given a larger compressor wheel, meaning that both can deliver a total of 1100 kg air per hour.

Finding Authenticity with Elliott Sailors - Episode 07 - Elemental Connections Podcast. 
During this episode I spoke with activist, model and Holistic Life Coach, Elliott Sailors. 
We discussed the theme of Authenticity, and how it‚Äôs the key to a finding satisfaction in life. 

We all have such a unique life journey. Everyone‚Äôs purpose and truth is theirs alone to discover. The important thing is learning to tune in to that inner knowing, and accepting ourselves in entirety. When we show up authentically, we inspire other to do the same, and are able to make deeper, and more meaningful connections. 
Our conversation was a lot of fun - it was open, fluid and very inspiring.
We hope you enjoy it as much as we did!

There‚Äôs not much I love more than meeting interesting people and learning what makes them tick. So when @oneplus commissioned me to interview and photograph Marc Spelmann (@iamspelmann) for @VICE, I jumped at the opportunity.

You‚Äôve probably seen Marc at work ‚Äî even if you don‚Äôt know it yet ‚Äî on Britain‚Äôs Got Talent or America‚Äôs Got Talent as his alter-ego, Magician X (@iammagicianx), leading to incredible success online and off, and hundreds of millions of fans around the world.

We spent an afternoon at Marc‚Äôs home studio in London chatting about our shared love of sci-fi, special effects, cognitive psychology, and design (among his many talents, Marc is a trained illustrator and graphic designer), and of course, magic.

Marc is, unsurprisingly, a talented wordsmith, and one thing he said keeps running circles around my head in the days since our chat, as it applies to so many human endeavours: ‚ÄúAnything is possible if you put your mind to it, and you have to have that mindset because ultimately what you‚Äôre trying to create is something that should not exist.‚Äù Brilliant.

His story is as captivating as his illusions¬†‚Äî read more from our chat at the link on my profile, and check out Marc and Magician X on Instagram and YouTube for more magic.

Whenever I‚Äôm about to head back to Vienna, I get a happy pang similar to homesickness (appropriately, there is a word in German for exactly this: ‚Äúfernweh‚Äù); a place I was planning to call home before the pandemic (and Brexit) interrupted, I‚Äôm still aiming to make it at least a part-time home one day.

Looking back on these images from February 2020 feels a bit dreamlike¬†‚Äî news outlets were buzzing about COVID-19 during my visit. I remember being surprised that there were no border restrictions upon my return to London, as the first confirmed cases in Austria had been discovered the day of my flight.

That trip was full of promise and excitement for things to come:¬†a full Spring & Summer of travel, workshops, documentary filmmaking, and commissions; a few months in Fall set aside for apartment-hunting in Vienna; years of planning, preparing, and patience all coming to fruition.

Though the last 4 years haven‚Äôt exactly played out how I imagined (ha!), each return to Vienna feels like a mini-reset back to that pre-pandemic energy and momentum.

Hope to see some of you at Wednesday‚Äôs mini-workshop and photowalk ‚Äî¬†link in the usual places ‚úåüèº

More views from Vienna, this time from October 2023 on the new Phoenix color film.

The last few years have been (mostly) good for analog photography: the new Leica M6, increased use of ECN-2 film stocks and processing, news of a new line of Pentax film cameras ‚Äî¬†while we‚Äôre also facing rising film prices and ongoing economic issues elsewhere, I‚Äôll take positive news when it comes.

When Phoenix was released, there was a certain amount of negativity about who was sent sample rolls as the launch coverage and reviews rolled out. The common complaint was that it was only sent to ‚Äúinfluencers‚Äù ‚Äî¬†not a term I love, though people with influence have always been a good strategy for getting the word out.

The implication was that if Phoenix had been sent to ‚Äúreal‚Äù photographers for testing, the images would have been better, or the reviews wouldn‚Äôt have been as favorable, etc. ‚Äî and that the generally-positive public feedback on the new film was only due to said influencers not wanting to get on Harman‚Äôs bad side.

This sort of commentary smells like jealousy, and I get it ‚Äî¬†there are a LOT of amazing photographers out there who haven‚Äôt been blessed by social media‚Äôs algorithmic deities, and it can be frustrating to see opportunities being handed to other people when you feel you could do better. However, indignance doesn‚Äôt do anyone any favors.

It‚Äôs also easy to be jaded, and say companies like @harmanphoto are making a money-grab by selling a limited edition product ‚Äî¬†though I‚Äôd wager most of the folks who made that argument happily took advantage of Black Friday deals.

Harman launched a new, niche product, and you can‚Äôt do that without promotion ‚Äî¬†if you can get the bulk of your press by sending people free product, more power to you.

So, let people be excited about new film! The world has enough darkness right now ‚Äî¬†choose to shine a light where you can.

Heading back to Vienna next week ‚Äî one of my favorite cities ‚Äî to run another mini-workshop and photowalk with my buddy Jahan (@doyoudevelop) and the good folks at @leica_akademie_austria & @leica_camera_austria. Link in my bio + Stories, et al.

This time we‚Äôre digging into high-speed B&W film (3200ISO, pushing film, and the like), so I thought I‚Äôd share some images I‚Äôve been sitting on for a while.

In February 2020, I was in Vienna for a few weeks and brought along a camera I‚Äôd had in my collection for years but never used: a Kodak Retina 1a from 1953.

I slowly captured a single roll of HP5+ while wandering Vienna‚Äôs streets, zone focusing at f11‚Äì16, pushing the roll 1-stop (effectively turning 400ISO film into 800ISO) to keep the shutter speeds higher at those smaller apertures.

I‚Äôll share some more from this roll in a few days ‚Äî it‚Äôll be nice to revisit Vienna on high-speed B&W film nearly 4 years on üéûÔ∏è

RECEITA: SALADA DE BATATA COM CEBOLA CARAMELIZADA E CREAM CHEESE ü•î ‚ú®

His attempts to escape the Russian siege had failed. He and his fellow Ukrainian Marines were surrounded, dozens of miles from friendly lines. They were nearly out of food and ammunition. Some panicked, others quietly resigned themselves to what would come next.
Then, a few days later, senior sailor Sergey Hrebinyk and his comrades emerged from the sprawling Ilyich Iron and Steel works in the southern Ukrainian city of Mariupol. It was April 12, 2022.

Nearly two years later, on the second anniversary of the start of Russia‚Äôs full scale invasion, Serhiy Hrebinyk, 24, remains in captivity as a prisoner of war, held somewhere in Russia. His family sits in purgatory, trapped between that day in April and the present.

The initial panicked flurry of calls to the Red Cross, the Ukrainian military and local officials subsided as official proof of life took months to come. The war dragged on, and now, like thousands of other Ukrainian families with relatives in captivity, the Hrebinyks wait.

Len√ß√≥is Maranhenses is located in northeastern Brazil, this unique national park unveils a mesmerizing landscape that seems like a blend of dreams and reality. Vast expanses of pristine, white sand dunes stretch as far as the eye can see, interrupted only by crystalline lagoons scattered like jewels in the desert. 
During the rainy season these lagoons form, creating a contrast between the azure waters and the pristine sand. 
The best time to go is between June and September, as during this time there is usually enough water from the past rainy season.

Viktoriia M. (not her real name), a member of the National Guard at the Chornobyl Nuclear Power Plant, is overcome with emotion as she recounts the harrowing story of her husband. Also a member of the Ukrainian National Guard, he was detained by Russian troops during their occupation of Chornobyl two years ago.

She is heartbroken because she has not yet received any sign that he is alive. Without knowing his whereabouts or the conditions he may be enduring, he is still one of the "10,000 [prisoners of war] believed to remain in Russian custody." - Forbes, 10/21/23. I am personally devastated by the diminishing support for Ukraine by the US and other western countries.

In November of last year, I photographed Viktoriia in an unmarked room to protect her and her husband's identities. She remains cautious and fearful for his fate.

I have been documenting the aftermath of the Chornobyl catastrophe for many decades. Since the Russian occupation after the start of the war in Ukraine, I have felt that my work remains unfinished. Following 10 months of negotiations, I was finally granted permission to re-enter the exclusion zone last October. Pay attention to this page over the coming weeks as I will be posting more images and stories from this trip.

World-renowned artist Joseph Beuys, easily identified by his iconic felt hat, kisses his wife Eva outside their home and studio at the Drakeplatz in D√ºsseldorf in 1978.

This photograph will be included in my upcoming bilingual book BEUYS LAND, published by Edition Lammerhuber, which will be printed later this month and available April/May 2024.

@thephotosociety #ValentinesDay #BEUYSLAND #JosephBeuys #artist

Joseph Beuys, one of the most influential artists of the 20th century, talking about his art in the kitchen of his residence/studio at Drakeplatz in D√ºsseldorf. This photograph will be included in my upcoming book BEUYS LAND, published by Edition Lammerhuber, available late April of 2024. 

BEUYS LAND is the first book to centralize the natural landscape of the Lower Rhine and Joseph Beuys' purported birthplace, Kleve, within the artist's universe. In January 1978, I captured how Beuys revisited his past in Kleve and its Lower Rhine environs, the place where his journey began. My collection of photographs predominantly features Beuys amidst the characteristic landscape of dykes, ponds, poplar-lined avenues, and the local populace. These images palpably convey the interdependence of Beuys' art concept and the starkness of his landscape. The book also includes never-before-published photographs of Beuys and his wife Eva at their residence/studio in D√ºsseldorf and the Basler Fasnacht (Carnival of Basel) in Switzerland.

Accompanying my photographs, cultural scientist Frank Mehring explores how Beuys derived inspiration and energy from the Lower Rhine's roots, honed his ecological consciousness, and nurtured the artistic dynamism that propelled him to the forefront of the global art scene.

Today, January 23, 2024 marks the 38th anniversary of Joseph Beuys‚Äô passing.

Ilyinsty, Ukraine, 2005. None of the nearly 400 elderly living in the Exclusion Zone have easy access to medical treatment. To ensure basic health care, teams of doctors from the Chernobyl hospital make their rounds to different villages about once every month.

I just returned from Zurich, where I attended the opening of the OPEN YOUR EYES Photo Festival. This photograph was taken inside the highly contaminated reactor #4 of the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (Ukraine, 2011). After the explosion, cleanup crews initially had to pass over hazardous ladders to a section underneath the melted core with life-threatening contamination. To facilitate faster access, a daunting hallway called the leaning staircase was erected. When I entered this area of the reactor, radiation was still so high that access was limited to less than 30 minutes per day. 

#Chernobyl #thenextchapter #chornobyl #Ukraine #Kickstarter @kickstarter

Silent nursery inside the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone. On the day the Nuclear Power Plant‚Äôs reactor #4 blew up, children oblivious to the nuclear accident played in this kindergarten of the reactor‚Äôs company town, Pripyat. The following day they were evacuated and had to leave everything behind ‚Äì even their treasured dolls and toys.

I have been given the rare opportunity to return to the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone and reactor #4 itself to document the highly contaminated areas beneath the New Safe Confinement and meet with victims, liquidators, and the few remaining returnees who are still living in the Zone. 

As traditional media outlets lack the necessary funds to support long-term reporting, I have once again turned to the Kickstarter community, colleagues, friends, and followers for assistance in this endeavor. 

Tap the link in bio to learn more and support my Kickstarter campaign.

Climbing brings us together.  Once you challenge yourself with gravity and share this experience with your friends something changes. It's the international language of belaying and spotting. It's the same everywhere. You have to trust someone to achieve your goals. 

@memphisroxclimbing has been a flywheel for the good that climbing brings. Built in the shell of a supermarket with a state of the facility, Rox is bringing gym climbing and outdoor experiences to South Memphis.

With a pay as one can model, the gym is open to everyone. Climbing as I was introduced to it was free. The cliffs were at  end of the road and my dad and his buddies had the gear and knowledge. I still recall the moment when climbing and being outdoors latched on. It's that same emotion that we see with the people we welcome to the crag, mountain and gym. Let's keep that going! 

The freedom that climbing brings comes at a cost. The facility and staff are monthly obligations. In business, as in climbing, the unexpected happens. In this case a burst water pipe needs immediate attention. To keep Rox a safe place (it's a polling station, health care facility and restaurant) the security team needs immediate funding. Going without costs the program more. 

Rox has been a part of my life for the past six years. I've made new friends, shared backcountry experience & knowledge while climbing outdoors and learned from each other on how to address the challenges of race in the United States. 

If you believe in the mission of @memphisroxclimbing please consider a donation. It will be put to good use. If you have the chance to visit Memphis, stop by the gym. You'll find family by the time you have warmed up.

The @khumbuclimbingcenter begins with a Puja ceremony. The students, instructors and volunteers hike to the lower Khumbila ice flows and share a meaningful start to the course. Aou Lama has been part of this tradition for 14 years. 
Once the ceremony concludes we toss toasted barley in the sky for long life. We then share the pemar (barley cake cone) and Losar biscuits. Once the goodness is lined out we begin climbing.

30 years ago today,  the last day of the year,  @johnmiddendorf4 and I climbed Cerro Torre, Patagonia via the Compressor Route. (South East Ridge) Established in 1970 by Cesare Maestri with a gasoline powered drill, the controversial route sported a stack of bolts and was the quick way to the top. 

John and I enjoyed the climb,  yet these was something amiss. The wildness of this peak was sacrificed for human ego. Maestri, making up for his fanciful ascent of 1959, bolted the peak into submission. 
 
In 2012 the late Hayden Kennedy and 
@jason_kruk removed the bolts, giving the mountain its power back and creating controversy.

If Cerro Torre is a peak that you are interested in please listen to @climbinggold. The recent season includes the Maestri Mystery with insight from @kellycordes, author of "The Tower", the definitive book on this subject.

In reviewing my journal from 30 years ago I reflect on how climbing has changed. Even if we have better weather  forecasts and lighter & stronger gear, the sense of self discovery one gets from a proper Patagonian beat down still remains. This primal connection to living is as real as it gets. 

First photo of the Cerro Torro group from the summit of Chalten by Galen Rowell.

Kyle Allen Rott 1987 - 2023 
On  November  25th we lost Kyle in a fall in Hyalite Canyon, Montana. My heart goes out to his mother and sister and the South Dakota family of this fine man.  For his friends the loss is immediate. The years of being together,  weaving the fabric of friendship through shared experiences are gone.

Kyle was a climber. Once he realized that the pursuit of gravity was his life's calling,  he lived with a singular purpose. "Let's go climb."

As someone close to Kyle, his "uncle" by age and knowing him with our family, his loss is another weight on the scale of "is it worth it".

Many of my close friends are introverts. In school we found each other and climbing self selected us. Kyle and I climbed together for 15 years - most of the time hiking the folds of Southwest Montana looking for the cliffs and drips that sustain us. In between climbs he helped out by housesitting for the climbing community. For those of that trusted Kyle without houses and animals - you know how conscientious he was.  Kyle's humble approach to life - not entertaining anything superfluous - was reflected by living in his truck.  Which made housesitting a good balance. 

While Kyle was quiet and shy in a room of his peers, there was this friendly side that Kyle shared with people in life. More than once he would carefully explain the gadgets needed to climb to curious people on the trail. This translated well to the guiding he did with Montana Alpine Guides and the Mountain School in Yosemite. 

At our service for Kyle we wrote in a small book for his mother and family. His worldly possessions, kept tidy in a Livingston storage locker, spread out over a picnic table, passed to his friends. They will cherish his memory and then ply the seas of gravity, risking it all for the moment. For his age peers, dealing with non sequential death, many for the first time, left adrift questioning and bonding closer with those that stand. I was there. And now 30 years later as an elder, with culpability and responsibility.

We love you Kyle for energy you brought to our climbing adventures. 

We love you for the reminder to live calm.

The Ambler industrial road is a 211-mile corridor across the western Brooks Range that would risk loosing North America‚Äôs largest ecologically connected area to endless open pit mining and development. It would cross 1200 rivers and streams, disrupt the migration of the Western Arctic
caribou herd, slice through Gates of the Arctic National Preserve and dismantle the subsistence livelihood of at least 66 communities. 

Seventy-four tribes and First Nations on the Yukon River watershed, 37 tribal governments in the Tanana Chiefs Conference, 23 Yupik tribes, 10 Inupiaq tribal governments, and five Athabascan tribes
closest to the road corridor all have standing resolutions in opposition to this disastrous development project.

The Biden Administration and the Bureau of Land Management have the authority to revoke permits and end it‚Äôs trajectory forward.

I‚Äôve been in a time warp for the past 2 days tackling the biggest DIY project I‚Äôve done on the house yet: repairing and updating this giant faux stone wall in the guest house. 

@terbumurph flew in to help me, and though we‚Äôd never done it before we were able to patch the edges of missing mortar and white wash the wall with a Venetian Glaze to brighten the room up a bit!

What do you think? Do you like the change or would you have left the stones as they were? 

In case anyone cares, I wrote a short blog post on the process üë∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

I can‚Äôt wait to show you all this room/house when everything‚Äôs done.

And thank you so much Molly for your help on this one ‚ù§Ô∏è

This has always been one of my favorite stretches, so I snuck in a few extra rounds after teaching today ‚ù§Ô∏è 

I haven‚Äôt had much time or energy to train recently, but it feels good to sneak it small moments here and there when I can. Usually I try to prioritize my training, but right now I‚Äôm focused on making one of my biggest dreams come true: creating a home that I never want to leave and that I can bring my students and friends to ü•π

Somewhere along the way we got this idea that change is something to be feared. But what if, instead of fearing change, we actually gave ourselves the space to grow into something different, something unexpected. The unknown might be scary, but it‚Äôs also the only place that endless possibilities exist. No one knows what the future holds for any of us, so instead of spending another second focusing on the things I can no longer do, I‚Äôm going to spend each day finding out what I CAN do and being extremely grateful for those things. Because one day that will change, too. 

Thank you all so much for the love and support on my last post, I didn‚Äôt realize how much better I would feel after sharing with you all ü•≤

I was inspired by @erin.skye.circus and @_fleximon to try this leg movement that they did in handstand, anyone else want to try it out?

I‚Äôm glad I knew exactly how much of a gift it was every time I was able to press into handstand, because it is a skill I will likely never be able to do again. 

It‚Äôs pretty amazing that I was able to do any of the harder handstand skills I did with a decaying bone in my wrist, and I‚Äôm so grateful I was able to push it as hard as I did when I did.

I got an MRI recently that confirmed my fears, and the bone in my wrist that is decaying has started to fragment and other parts of my wrist are becoming affected now as well. I didn‚Äôt need imaging to tell me things were getting worse, I could feel it. The good news is I can still do a few handstands here and there for now and demo basic skills in classes, but I will no longer be training handstands regularly or pushing to advance my skills at all. 

There‚Äôs too much to say about all of this, so I‚Äôm not going to say much else right now. I‚Äôm so lucky because I have a lot of amazing things happening in my life that I can focus on, and I can continue sharing my love for handstands through teaching and my students. 

At this point all treatment options are experimental, but don‚Äôt worry I will definitely be over here getting whatever experiments done that I can üî¨

Thanks for reading ‚ù§Ô∏è

My mom had some major breakthroughs last week, including her first unassisted hang since she was a kid! ü§©ü•πüéâ 

She did a multiple reps like this hovering her feet for a few seconds each time. Working with the smith machine has made it more approachable for her, but I‚Äôll get her hanging on a taller bar soon. 

More importantly, after a week of strength training (specifically working on hanging and rows) my mom was able to reach behind her back with no shoulder pain, which is huge for her! 

I‚Äôm in Michigan for the next 10 days but I‚Äôll do a few more sessions with my mom when I‚Äôm back in Maryland for Christmas!

My mom wants to learn how to lift weights, so here‚Äôs a recap of what we did on her first session! 

She has been teaching yoga for a long time and is very active, but her doctor recommended that she build more leg muscle.  She‚Äôs never really lifted weights (more than a few pound dumbbells), so we are building from the ground up with both compound and isolated exercises. 

We started with a standing warm up focusing on balance and leg mobility (I couldn‚Äôt film everything!)
Then we worked on hanging with supported hangs and scapular shrugs (grip strength is super important for older adults and also hanging is great for shoulder health + more)

Then she did:
3 x 10 Goblet Squats
2 x 10 RDLs
2 x 10 Leg Extension Machine (single leg)
2 x 10 Hamstring Curl (both legs)
2 x 15 Hip Abduction
2 x 10 Hip Adduction

Let me know if you found this interesting and I will film her again next time ‚ù§Ô∏è

time for a story. I wanted to create with Inja for a long time. she‚Äôs an actress that moved to LA from Slovenia. super down to earth and fun to chat with, but also crazy expressive and emotional in front of the camera. an absolute dream to work with. she has so much energy and personality that you hardly have to direct, if at all. 

we got coffee way back when. for one reason or another, our schedules never lined up. finally, a couple years later we ended up dialing in a shoot. an adventure, rather. 

we snuck our way into this big historic apartment complex downtown LA. once we reached the top floor, we climbed out the window at the end of the hallway onto the fire escape. the first photo from the set is there. from there, the ladder to the top of the roof was really sketchy. it went up the side of the building about 20 feet, mind you we are 20 stories up. suddenly, something fell from her pocket... a neckless. I could hear it slipping through all the cracks of the metal escape. I asked her if it was valuable. her response, ‚Äúit was silver. my mother gave it to me. it‚Äôs ok though.‚Äù we kept climbing.

Big love to this guy, my dear dear friend Reinaldo Marcus Green for his new film One Love @onelovemovie out in theaters now. I don‚Äôt know how many times I‚Äôve talked about the importance of lighting throughout my career. Too many. Which is it‚Äôs so funny that Rei and I met in Lamps Plus on some random Tuesday (that‚Äôs Rei‚Äôs review on the last slide)

Biopics are notoriously hard films to make, especially when the person depicted is still fresh in our memory. Covering an entire life and weaving it all together is an incredibly difficult task. It‚Äôs arguable that Bob Marley is the most globally recognizable musician in the world. His music is pervasive and I‚Äôve heard it everywhere I‚Äôve traveled, from an international science station in Antarctica to a boat in the Russian Arctic to a tea house in Tibet. Few contemporary artists have such a fingerprint and I believe his message is important now more than ever.

It‚Äôs hard to comprehend the undertaking of Rei, Kingsley Ben-Adir, Lashana Lynch @lashanalynch and everyone else involved in the film. Regardless, under his direction, the roles are transformative and played with incredible skill and care. Well done! Go have some popcorn and let the music you already know be born again.

The curb weight of the Porsche 356, the first Porsche automobile, was 1700 ‚Äì 2,296 lbs. The weight of the Porsche name is much heavier. Ferdinand ‚ÄòFerdi‚Äô Porsche, an architect by trade and the great grandson of the company‚Äôs founder Prof. Ferdinand Porsche, is now adding his fingerprint to the family‚Äôs rich motor-sports legacy.

At 30 yrs old, Ferdi defies all the seriousness and pomp of racing cars. He‚Äôs affable, warm, and almost boyish in his excitement. To put it bluntly, he‚Äôs ‚Äòcool‚Äô without effort, working hard to invite the next generation into the motorsports world.

 On February 24, Ferdi‚Äôs F.A.T. International held its first ice race in Zell am See, Austria, and has followed it up in Aspen, Colorado. Over the past two days on an icy track in Carbondale, the race has included models from the @aetherapparel Half11 (half Porsche, half F1) to the Rivian R1T, to a host of various Mobil 1 cars tearing around corners, over-steering, under-steering, and generally bringing joy as they spit rooster tails of snow from their tires. 

I watch as an enthusiast warm his hands in the exhaust of a loud engine. He brings them to his nose, closes his eyes and inhales deeply, letting his senses coalesce into something whole and visceral. Ferdi sits in his car nearby grinning. It‚Äôs an expression of sincere, palpable joy. As an arm drops, he accelerates onto the track. In a burst of exhaust, something old becomes new again. It‚Äôs a Herculean task and these are enormous shoes to fill, but Ferdi seems to be carrying the weight of legacy effortlessly.

Over the past two days on an icy track in Carbondale, the @fat.icerace has included models from the @aetherapparel Half11 (half Porsche, half F1) to the Rivian R1T, to a host of various @mobil1 cars and drivers tearing around corners, over-steering, under-steering, and generally bringing joy as they spit rooster tails of snow from their tires. 

I watch as an enthusiast warm his hands in the exhaust of a loud engine. He brings them to his nose, closes his eyes and inhales deeply, letting his senses coalesce into something whole and visceral. Ferdi sits in his car nearby grinning. It‚Äôs an expression of sincere, palpable joy. As an arm drops, he accelerates onto the track. In a burst of exhaust, something old becomes new again. It‚Äôs a Herculean task and these are enormous shoes to fill, but Ferdi seems to be carrying the weight of legacy effortlessly.

Time is slippery. 13 years ago today we (barely) managed do the first winter ascent of one of Pakistan‚Äôs 8000 m peaks, Gasherbrum II. So much has changed since‚Ä¶and so much remains the same. One thing that will never change is the love and gratitude I feel for @iamsimonemoro and @urubkodenis for their friendship and mentorship. This climb unquestionably changed the trajectory of everything. More on that in #TheColorOfEverything out July 9th, 2024.

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // In the wide desert of Upper Mustang, the road planes along canyon walls and dry mountainsides dotted with hundreds of unspeakably ancient human-made caves. The light plays a slow game of chase with the shadows cast by the highest mountains on the planet, now behind us. We sweep the corners wide, drawn to cliff-edges teetering above the braided Kali Gandaki River below. We don‚Äôt know where to look ‚Äì the road, the layers of tortured mountains, or the sand-castle parapets of rock and mud towering above us.
 
Instead, we watch the oncoming frame-bent jeeps as they roaring around the blind corners on bald tires. In Tsarang, the drivers share a rough kindness with us. We play snooker, a game we don‚Äôt know. Cory tries and fails to find a tutorial on YouTube. Nursing warm cans of beer, we realize the drivers don‚Äôt know how to play either.
 
The evening passes in one long, impossible game of scratches and flubs until the young man running the hall flicks the light switch and kicks us out into the cold, thin air of a star-streaked night.  @vacheronconstantin

Our hearts remain with the thousands of families that have lost loved ones in the 6.4 magnitude earthquake in West Nepal. As winter approaches, tens of thousands remain without adequate shelter or warmth. If you‚Äôd like to contribute please visit Blinknow.org - these are friends of ours working tirelessly on the ground, and every contribution matters.

We will resume our Mustang travelogue starting today to celebrate all the beauty, resiliency, and magic of Nepal in the faith that if we all work together, brighter days will come soon. // following words by @jetbutterflies Hoping for mountains, we find fog. Climbing towards Sarangkot, the city disappears behind us. Marigolds line the road that falls away into steeped terraces dotted by clusters of roughhewn homes. An hour in, we find the main highway again, paved and twisted into tight curls across the steep hillsides like a pig‚Äôs tail. Todd‚Äôs back wheel blows up, death-wobbling him across the narrow road and directly into a stable of split-open motor scooters under a corrugated tin roof held together with wire.

The mechanic opens the rear tire, and leaves the parts strewn across the shoulder of the highway. A metal-handled hammer and broken screwdriver finish the job: a blown bearing. The mechanic isn‚Äôt much of a talker. He saddles a scooter and buzzes off to somewhere while the town gathers around us, sharing stories and children and a, most proudly, new iPhone 12 ProMax.  They return with two bearings ‚Äì ‚ÄúJapan‚Äù brand. ‚ÄúBest quality‚Äù, he says.
Four hours of riding to go. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

In these crucial first days after the quake, rescue efforts give way to the critical, and complex, process of providing impacted communities with food, warmth, and shelter.  Rebuilding takes time, but helping provide these basic needs can make a tremendous difference in the long run.

@maggiedoyne and @blinknoworg are on the ground at the epicenter and are focusing their efforts on vulnerable groups like pregnant women,  and the most isolated communities that are typically the last to receive aid. 

Supporting their work is the best way you can help from afar. Donations of every size matter.  Nepal has given us both so much, please help us in our efforts to give a tiny bit of that back when it matters the most.

http://www.blinknow.org/earthquake
üì∑ @rushsturges @coryrichards

The thing about earthquakes is that they impact poor and vulnerable communities the most. Those who can‚Äôt afford to reinforce their homes, or who don‚Äôt have a surplus of resources like family, income, or grain to weather months of rebuilding and trauma.

In light of the recent 6.4 magnitude earthquake that struck Western Nepal last night - just miles from Mustang - and our hope to focus public attention on supporting relief efforts, we will postpone our travelogue until next week.

Currently, there are 150+ known deaths from the quake with many hundreds more injured and tens of thousands left without shelter as winter approaches. Please watch this space for updates on how you can help the families in Jajarkot and Rukum recover and build back better.

With love, 
Cory and Ben

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // The highway is a perpetual a fever dream of construction and destruction. Dust, scattered pavement, clawed ridges of clay are punctuated with the idle carcasses of heavy equipment, thin herds of goats, and garish tractors bouncing between knee-deep ruts. When you don‚Äôt have any lanes, you‚Äôre always splitting lanes.
 
Six days ago, Cory did what any responsible motorcyclist would do: he watched a YouTube video titled ‚ÄúHow to Ride a Motorcycle in ONLY 1 HOUR,‚Äù which, it turns out, was only twenty minutes long. 
 
Cory then traced the backstreets of Santa Monica on a tiny caf√© racer for five days before boarding a plane for Kathmandu. Now, eight hours of riding on Nepal‚Äôs worst and busiest highway later, the sun collapses across rice paddies heavy with grain. We still have hours to go.
 
In this perpetual present, when you‚Äôre gripped, you experience the relativity of time. It slows to a game of seconds until, as if by magic, hours have passed.

I‚Äôve known Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies for over a decade. He‚Äôs a Kathmandu staple and has called Nepal home for twenty some years. He came for the mountains and stayed for the people, starting and running non-profits for pieces of the community. At his heart, he‚Äôs an artist and filmmaker. He‚Äôs also a ferocious writer. I‚Äôve been to Mustang with him before on assignment for NG. But this trip is just for us. The following posts are his words.
 
Our other companion is Todd Hoffman. He doesn‚Äôt use Instagram. He‚Äôs one of those leather-faced legends of the eighties who lived hard and fast enough to know when to leave the racetrack. Even if you hardly know him, you want him on your team. At your back. If he looks familiar, it might be from that one time he took Pepsi to task over a Harrier jump jet.
 
The following posts are from our motorcycle trip from Kathmandu to Lo Manthang. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

Farming, in its humble beginnings, was an unrefined art. 

The first farmers, with their rudimentary understanding of agriculture, simply scattered seeds on the ground. This practice, known as broadcasting, prevailed for thousands of years. 

Yet, broadcasting was not without its flaws. The haphazard distribution of seeds led to uneven growth and made the seeds easy pickings for hungry birds. 

In essence, early farming was a game of chance.

Whiskey, a popular distilled alcohol, originates from a fermented grain mash. 

With barley, corn, rye, and wheat as the primary ingredients, it shares a close kinship with beer - distill a beer and voila, you have a basic form of whiskey! 

Around the globe, whiskey takes on many forms, each with stringent regulations defining their production, sale, and marketing. 

Consider Scotch, distilled twice and born in Scotland, or Irish whiskey, hailing from Ireland and typically distilled thrice. 

Then there‚Äôs Bourbon, a uniquely American whiskey, predominantly from Kentucky and Tennessee, mandatorily containing at least 51 percent corn and aged in charred white oak barrels.

The Cold War, a period steeped in tension and rivalry, was not limited to political and military standoffs. 

The board game of chess became a silent battlefield between the United States and the Soviet Union. 

The Soviets, with a near-monopoly on the title of World Chess Champion from 1948 to 2007, were a formidable force. Their secret weapon? An institutionalized training system that nurtured young talent, studied past grandmasters, and drilled opening moves to perfection. 

Chess in the Soviet Union was not a mere pastime, but a sport of national pride.

Americans sure loved their spirits, and that love affair birthed the infamous sin taxes we know today, levied on our beloved alcohol and tobacco. 

Even the great President George Washington was skeptical of this tax, but after touring Virginia and Pennsylvania in 1791, he found local elected officials toasting to the idea of a whiskey tax. With newfound conviction, he returned to Philadelphia, championing the legislation. 

It‚Äôs interesting to note that in those times, a whopping 96 percent of the American population resided east of the Appalachian Mountains, the very folks the whiskey tax targeted. 

Meanwhile, the remaining 4 percent lived west of the Appalachians, in what was then known as the West, where corn was king and distilling whiskey was just part of the subsistence lifestyle. 

And thus, the sin tax saga began.

Swiss pikes, towering spears stretching 10 to 25 feet, were the ultimate equalizers in battle.

True, one-on-one, this weapon falls short, but when assembled in a tight formation, the Swiss pike became a force to reckon with.

The front row kneeling, the second row propping their pikes on their left foot, the third row at waist height, and the fourth at shoulder height. 

Against this formidable formation, even the most expensive armor was rendered useless.

Picasso, a name synonymous with 20th-century art, stands tall in the annals of history.

The Cold War era, known for its nuclear arms race, also saw a less publicized contest between the U.S. and the Soviet Union. 

A race to the depths of the Earth.

In the late 1950s, the U.S. embarked on Project Mohole, an ambitious plan to drill through the Earth‚Äôs crust from a ship off the Mexican coast. 

Despite the drilling reaching a depth of 183 meters, the project failed to hit the mantle. 

On the other side of the world, the Soviets started a similar project in 1970 on the Kola Peninsula, close to Norway. By 1989, they had achieved a staggering depth of 12,262 meters, deeper than Mount Everest is high, and deeper than the Marianas Trench. 

A testament to human ambition, it‚Äôs fascinating to realize there were battles fought not just in space, but also within our very own Earth. 

In the end, it‚Äôs not about who won or lost, but the lengths we go to satiate our curiosity.

The U.S. Constitution doesn‚Äôt explicitly mention a jury of one‚Äôs peers. Instead, the Sixth Amendment grants the right to an impartial jury. 

Yet, the concept of a jury of peers is deeply ingrained in our legal culture. The jury‚Äôs power is virtually limitless, free to reach any conclusion for any reason. 

This leads us to the idea of jury nullification. Not a formal law, but a concept founded on the premise that juries can‚Äôt be penalized for their conclusions. 

In the past, U.S. juries have chosen not to convict in cases where they deemed laws unjust. 

This underlines the importance of the jury process in upholding freedoms within our legal system.

John D. Rockefeller, a titan of the Gilded Age, was the first to amass a nominal net worth exceeding one billion dollars in 1919. 

Adjusting for inflation, Rockefeller‚Äôs fortune would amount to a mere 15 billion dollars today, still securing him a spot among the world‚Äôs richest.

Shakespeare, the name synonymous with English literature, was not always held in such high regard. 

In fact, for a century and a half after his death, he was merely another playwright among many. 

It was only as the 19th century dawned, and his works began to be studied with fervor, that doubts about the real authorship came to light. 

With no existing documents penned by Shakespeare himself, save for six inconsistently spelled and poorly written signatures, the mystery deepens.

Halloween, first referred to by this name in 1775, traces its roots to the ancient Celtic pagan festival of Samhain. 

This festival, celebrated on November 1st, signaled the end of harvest and the onset of winter, and was the highlight of the Celtic calendar. 

As Christianity spread, it absorbed the customs and traditions of Samhain, morphing them into Christian celebrations that coincided with the same period. 

In England, Halloween traditions slowly faded and were replaced by Guy Fawkes Day on November 5th. However, in Scotland and Ireland, Halloween continued to be celebrated with fervor.

The early settlers in the Americas brought these traditions with them, with Anglican and Catholic settlers both observing the holiday, but not the Puritans up in New England - they were generally against everything.

In conclusion, Halloween is deeply rooted in ancient traditions that have evolved and survived the passage of time.

Here is the result of Midnight Flame 7 on a darker starting level. When coloring hair red always consider the base and background contributing color that supports the end result. 
Midnight Flame 7 has a Copper/Red tone and if you apply it on lighter levels with less red underlying pigment you will see more copper. If you apply it on lower levels with more depth then you will see more red since lower levels has more red background. Always understand color theory so it helps you formulate to achieve your end result.

Let‚Äôs make a clarified whiskey sour!

For centuries, milk has been an essential ingredient in many culinary and beverage creations. From creamy soups to decadent desserts, milk has proven to be a versatile and beloved ingredient. However, one particularly interesting use of milk in the culinary world is its role in clarifying cocktails.

The process of clarifying cocktails using milk is not a new concept. In fact, it dates back to the early 19th century when the technique was first documented in Jerry Thomas‚Äô 1862 book ‚ÄúHow to Mix Drinks or The Bon Vivant‚Äôs Companion.‚Äù In this book, Thomas describes a technique called ‚Äúmilk clarifying‚Äù that uses milk to remove impurities and sediment from alcoholic mixtures.

The process itself is quite simple. It involves mixing milk with an acidic component such as lemon juice or vinegar and then combining it with the alcoholic mixture. As the mixture sits, the milk proteins bind with the impurities and sediment, causing them to separate and sink to the bottom. The result is a clear and visually appealing cocktail.

But why use milk in this process? The key lies in its composition. Milk contains casein, a protein that has strong binding properties. When combined with acid, the casein forms clumps that trap impurities and sediment, making it easier to remove them. This technique is similar to how egg whites are used in fining wines, although milk does not alter the flavor of the cocktail like egg whites can.

In conclusion, the history of clarifying cocktails using milk is a rich and time-honored tradition. From its first mention in a 19th-century cocktail book to its recent revival, this technique showcases the creativity and ingenuity of bartenders and mixologists throughout the ages. So the next time you enjoy a clear and pristine cocktail, remember the role that milk played in perfecting its appearance and taste. #milkpunch #clarifiedcocktail #whiskeysour

Multi Blade Razor:

Pros:

1. Convenient & Quick

Cons:

1. Expensive

Safety Razor:

Cons:

Straight Razor:

Pros:

1. Closest Shave

Cons:

2. High Maintenance
3. Expensive

The last five days have been a whirlwind. I had my last day at Circle Round and left a little bit unceremoniously since we had to fly to Arizona the next morning very early. Adam‚Äòs mom had a stroke and he flew here a few days before. My mom and stepdad were in Arizona already for the gem show, and so we got to spend one glorious afternoon and evening with them before they flew back to Connecticut. 
This trip has been quite a bit different than many in the past. We‚Äôve spent a lot of time going to visit Adam‚Äòs mom in the hospital and a lot of time at home cooking and running around after Palomino. There‚Äôs a level of breathtaking that I am finding myself becoming more aware of. 
My personal breath. I realize how much I hold without breathing. And then when I finally sit down, my nervous system feels so frazzled. Adam is doing so amazing, holding space supporting his dad being so calm and loving and kind. It‚Äôs his nature. But it still fills me with gratitude to experience the calmness of his loving heart.  How he shows up in crisis and in calm. 
We have a few more days down here and then we fly home to start the next adventure which includes taking a well deserved break, pivoting @modernmacrame /closing down, dreaming up the next direction of focus for my creative entrepreneurial spirit, and BEING. Being for myself. For Pal. For Adam. For my family. For my community.
I will share more about my departure from Circle Round soon, but for now I‚Äôm focusing on being present, playing with Pal, we took our first bike ride together today!
It‚Äôs a mix of grief and gratitude.
Sending love and peace to all. 
Update, no we are not pregnant. ‚ù§Ô∏è one and done thank you. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Like over 200,000 people in the Portland area these past days, my dad‚Äôs house lost power and being over 70 and not very mobile,  with temps in the teens, he wanted us to come get him. Unfortunately all the roads to his house were closed and he was going to have to stay home for the night.
I awoke in the multiple times filled with worry for him, and for all the people without power or shelter. A fear gripping my heart for him and them. 

His phone has little power left and no way to charge it.

The next day, a generous neighbor was able to pick him up and deliver him to our heat cranked home. And I‚Äôm just so filled with gratitude for what we have. The joy of watching my dad laughing hysterically from the pleasure of getting stoned and eating his first @sarahminnick_ üçï, salad, and ice cream.
The joy of bundling up the child and playing till her lips were blue but knowing we had somewhere warm to rest.

I‚Äôm grateful for our friend Larry for helping my dad get to us.
For family of blood and chosen.

Hoping everyone out there is safe and warm tonight. Sending love and peace to all.

Sending you all love and peace.

A theme lately has been
Rupture & Repair.
I'm learning about this with
my therapist as we heal
some of my childhood
traumas.
How can our nervous
systems know that it's safe
to trust someone if any
time there is a rupture,
there is no repair? That
conflict can be an
opportunity for discussion,
for showing love instead of
fear and hate?

Everyone is dealing with
their feelings about this
war/genocide in different
ways. Like @aleladiane
mentioned in her post I shared. Some mourn
privately, some post and call
to action. Some do those
things without sharing
publicly.
Some people are privately
experiencing depression, or
crisis, or myriad things.
So please show up to love
our sisters here. It's hard
enough being human, but
without compassion, how
can we learn?

And if my actions or perceived lack of
actions have hurt you in
some way,
I'm deeply sorry.
Its overwhelming to be the
owner of two businesses
(one which is closing)
Taking care of a toddler,
Being extremely under
financially resourced,
Experiencing the darkest &
scariest postpartum
depression I imagined, all
the while the world around
us in climate crisis, people
are experiencing
unbelievable suffering.
It's too much.

I've been going non stop.
Now, I'm actually sick in
bed with COVID, and have
a moment to catch my
breath. (Though I have
shortness of breath)
Thank you to everyone who
is out there being the voice
of resistance.
I'm doing my best. And if
you don't think that's
enough, then I'm sorry.
But if you have a problem,
please, how do we heal
without connection?
There is no healing through
violence.
There is no healing through
giving someone the cold
shoulder.
There is no healing through
avoidance.
We heal through our
suffering being welcomed
in, shared, and not by being
pushed out.

Sending love to all

All who are suffering 
All who experience pain in their own ways. 

And to 
All who are celebrating 
(Because we need to also hold dear the beauty right in front of us) our health, the faces of those we love, our friends and community, our children.

I pulled a card for my 41st year. Welp! Guess I need to get clear. ‚ù§Ô∏èüåπ‚ù§Ô∏è
From @biddytarot :
The king of wands

The King of Wands represents pure fire energy in its masculine form. Unlike the other Wands court cards, the King is not so interested in creation and creativity, or in dreaming up ideas and implementing them himself. Instead, he is more inclined to take an idea and then enlist others to help him actualise it. Thus, when the King of Wands appears in a Tarot reading, it is a sign you are stepping into the role of a visionary leader, ready to direct your people towards a common goal. You have a clear vision of where you want to go, and now you are manifesting that vision with the support of those around you. Others naturally gravitate towards you because you are charismatic, focused, and determined, and they believe in you and your vision. They want to be a part of what you are manifesting and are here to support you one hundred percent of the way. You are also masterful at getting other people to do your work for you while keeping them on-side throughout the process.
The King of Wands reminds you to lead your life with intent, vision and a long-term view. You have a grand idea of what is truly possible, and you will stop at nothing to see it through. You achieve a lot because you are clear about your future direction and how you will get there ‚Äì and do not waste your time on activities or relationships you believe will lead nowhere. You never just go with the flow; instead, you prefer to embark on a direct and robust course of action. And you are inspired by long-term, sustainable success, wanting to have a lasting impact. You are here to leave a legacy.
The appearance of the King of Wands also suggests that an opportunity is presenting itself to you, and you now have the power to take on the challenge. You are the determining factor in this situation. If you want it to be successful, it will. And equally, if you do not fully commit to it, this seed will struggle to blossom and grow. You can create any outcome you wish, so be mindful about your intentions and vision. You hold the power.

How often do you stop to measure your successes? I find it is usually easier to remember the difficult times, but in this moment, I would like to honor all that we have accomplished.

In the past 10 years since starting Modern Macram√©, I have traveled the world teaching plant and wall-hanging workshops. I always dreamed of traveling for work, and I was lucky to be welcomed to teach in Mexico City, Barcelona, Copenhagen, Kyoto, Berlin, London, Amsterdam, and many more places. I visited our rope supplier in Turkey. 

In 2018 wrote a book about macram√© that finally paid out the advance this week! Woot! (a new book idea is brewing!)
 

I toured the USA in a mini van with my friend Caitlin teaching over 50 workshops from coast to coast over 3 months to celebrate that book.

I worked with amazing women in the studio and across the world, my teammates and my students who taught me so much about how to lead, how to be kind, how to ask for what you need, and how to be human. I am still learning. You know who you are.

We as a company sold over $3 million worth of rope, classes, and other craft supplies.
 
Our work helped launch the careers of small craft business owners around the globe. - continued in slides and comments

Goodbye my sweet friend. I‚Äôll miss you forever. 10 years wasn‚Äôt long enough. 
There are 100‚Äôs of photos and videos of Donut Underfoot PorterKatz from the past 10 years, it‚Äôs impossible to pick 10. There will be more to share for sure.

The story of Donut:
After about a year of living together one day Adam said what do you think about getting a dog. I thought hey how about we foster one instead. We have such busy lifestyles and maybe we should see if bringing a dog into our lives will be a good fit. That was on a Friday. On Monday this little scruffy sickly fearful creature showed up to our house,  he had eaten an entire plastic bowl and wouldn‚Äôt eat in front of us for months. After just a few days we decided there was no way we could give him back and we just we named him Donut after the tiny donut shaped ball he curled up into. Circa 2013?

Donut was our eternal adventure buddy. He came everywhere with us. He came to work every single day to the Macram√© studio and Adam‚Äôs screen printing space. He climbed ladders. He rode in backpacks. He hiked mountains. He‚Äôs snuggled under blankets and sleeping bags in tents and in the back of our Ford truck. He was a protector. All that he wanted was love. And we gave him as much as we could.

This week the USDA announced that there are fewer farms in the U.S. than at any time since 1850, and 40% of them are owned by people over age 65.  In most industrialized countries, farmers are less than 2% of the population and shrinking.  Here, Doug Hellinger is driving a weed sprayer past the homestead that his grandmother established near Shelby, Montana, shortly after 1909, when the Homestead Act gave 320 acres for free if you farmed the land for five years.  At that time, there were 72 families per 36 sq miles, and today, just 8 people remain, including Doug.

Always good to have friends in high places.  I had the easy job on this helicopter shoot for @nytmag a few years ago, with @jimmychin hanging over the rail while photographing a maintenance worker climbing up the antenna of One World Trade. Jimmy and his amazing wife @chaivasarhelyi have gone on to scale the heights of Hollywood, but when I ran into Jimmy last week he sheepishly declared ‚ÄúI‚Äôm still just a dirtbag climber.‚Äù Aren‚Äôt we all?

Looking for covers for my next book today, and I came across this forgotten image from the soybean harvest in Brazil two years ago.  Soybean production in Brazil is almost ten times what it was in 1985, and those numbers continue to rise to meet China‚Äôs growing demand for pig food. Much of that new production is from land that was once forest.

Volcanic crater of Wau al Namus (hole of mosquitos) in Arabic. 
This massive volcano can easily be seen in satellite views of Southern Libya, as a large black smear in the wind-scoured sands of the Sahara.  The inner crater is bordered by a chain of small salt lakes which are sumps for underground springs). Outside the rim are small black dunes of windblown volcanic ejecta.  It was difficult getting there with my motorized paraglider during the time of Gadaffi, but would be even more complicated today. Carpe diem!
So nice to see my photo above the fold on front page of today‚Äôs @NYTimes!  To see more and read the story on-line, go to link in bio.

Herding over 600 sheep down from the remote high pasture of the Aletsch Glacier Valley in Switzerland.  So happy to see this story about the effects of climate change in the Alps in today‚Äôs @nytimes

Herding 145,000 sheep and goats onto a livestock carrier in the port of Berbera, Somaliland last July for shipment to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, where 2.6 million animals were ritually sacrificed on the third day of the Hajj pilgrimage.  According to today‚Äôs @NYTimes, Somaliland has just granted military use of this sleepy deepwater port to landlocked Ethiopia, allowing access to the busy shipping lanes of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden.  No monetary terms were disclosed, but the deal makes Ethiopia the first nation to recognize the sovereignty of Somaliland, a self-declared democratic republic in one of the world‚Äôs poorest regions.  Last year, live animal exports were 85% of Somaliland‚Äôs export earnings and 30% of its GDP, but that may be about to change.

Pope Francis embraces a disabled person during a general audience in St. Peter‚Äôs Square, Vatican City. This picture is from the cover story on the tremendously popular pontiff in National Geographic magazine (@natgeo ) next month, the August 2015 issue. @natgeo is also publishing a book from the assignment, with much more photography, to be released August 4, and is available for preorder on Amazon. @thephotosociety @natgeocreative

My @Natgeo magazine cover story on Pope Francis and the Vatican is out! I spent a lot of time over the course of six months working on this project, with unprecedented access given to a photojournalist. On August 4 a beautiful photography book on this work on the Vatican, with great writing by Robert Draper, will be published by National Geographic, called 'Pope Francis and the New Vatican,‚Äô available for preorder and easy to find on Amazon right now. I‚Äôll be posting a few outtakes in the coming days. And stay tuned, in October @Natgeo magazine publish a story I shot in unexplored jungle in Honduras where I went with a team to visit a lost city once inhabited by an ancient civilisation that were neighbours to the Maya. It‚Äôs been an interesting, lately!  Edited to add: I took this picture on Christmas Day when Pope Francis made an unexpected visit to the Sistine Chapel after speaking to the people in St. Peter's Square from the balcony of the basilica. It was a wonderful Christmas present, to say the least.

A member of the Swiss Guard paces at his post near the foot of Scala Regia, the royal staircase that connects the Apostolic Palace to St. Peter‚Äôs Basilica in Vatican City. Once a formidable mercenary force dating back 500 years, the title Swiss Guard now usually refers to the Pontifical Swiss Guard, a small force of just over 100 Swiss Catholics who serve as bodyguards to the Pope. Despite their outwardly appearance of a ceremonial role, they are a serious and well-trained combat force, equipped with modern weaponry such as submachine guns. This is an outtake from my August @natgeo magazine cover story on Pope Francis and the Vatican. A National Geographic book from the assignment will also be published on August 4. #swissguard #vatican #thephotosociety

Before and after the audiences, held on Wednesdays in St. Peter‚Äôs Square, he spends considerable time meeting people who are sick, about to get married, or who just really want to meet him.

The largest-ever astronomical project, ALMA, is a cooperation between the three continents--North America, Europe, and East Asia--to build and network 66 radio antennas at 16,500 feet altitude in the Atacama Desert in Chile. The radio telescope array is searching the heavens for clues about the origins of the Universe and many other mysteries. This picture was shot on assignment for National Geographic Magazine, for a story that will be running in the April issue. #atacama #chile #ALMA @thephotosociety

Big announcement! We're so excited to finally share the cover of our new book Green Kitchen: Quick + Slow.
‚Ä¶
This book captures the two different cooking situations we often find ourselves in throughout a week.
We‚Äôve got recipes for the little moments ‚Äì The QUICK. The easy before-work-breakfasts, the simple but special lunch you make for yourself (Lunch-Therapy! ‚ò∫Ô∏è), the weekday dinner when you don‚Äôt want to spend the whole day in the kitchen but still want to eat something delicious. An easy soba and tofu salad, a blitz-roasted tomato and harissa pasta served over yogurt, or a speedy lentil and feta bake. Quick, hands-off, low effort ‚Äì big flavor!
But we also cover the special moments ‚Äì The SLOW. When cooking becomes the best part of the day. When you put on your favorite music and focus on making homemade kimchi burgers, mandolin fennel thinly for a crunchy slaw, cook a 4 hour vegetable ragu, pick up that special cheese, or place potatoes in salt brine on Sunday because you want to serve fermented fries the next week. Food you cook when you have friends coming over or when you just want an excuse to have a joyful moment. 
We hope it can be a reminder to balance the quick and slow in the kitchen. And in life. A cookbook, but also a conversation about how food can be our best therapy, friend and the ultimate joy.
‚Ä¶
The book will be out in June and is available to PREORDER via the link in my bio now!!
It‚Äôs always nerve wrecking to write a book and we so hope that you are going to like it. If you want to preorder and spread the message, Luise and I would be immensely grateful.
I can't wait to share more with you, sneak peeks coming soon!...
‚ù§Ô∏è

Big thanks to @sophiesuppers who has been working with us on recipe development. Our publisher @kj_mistry at @hardiegrantuk. @studiopolkadesign for the cover design. And our tester @the_traveling_noodles. Love to you all!

This is my ultimate fridge-clean out-dish. In Sweden we call this ‚ÄúPytt-i-panna‚Äù and it is essentially fried fridge leftovers (sad vegetables) served with sweet pickled beetroot.
Here are three tips to make a great pytt:
1. You can literally use any veg for this. Start with the ones that need longer cooking time (potato and roots) and add broccoli etc as you go. 
2. Protein upgrade it with tempeh, black lentils or halloumi.
3. Think of it as a Scandi Bibimbap and top with a fried egg and some hot sauce. Crack the yolk and give it a good stir so that the yolk dresses the veg. It‚Äôs the üí£

Let‚Äôs make Breakfast Cake a thing! 
We have been making Baked Oatmeal for more than a decade and a couple of years ago I started transforming that recipe into a cake. Key is to get the crust on the sides while still keeping that creamy oatmeal consistency in the center. And I always top with crunchy and sweet nuts and seeds on top. I really nailed it this morning so I thought I‚Äôd share the recipe:
‚Ä¶
Raspberry Breakfast Cake
‚Ä¶
2 eggs
500 ml / 2 cups oat milk
1 carrot, peeled and grated
1 tsp ground cinnamon
1 tsp salt
1/2 tsp ground cardamom
1/2 tsp ground ginger
500 ml / 2 cups rolled oats
125 ml / 1/2 cup almond flour
3 tbsp buckwheat flour
1 tsp baking powder
200 g frozen raspberries
5 tbsp butter
5 tbsp honey
1 cup mixed seeds and nuts
‚Ä¶
Whisk the eggs in a mixing bowl. Add the milk, grated carrot and spices and whisk until combined. 
Add the oats, almond flour, buckwheat flour and baking powder and stir. Let sit for 10 minutes while setting the oven to 180C / 360F and lining a 20 cm / 8 inch baking tin with baking paper.
Add 1/3 of the raspberries to the bottom of the pan and stir in 1/3 of them into the oat batter.
Melt butter and honey and pour half of it into the oat batter. Pour the oats into the cake tin.
Add the nuts and seeds to the remaining melted honey butter and stir around until everything is coated. Spread the nuts and seeds on top of the oats and finish with the remaining raspberries. Bake in the oven for approx 35 minutes.
Serve in bowls with warm foamy oat milk. Enjoy!

If you need a recipe for an epic Tofu Cashew Masala, I‚Äôve got you. üß°
We first featured this recipe in Little Green Kitchen (swipe for cute kid) and since then we have cooked and tweaked it so so many times. Most recently this weekend when my mom came for dinner. This a great autumn meal and easy with the kids too. The original recipe only features chunks of tofu in the sauce but here we also added cauliflower and chickpeas.
This is the recipe üëáüèª
‚Ä¶
1. Start by letting 100 g (2/3 cup) cashew nuts soak in water.
2. Add 2 tbsp coconut oil to a large thick bottomed sauce pan on low/medium heat. Then add 1 chopped onion, 2 coarsely chopped garlic cloves, 1 finely chopped carrot, 1 big chunk fresh grated ginger, 1 tsp ground paprika, 1 tsp ground turmeric, 1 tsp ground cardamom, 1 tsp salt, ¬Ω tsp ground cumin and 1/2 tsp garam masala. Let saut√© for 15 minutes until soft. 
3. Add 1 can of crushed tomatoes and let simmer for 15 more minutes. 
4. Take it off the heat and stir in the soaked cashew nuts and 250 ml water (you can also use cream or coconut cream) and use a hand mixer or heatproof blender to mix into a smooth sauce. 
5. Chop 1 small cauliflower into florets and dice 400 g / 14 oz tofu, dry with paper towels and add to the masala sauce along with 1 can of chickpeas. 
6. Let cook for 20 minutes. If you want an extra round flavor, stir in a big chunk of butter towards the end. Taste and season to your preference. Serve with cooked rice, lemon kale salad, a dollop of yogurt and toasted cashews. Enjoy!

You can make homemade Bounty dupes with just five ingredients and zero cooking skills! A super easy weekend treat. Here is the recipe:
‚Ä¶
3 tbsp coconut oil
2 tbsp coconut cream or cream
3 tbsp maple syrup
200 g / 2 cups desiccated coconut
200 g dark chocolate
‚Ä¶
1. Add coconut oil + coconut cream or ordinary cream to a sauce pan along with maple syrup and a pinch of salt.
2. Let melt over medium low heat, then add the desiccated coconut. Stir together until warm and sticky.  Taste and add more sweetness if you think it‚Äôs needed.
3. Press the coconut mixture into a tray covered with baking paper and place in the freezer for 1 hour.
4. Melt the chocolate over a water bath.
5. Cut the coconut into bars and dip each bar in the chocolate. Place on a mesh rack and sprinkle with some extra coconut.
6. Store in the fridge or freezer.

Vast and ever-shifting, the sea has always been emblematic of life‚Äôs dualities: beautiful but treacherous, clear yet vague, the beginnings and inevitable endings. ‚ÄúAll at Sea‚Äù is a project focussing on the expansive and unpredictable nature of the ocean and linking it with our own human emotions. It is a somewhat melancholic nod to my Father, a sailor who died in 2010, and is an ongoing conversation with myself, exploring concepts such as memory, relationship, time, place and the strange waves of conflicting emotions that have arisen since he passed. 

@finn - 2024

I‚Äôm not a trained architect, but having helped design and build our house (above), which won 5 RIBA awards this year and the Gold Medal for Architecture, I hope to bring a different but valuable perspective to the panel! Looking forward to the site visits, which begin in the spring.

New year, new personal project.

My son and I recently discussed The Soul Hypothesis - the belief that souls exist and that humans have them. This immaterial part of a human being, often regarded as immortal, is impossible to prove or disprove, but a good portrait is universally thought capable of immortalising or carrying the soul, so he set me the challenge. I hand-painted a canvas backdrop over the holidays with the intention of making a series of new portraits this year. I am limited to simple setups that lean on purposeful, elegant posing ‚Äì something of a test, as much of my photography falls into the environmental category. My backdrop can travel to locations, but its physical constraints will force me to work with just the person themselves‚Äîmy only aid: light and an ability to relate.¬†¬†

So here we go, some slides from my first session yesterday. Thank you, @hayward151, for assisting, and @cloudmaker_and_the_wolf, for bringing your boys and the whirlwind surrounding them to my backdrop. The last slide shows these wee legends turning the tables on their photographer - I love it.

Genie, also known as the shark lady that spent her life studying shark behavior as a Professor at the University of Maryland and @motemarinelab . I want to share good news on World Oceans Day: our current @natgeo story RESHARK -A WILD PLAN to put zebra sharks from aquariums back into the sea appears in the July issue. In this frame Marine scientist @neshaichida gently swims a juvenile zebra shark through its nursery sea pen habitat  at  @rarcc (Raja Ampat Research Conservation Center) located at @papuadivingresorts on Kri island in Indonesia. A team of biologists affectionately known as shark Nannie‚Äôs will conduct a final health assessment before the shark is transported for release into Wayag Islands a patrolled Marine Protected Area where historic populations of zebra sharks were fished out. This global collaboration of  70+ stakeholders from 15 countries (and growing)  is the first of kind to Rewild sharks from 44 participating aquariums. And the best news: This is just the beginning - @reshark_org does not stop at Zebra Sharks. #WorldOceanDay #Sharks #babyshark #Reshark #moreocean with @jenniferhayesig and @daviddoubilet

Exclusive #EarthDay video: Photographers David Wilson and Mike Theiss from Sundiver Snorkel Tours went on a mission to document marine life at the reefs after weeks of quarantined conditions due to the Covid-19 virus. Some of the coral reefs offshore of #KeyLargo haven‚Äôt experienced boat traffic nor human visitors for many weeks. Will this help our chances of documenting the elusive spotted eagle ray ? We used drones to monitor the area and within minutes discovered a large group of several dozen spotted eagle rays, also known as a ‚Äúfever‚Äù. We were able to track the eagle rays with drones and quickly deployed into the water and snorkeled right up next to the them. They were beautiful and looked like birds flying under the water. Mission accomplished!

Wow, hard to believe this, but I started this Instagram account 10 years ago today. It all started when I wanted to share some woodworking projects online and found some like minded peeps. 

And I don't know when this Pic was from, but I was pretty stoked about 50 followers! üòÇüòÇ

2.5 years later I went full time content. Running my own content business has been the hardest and most rewarding job I've ever had. 

It's changed the trajectory of not only my life, but my family's lives too. Working side by side with my wife (Susan) from our house has strengthened our relationship (through struggle üòÇ) and give me so much more time with our kids.

And if you're reading this you've likely been along for the ride. Maybe as a passerby over the years or a hardcore supporter who's been around for years and loved hanging out on the Lives. Either way, thank you. Without people on the other end watching and enjoying our content the business doesn't exist.

It's been a heck of a 10 year journey, and in some ways I feel like we're still just getting started. And we can't wait to continue the ride with you guys/gals. 

Here's to another 10! 
Brad & Susan

I‚Äôve been putting in a lot of work on the shop renovation and we‚Äôve got a lot of material to move around including framing lumber, OSB, and a ton of bagged insulation. It‚Äôs not light work, but I enjoy the hard work and just putting my head down and going. @timberlandpro sent me their Morphix 5-Pocket Athletic pants and Morphix 6‚Äù Outdoor Boot to check out and I‚Äôve been wearing them on the job.

The Morphix line is lightweight and flexible which I LOVE in workwear. I‚Äôm not a fan of the big stiff canvas type work pants. The pants have some clever features like a tape measure guard, doubled up cuffs so your boots don‚Äôt tear them up, and an extra little loop for your EDC to hang from.

And the boots are also flexible and lightweight with composite safety toes and waterproofing. They‚Äôre comfortable too which I assume comes from their Hover Spring midsole. The Ford GT90 Concept Car 

Unveiled in 1995 to celebrate Ford's 90th anniversary and honor the iconic GT40, the Ford GT90 concept car was a bold statement of automotive innovation. It housed a potent quad-turbocharged 6.0-liter V12 engine generating up to 720 horsepower. 

It included advanced features like carbon fiber construction, traction control, and active suspension, the GT90 boasted impressive performance figures, reportedly hitting a top speed of 253 mph (407 km/h) and achieving 0-60 mph in just 3.1 seconds. Despite its acclaim, the GT90 never saw production, serving as a testament to Ford's boundary-pushing engineering and design capabilities.

Rumor has it that only one GT90 Concept Car was ever made, and it currently resides at the Hajek Motorsports Museum in Ames, Oklahoma.

Packed with plant protein, these sticky miso tofu bowls with peas, edamame and ginger are nourishing, flavoursome and super easy to make. Thanks @deliciouslyella. 

Ingredients¬†
2 servings of basmati rice, (about 100g / 3.5 oz) rinsed¬†
1 tablespoon olive oil¬†
Small chunk of ginger, (about 20g / 0.7 oz) cut into matchsticks/grated¬†
2 large cloves garlic, thinly sliced¬†
1 tablespoon tamari¬†
100g / ¬æ cup / 3.5 oz frozen peas, defrosted¬†
100g / ¬æ cup / 3.5 oz frozen edamame beans, defrosted¬†
Pinch of sea salt 

For the sticky tofu¬†
1 tablespoon olive oil¬†
1 block firm smoked tofu, (about 280g / 10 oz) drained & cut into bite-sized pieces¬†
1 tablespoon tamari¬†
2 tablespoons maple syrup¬†
2 tablespoons brown rice miso paste¬†
2 tablespoons rice wine vinegar 

Method¬† 

Pour the rice into a small saucepan, along with 200ml / 7 fl oz water and a large pinch of salt. Bring to the boil, then cover with a lid, reduce the heat to low and simmer for 10 minutes until all of the water has been absorbed. Remove from the heat and set aside.¬†
¬†
While the rice is cooking, warm 1 tablespoon of oil in a large frying pan set over medium‚Äìhigh heat. Add the tofu and cook for 10 minutes, stirring often, until crisp and golden on all sides.¬†
¬†
Next, whisk together 1 tablespoon tamari, the maple syrup, miso paste and rice wine vinegar. Once the tofu is cooked, pour the sauce into the pan and let it reduce to create a sticky sauce that coats the tofu. Remove the tofu from the pan and set aside on a plate.¬†
¬†
Pour 1 tablespoon of olive oil into the same pan, followed by the cooked rice, ginger and garlic. Fry for 5 minutes, until crisp, then stir in the tamari, peas, edamame beans and crispy tofu. Divide between 2 bowls and serve with your favourite crispy chilli oil/sauce.

Dial the chilli up or down to taste, or simply add it at the end if you‚Äôre making this for little ones (once you‚Äôve served them) 

For the nourishing veggie broth with orecchiette, you‚Äôll need 
- 2 tablespoons olive oil
- 1 large onion, thinly sliced
- 2 carrots, halved lengthways & cut into 1cm half moons
- 2 sticks of celery, finely chopped
- 4 cloves garlic, crushed/finely chopped
- 2 bay leaves
- small handful of thyme sprigs
- 1 tablespoon tomato pur√©e
- 1 tablespoon brown rice miso paste
- 1 x 400g tin chopped tomatoes
- 1 x 400g tin chickpeas, drained
- 1¬º litre vegetable stock
- 3 servings of orecchiette (about 225g)
- large handful of basil
- pinch of dried red chilli flakes
- pinch of sea salt

1. Warm the olive oil in a large deep saucepan or casserole dish set over medium heat. Add the onion, carrots, celery, garlic, a pinch of salt and cook for 5 minutes until slightly softened.

2. Stir in the bay leaves, thyme leaves, tomato pur√©e and miso; cook for 2‚Äì3 minutes until fragrant. 

3. Next, pour in the tinned tomatoes, chickpeas and stock. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer for 10‚Äì15 minutes until the vegetables are tender. 

4. Remove the pan from the heat and use a hand blender to roughly blitz half of the soup to thicken it slightly (if you like), then return to the heat, add the pasta and cook for 8‚Äì10 minutes until al dente. 

5. Divide between bowls and scatter over the basil, chilli flakes (if using) and a drizzle of olive oil
