Christopher Anderson naturally began photographing his family after his son Atlas came into the world in 2008. When his daughter Pia was born, he continued the fatherly attempt to stop time and not let a single moment of this new life slip away. Marion features throughout these albums, as a woman, mother, and partner. As a documentary photographer, Christopher Anderson had never considered these personal photos as a ‚Äòseries‚Äô, but his opinion changed when war photographer Tim Hetherington pointed out that ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre all about the passage of time.‚Äù Christopher Anderson began seeing his family pictures in a new light and realised that they may well be his best work. Pia, Son and Marion were published as three separate books, forming a unique and moving intimate family trilogy.

Spinach and ricotta shells üòã

This recipe is one of my favourite pasta dishes, so easy to make and a great one for entertaining too ü§åüèº

Ingredients:‚Ä®- 250g ricotta‚Ä®- 3 tbsp lemon juice‚Ä®- 100g chopped spinach‚Ä®- 1 tbsp minced garlic‚Ä®- 1 tsp salt‚Ä®- cracked pepper, to taste‚Ä®- 700g passata‚Ä®- handful of fresh basil leaves‚Ä®- 12 pasta shells‚Ä®- sprinkle of parmesan‚Ä®- 1 tbsp pine nuts

Method:
1. Preheat the oven to 180¬∞C fan-forced and place a large pot of water to boil over the stove, on high heat.
2. Once water is boiled, add the pasta shells to the pot. Cook as per packet instructions, ensuring not to overcook. Then, drain and rinse with cold water.
3. Add passata, fresh basil leaves, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a 30cm x 20cm baking dish and mix, spreading evenly.
4. Add ricotta, lemon, spinach, garlic, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a bowl and mix well to combine.
5. One-by-one, spoon approx 2 tbsp of the ricotta mixture into each shell and place into the baking dish. Repeat until shells and ricotta mixture are all used up.
6. Sprinkle with parmesan and pine nuts, and place into the oven to bake for 15-20 minutes, or until pine nuts and pasta shells begin to brown.
7. Serve hot & enjoy!

1. Place a large pot over medium - high heat, add oil, once hot, add mushrooms and fry for 2 minutes, strirring occasionally. Add corn and white portion of spring onion. Fry for further 2 minutes.
2. Place another large pot filled with water over high heat, bring water to the boil and cook noodles as per packet instruction.
3. Slice pak choy into quarters and fry over medium heat, until lightly crispy. Set to the side.
4. Crumble the vegetable stock cube into a bowl with the boiling water, add miso paste and stir to dissolve, add to the pot of vegetables, along with the oat milk and soy sauce, bring to the boil and then remove from heat. Stir in sesame oil.
5. Drain noodles and place in the bottom of bowls along with tofu cubes.
6. Ladle the veggie broth across bowls, covering the noodles and tofu.
7. Top with pak choy, remaining spring onion and shredded nori, and if you like some spice, add sriracha sauce or shichimi togarshi seasoning.

In addition to my previous post with photos I just had to share a reel to show you all the details of the most wonderful stay at @cowleymanor which is now my favourite design hotel in the Cotswolds @experimentalgroup [press stay].

#visitcotswolds #hoteldesign #visitengland #iamatraveler #tlpicks

The hotel in the Cotswolds that has it all: incredibly beautiful design, delicious food, a spa with an outdoor and indoor swimming pool, a cocktail bar, a games room and friendly service - let me introduce you to @cowleymanor [press stay]. My first experience of @experimentalgroup hotels and hopefully not the last! We opted for lunch instead of dinner and enjoyed an excellent Sunday roast. Taking inspiration from each chapter of Cowley Manor‚Äôs book, spanning from 1695 until today, designer Doroth√©e Meilichzon has carefully woven together classical inspiration with contemporary elements - from baldaquin beds to bold colour patterns and use of rattan - I loved all the details! Scroll through to see a selection of photos I took, it wasn‚Äôt easy to choose just 10! A reel of our stay coming nextüòä

#visitcotswolds #visitengland #hoteldesign #tlpicks #iamatraveler #cowleymanor

The newest Afternoon Tea to try in London at @thenomadhotel located in the storied Grade II-listed building in the heart of Covent Garden [invite]. I loved the savoury sandwiches with a twist, both sweet and savoury scones and a delicious selection of sweet treats. You can choose to have your tea with a glass of champagne or a cocktail. Would you try it? 

#visitlondon #londonafternoontea #londonfoodies #londonhotels #tlpicks #iamatraveler

#londonrestaurants #londonfoodies #londoneats #tlpicks #iamatraveler

I used a recent opportunity to take some photos inside Westminster Abbey, and while it‚Äôs a very popular tourist destination I managed to get a couple of shots when it wasn‚Äôt too crowded. 
Since 1066, it has been the location of the coronations of 40 English and British monarchs, and at least 16 royal weddings have taken place at the abbey since 1100.

#visitlondon #tlpicks #iamatraveler #prettycitylondon #thisislondon

Starting from today if you‚Äôre visiting Westminster Abbey, you can also explore the story of the French gothic masterpiece, Notre Dame de Paris from its earliest origins in the 12th century and its 850-year history to its restoration following the devastating fire of 2019 in this immersive, interactive exhibition. Open until the 1st June at Capter House @westminsterabbeylondon, the exhibition is included in the Westminster Abbey admission price but you need to book a time slot. 

#visitlondon #prettycitylondon #tlpicks #iamatraveler #thisislondon

New restaurant to try in Borough Yards - @akara.london, named after the popular West African street food dish, Akara offers a variety of crispy savoury fritters made from black eye beans, served with different fillings - we tried BBQ tiger prawn and Braised ox cheek [invite]. Don‚Äôt miss the Rice Pancakes with Black-eyed Bean Hummus and Efik Style Coconut rice. For mains, there‚Äôs a selection of barbecued meat, fish and vegetable plates. Dark Chocolate, Kahluah and Citrus Meringue Dessert was very light and perfect to finish this delicious meal. 

#londonrrstaurants #londoneats #londonfoodies #eatlondon #prettycitylondon #tlpicks #iamatraveler

‚û°Ô∏è Leaping into the future to see what the kitchen will look like later this year ü§∏‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüëÄü•π

I‚Äôm obsessed with these renderings of the space and the way the kitchen design came together from @strucksured üòç

We have made some changes since these were rendered over a year ago, but the general feel of the space remains the same. Warm, cozy, welcoming, and with big bright windows!

If anyone is curious, the changes were:

üìù White cabinets will be a light sage green color instead
üìù Hood vent will be sloped rather than straight
üìù We added some glass fronts to the cabinets on either side of the big window trio
üìù The drawer pulls were swapped for a more old-world-looking pull
üìù We added an arch to the doorway from the kitchen to the hallway

It‚Äôs been SO insane seeing this space take shape, bit by bit, right in front of me after imagining it for so many years. We started the design process for the house back in 2020, and in some ways it feels like it‚Äôs gone by in a flash, and in other ways it feels like it‚Äôs taken forever lol üòÇ

But I‚Äôm incredibly grateful that all the hard work has resulted in a real solid structure taking shape before our eyes!

I can‚Äôt wait to share more about budgeting for design choices in a blog post soon (working on it at the moment, hoping to have it up next week! ü§û) In the meantime, have a wonderful leap day my friend!!!

PS‚ÄîDon‚Äôt let fear keep you from taking a wild, ridiculous leap. With some work + a dash of stubbornness, you never know where it might take you! üòä

I still have a LOT more peonies to dig up (I knowwwww, it‚Äôs already late in the season to do that üò¨), and I‚Äôll be tackling the dahlia tubers next month with a group of amazing friends.

Spring + blueberry season is just around the corner, and there‚Äôs no better way to enjoy it than with a @empress1908gin Blueberry Negroni! ü´ê #sponsor

It has THE perfect balance of herbs and fruit, with a wonderfully pleasant bitter hint that‚Äôs signature of the classic negroni, this is one to bookmark! üôå

Enjoy my friends + #SipResponsibly! ü•É

ü´ê Blueberry Negroni ü´ê
Makes 2 Servings

2 ounces @empress1908gin
2 ounces Luxardo bitter bianco
1 1/2 ounces sweet vermouth
1 ounce blueberry concentrate

Stir together all ingredients in a mixing glass with a few cubes of ice. Strain and pour into 2 chilled rocks glasses filled with ice. Serve immediately.

Blueberry Concentrate

1 cup blueberries, fresh or frozen
1 tablespoon finely grated orange zest
2 tablespoons sugar
1/2 cup water

Bring to a boil over med-high heat. Reduce heat to low and simmer until blueberries release their juices, about 10 minutes. Place a sieve over a small bowl and strain, using a spoon to press the blueberries to get as much liquid as possible. Reserve the liquid and discard the blueberry pulp. Cool to room temperature then refrigerate in an airtight container.

Where we ended up, and how we got there ‚û°Ô∏èüëÄ I‚Äôm breaking down how I use layering to add dimension +  texture in captures, and you can get the full behind-the-scenes emailed to you by commenting LAYER below or via the link in my profile! üíå

And if you‚Äôre wondering what this golden concotion is, it‚Äôs a creamy and ultra-comforting roasted parsnip soup üçúüíõ

Because I‚Äôm obsessed with all things both salty and sweet, I caramelized some leeks and pureed them into the soup with the roasted parsnips, and sprinkled some on top as well for texture.

Leeks have much less moisture than onions, so they caramelize much quicker in the pan. But be careful! That also means it‚Äôs easier to burn them if you‚Äôre not paying attention since they dry out faster. üî•

And for a slight bit of crunch and a wonderfully toasted flavor, there‚Äôs some roasted hazelnuts sprinkled on top. The tired cook might say ‚Äúmeh, I don‚Äôt really need those‚Äù and cut them from the grocery list, but let me insist, that you *do* in fact need them. They are SUCH a good complement to the roasted parsnip soup, and if you get tired of the same texture easily like I do, they add a really nice crunch to an otherwise super smooth soup. And they‚Äôre super easy to make (less than 10 minutes to toast them, I promise!) Live a little and go for it, I say! üôå

Oh hi there! üëãüèª Erica booked highlights with an ash toner and left as a bombshell with cowboy copper! üí• it‚Äôs ok to change your mind, that‚Äôs what makes it fun! ü§© 

Colour was achieved using @guytang_mydentity brand new MidnightFlame7 Demi mixed with NakedGlow7 at the rootage and NakedGlow9 mids and ends then overlaid with Naked8 to ease the flames ever so slightly. üî•

Here is the result of Midnight Flame 7 on a darker starting level. When coloring hair red always consider the base and background contributing color that supports the end result. 
Midnight Flame 7 has a Copper/Red tone and if you apply it on lighter levels with less red underlying pigment you will see more copper. BODY BOOKWORM / SOMATIC SCHOLAR 

During the time I‚Äôve been with my husband my body has seen many changes. Seemingly subtle ones that speak loud as women‚Äôs bodies do in all our many stages. These are changes that a superficial mind conditioned by a skin-deep culture would label as not attractive. I remember my EX-husband being disgusted by my armpit & random nipple hairs which I thought was hilarious, after all women have testosterone helping us produce new blood cells, maintain bone health, libido & boost other reproductive hormones. I‚Äôve been learning more about hormone changes as I approach menopause which is incredibly fascinating & always reiterates to me how wise the body is in adapting throughout its phases. 

The body is a book that reads of its lifetime. Birthmarks, scars, aging marks, wrinkles, tattoos, spots, hair loss, stretch marks, some of us lose limbs or gain ‚Äúextra‚Äù parts along the journey. The book of the body is beautiful in its creativity. It tells a rich story. Looking at a dead body is captivating in a way, being that the soul has left its shell. It‚Äôs like an artifact left behind with stories of the past written on its skin. A tangible object the soul crafted while here on earth. But the beauty of an alive body is that the soul is still inhabited & can continue to write. Creating until its very last day. I want my body to be a museum when my soul leaves it. 

Often my clients are surprised that I know so many intimate details about their inner world without them having to tell me.  They say ‚Äúhow did you know that?‚Äù ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs like you‚Äôre inside me!‚Äù ‚ÄúYou were saying what I was thinking as I was thinking it! How do you know that?‚Äù Well, I‚Äôve read a lot of bodies in my lifetime & it‚Äôs my gift (one could say). I‚Äôm a body bookworm or a somatic scholar. The beauty of the way the body reads is that it doesn‚Äôt lie like the mind does. It‚Äôs vulnerable (even if you think you‚Äôre not). It‚Äôs incapable of lying; just like an aged body cannot look young no matter how hard you or your plastic surgeon try to turn back time. That‚Äôs what I find stunning about aging & my work as a somatic healer. It‚Äôs honest AF & the Scorpio in me doesn‚Äôt do casual or roundabout.

I was asked if I could talk about my positive mindset towards aging: 

The older I get the smaller my ego becomes. As the persona dies I embrace my authentic self/true essence more (what people describe as ‚Äúmore comfortable in your own skin‚Äù).Not placing so much attention on the superficial I have loads of time/mind/energy space to be without the ‚Äúnoise‚Äù. It‚Äôs an ALWAYS VACATION. But most of my comfort is directly linked to my comfort with death. The reason our culture is so afraid of getting old is because they are afraid of death. So we don‚Äôt talk about death, we talk about aging when we should be talking about death. 

There are many reasons why people fear death. Where do we go? What happens? We imagine the worst. There are those (including myself) that have had near death experiences & have crossed the veil which gives us a sneak peek into the other-side BUT unless you know someone that was straight dead & has come back to share the mystery‚Ä¶ The mystery remains & that‚Äôs what freaks people out & fascinates me so. Our brains are wired to reduce uncertainty & death is the epitome of uncertainty which is why life‚Äôs greatest practice is to get comfortable with the uncomfortable which in essence is practicing death. 

But think of it in this way; Look at history & our current world. War. Pain. Struggle. Hurt. Greed. Violence. It‚Äôs all fucked. And we think the other-side is scary?! That makes me LOL! Life isn‚Äôt easy & it‚Äôs purposefully designed that way! The longer you live the more of a chance you get to get comfortable with the uncomfortable, that means embracing aging (death). That is if you understand that‚Äôs what life is for. If you don‚Äôt aging will become the living death you fear & it will become your reality. The more you repress the process the more the fear virus will spread within you. The more you embrace it the more ‚Äúlife‚Äù you get.

CREATIVITY IS THE GREATEST HEALING TOOL

I give a lot of credit to my creativity in terms of my healing abilities in myself & in guiding others. Creativity is the greatest facet to human intelligence & consciousness. There‚Äôs no greater tool than creativity when it comes to EVERYTHING.

Yet I‚Äôve found that when it comes to healing trauma, reconnecting energetically, getting past our emotional wounds, the power of creativity gets overlooked or even laughed at. 

The brain says ‚Äúwhy are we playing around making art when you‚Äôre in pain?‚Äù Well brain to answer your question: because through abstract expression & creative sourcing I discombobulate your narrative & give myself an outlet of energy, thus giving IT a voice instead of you continuously reciting the same ol‚Äô wack narrative that keeps me stuck! 

Creativity is empowering. The fearful brain doesn‚Äôt want you playing around with new ideas. It wants you safe & sound staying in its ‚Äúknown‚Äù state so it doesn‚Äôt have to be left in some weird unknown where it can‚Äôt ‚Äúprotect‚Äù you. But the body wants to express itself freely. Where we tend to get stuck in our healing is that we always go the same route, ending up at the same point. The Worrying Mind

It‚Äôs been quite the 2 weeks as we figure out what‚Äôs going on with Ganchos health. He‚Äôs now stable. Seemingly at peace as we wait for the exam results to understand more of what‚Äôs going on in his little body. Once again, as the universe does so well, she‚Äôs testing me. Luckily I‚Äôve been consistent with my practice of BEING in awareness, feeling the feels, emoting the emotions & flushing the residue of my internal happenings before they grab hold & throw me around. Not this time. Showing up is showing up for me right now.

In the past my worrying mind would‚Äôve hijacked me to the point of immobility. After years of learning how to not fear my pain, or overindulge in it, I‚Äôve found the sweet spot where all my emotions can sit at the table & have a productive cordial conversation without freaking the FUK out. In the past worry would have annihilated everyone else at the table. Now all my feelings/emotions can mingle mindfully with each other to reach a reasonable, respectable & manageable compromise for the good of every emotion that lives in my vessel.

This emotional wisdom did not come easily. I‚Äôve invested a lot of time & effort to get to where I am now in body-mind-spirit. This is crucial work. This is why we are here. To learn. To evolve. To receive the lessons & give back. Gancho is the Angel on the ground dishing out homework from the universe. I appreciate the universe‚Äôs tests and proceed onwards with gratitude for all ‚ù§Ô∏è

MovMEANT.com
Do the work. 
It‚Äôs your important work to do while here on earth.

Feelings are our friends. I know some will roll their eyes & be like ‚Äúyeah right‚Äù. Feelings can feel like the enemy but it‚Äôs only because you‚Äôre taking it personally. Have you ever tried listening & observing the feelings as a witness or vessel instead of the persona of which they are happening to? It won‚Äôt feel like an attack but an important message. Because it is. 

Imagine not having feelings. Btw, repressing feelings isn‚Äôt NOT having feelings. Repressed feelings still live in you, even louder in-fact. I‚Äôd say it‚Äôs the opposite of not having feelings. Repression/suppression amplifies the feelings, it does not rid you of them. By doing so you‚Äôre only building a stronger army inside you. 

There is no person without feelings. Those are called robots. To feel is to be alive. Feelings are essential, vital information you need to communicate with your inner & outer worlds. They help us survive, grow, adapt, connect. When you don‚Äôt allow them to speak you‚Äôre left lost in the world without your emotional GPS. The feelings only scream louder, the emotions move stronger in you. Suppress more & they‚Äôll stop nudging & start fighting. Cage them up for long enough & they‚Äôll start rotting in you. Disease. 

All they wanted was to let you know they had something important to tell you cause they care about you. If you didn‚Äôt agree at least you could have had a conversation with them instead of locking them away. Sitting & talking to your feelings is the most important conversation you‚Äôll ever have. Learn how they speak & you‚Äôll want them around more often. 

Allow me to guide you into your emotional heaven. Dm me for private sessions & more offerings.

LEVEL ONE POSTPARTUM WORKOUT!

üî∫IMPORTANT: you MUST receive clearance from your doctor and if possible a women‚Äôs health physiotherapist, after 6 weeks postpartum before attempting this workout. Once you have that clearance, this can be your potential starting point. Begin basic, slow and easy. Reduce reps and sets as necessary and adjust to your individual level.
üëâ Repeat 2-3 times a week for 2-3 weeks or until level two feels suitable. 

Ensure you can engage and control your core / pelvic floor with all movements. If you‚Äôre struggling with this, try to see a women‚Äôs health physio in person to help you with that proper connection. 

Remember, there‚Äôs no race or competition. Be kind to yourself and don‚Äôt rush yourself or push your body before it‚Äôs ready. üíõ

ü§ù DM me for help with a fully personalised workout plan created for your current level and goals.

It‚Äôs not easy and I won‚Äôt sugar coat it, some days it works and some days it doesn‚Äôt. Some days they give me 8 minutes and some times I get a full 30. 
It was hard work getting myself into this routine but I didn‚Äôt give myself the choice.
I know I want to be active, I know I want my babies to see me being active. 
I know this phase of my life won‚Äôt last forever, and I can either make the most of it to focus on myself too, or I can sit back and watch the months turn into years where I‚Äôm still waiting. 

You can do this too mama. 
You just need to try. ü´∂

#postpartumfitness #postpregnancy #fitnessmotivation #fitness #workout #homeworkout #postpartumjourney #exercisemotivation

Your postpartum journey was not made to be an overnight road trip. It‚Äôs a long haul journey. But mama, you gotta show up for yourself. 
It‚Äôs tough work taking care of little people, and it‚Äôs even tougher work to find the time for YOU. I promise you will again one day. Any few moments in the day you can find to make yourself a priority, take it. 

This is almost 10 months of progress for me. 
That‚Äôs almost an entire year of waking up, trying my best, falling off track, but getting back on it again. 

It‚Äôs not easy, but give your body the same love, patience and care you gave it when it was growing a human. Be kind to yourself. But show up for yourself too üíõ
Hey, welcome üíõ LIKE this if you‚Äôre a fellow mumma trying to be your fittest and most confident self.

Remove your all or nothing mindset. 
The minute you allow yourself to just show up in whatever form you can each day, instead of being perfect, you take a tonne of weight off your shoulders.

He died on remote South Georgia Island and that is where I photographed his grave where sailors visit to pay their respect to the man known as ‚ÄúThe Boss.‚Äù Shackleton‚Äôs Endurance expedition is one of the great exploration epics of all time and it continues to inspire people, including me. Photos by @FransLanting Today is Western Monarch Day. One of the most important overwintering sites for Western Monarch butterflies is just a few minutes from our Studio in Santa Cruz, California, along the coast. The butterflies there survived the extreme storm event we experienced yesterday, but whether they can weather the bigger issues they are confronted with remains a question.

The first image in this post was made this winter. It shows a small cluster of Monarchs in the same place where I made the second image in 1986. You can see the dramatic decline in the overwintering populations. The Western Monarch population has decreased more than 98% from the 1980s due to pesticide use in their summer areas, habitat loss, climate change, and other threats. Yet insects can bounce back quickly when conditions improve and people can help make that happen.

FYI, Western Monarchs spend their summers farther inland and go all the way to the Rocky Mountains. The Eastern Monarch population is much larger and overwinters in Mexico. The @NatGeo story about Monarchs published January 2024 photographed by my friend and colleague, @JaimeRojo, gives a great overview of what Monarchs are faced with. Check the organizations named below to learn more about how you can support Monarchs. And follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more stories from the frontlines of our changing planet.

@xercessociety @monarchbutterflyfund @Thephotosociety #Monarch #endangeredspecies #Butterfly #SantaCruz #MontereyBay #California

Photo by @FransLanting When chinstrap penguins display, they raise themselves to show off their black chinstraps while flapping their flippers and screaming at the top of their lungs. Sometimes this triggers a raucous response from other birds nearby. I was impressed by this male who had found a rocky perch that elevated him above his neighbors. Not sure if he succeeded in attracting any females, but he certainly looked like a performer. 

Things are different for visitors to Antarctica this year because of an outbreak of bird flu which has potentially disastrous consequences for penguins, other birds, and marine mammals. Visitor rules have been tightened up to prevent the spread of this highly contagious disease. Check my stories to see how I adapted my gear to operate within the new guidelines. And follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more stories about our changing planet.

We‚Äôre happy to share that the incredible Frans Lanting will be on the @nature_org 2023 Global Photo Contest judging panel. Hailed as one of the great nature photographers of our time, Lanting‚Äôs influential work appears in numerous publications and exhibitions around the world. For more than three decades he has documented wildlife from the Amazon to Antarctica to promote understanding about the Earth and its natural history through images that convey a passion for nature and a sense of wonder and concern about our living planet.

Lanting has received honors and acclaim for his work. H.R.H. Prince Bernhard inducted him as a Knight in the Royal Order of the Golden Ark, the Netherlands‚Äô highest conservation honor. He has received top honors from World Press Photo, the title of BBC Wildlife Photographer of the Year, and the Sierra Club‚Äôs Ansel Adams Award. He has been inducted as a Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society in London and is a recipient of Sweden‚Äôs Lennart Nilsson Award. Lanting acts as an Ambassador for the World Wildlife Fund Netherlands and sits on the National Council of the World Wildlife Fund USA, as well as on the Leadership Council of Conservation International, and on the International Board of WildAid. He is also a Trustee of the Foundation Board of the University of California Santa Cruz. He is a co-founder of the North American Nature Photographers Association and a Fellow of the International League of Conservation Photographers

Lanting‚Äôs mission is to use photography to help create leverage for conservation efforts ranging from local initiatives to global campaigns, through his publications, alliances, public appearances, and active support of environmental organizations. Along with his wife and partner Christine Eckstrom, Lanting recently launched Bay of Life: From Wind to Whales. This project explores and educates on the importance of California‚Äôs Monterey Bay ecosystem, which The Nature Conservancy identified as the ‚Äúhottest hot spot for biodiversity in North America.‚Äù

Time is running out. Help give voice to nature and enter your best images by September 29th. Follow the link in our bio for more details.

Photo by @FransLanting Our friend Morad Tahbaz flew to freedom earlier today with four other American citizens after the Biden administration negotiated their release from prison in Iran. Morad is a cheetah conservationist with whom I had the pleasure to work while I documented Asia‚Äôs last cheetahs, which survive only in Iran. Morad, along with his colleagues from the Persian Wildlife Heritage Foundation, had been wrongly accused of using their camera traps to spy on military activities in Iran. 

We are grateful for Morad‚Äôs release, and thank everyone who played a role in this. But we also want to draw attention to the plight of his colleagues who remain in jail. Niloufar Bayani, Sepideh Kashani, Amirhossein Khaleghi, Taher Ghadirian, Sam Radjabi, and Houman Jowkar deserve to be freed as well to pave the way for new international cooperation efforts that will benefit big cats and people alike. 

Please spread the word and follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more stories from the frontlines of conservation.

Have you ever looked back at a time in your life where you wished you had just slowed down and enjoyed it a little more? There have been many times that I wish I had been a little less preoccupied with the unnecessary nonsense that seemed to have consumed me and focused more on enjoying the present. I think back to when I was younger, I think of all the BS fad diets I tried, the stress I would put myself through to weigh less or meet some unrealistic standards for my body. I think of the things I kept wanting to change in myself and the comparisons I would make to others. 

But you know what, when I think back to those days, I don‚Äôt remember what I weighed, I don‚Äôt remember when I had visible abs or when I had a little extra padding. I remember creating memories with my family, I remember creating, travelling, meeting incredible people from all around the world and making lifelong friends. I remember all the special things that can so easily escape us on the day-to-day basis but I didn‚Äôt have a single fond memory that was associated with being restrictive or obsessive when it came to body image. 

Funnily enough the moment I decided to stop focusing on purely the aesthetic side of fitness I achieved what I wanted as a by-product of enjoying the process and getting stronger. 

If you want to start training for long term, sustainable results, check out the programs in my bio ‚ù§Ô∏è

3 Reasons your glutes aren‚Äôt going üçë

Building muscle is hard work and takes time. You have to be patient and consistent to see results. Here are some reasons you may not be seeing results and how to overcome them: 

1Ô∏è‚É£ Inadequate Training Volume or Intensity:

Issue: Building muscle requires adequate training stimulus. If you‚Äôre not training with enough intensity (upping your weights and training close to failure for at least your first compound lift) your glutes may not be receiving the necessary stimulation to grow.

Solution: Focus on increasing the intensity of your workouts by increasing the weight you‚Äôre lifting, incorporate progressive overload and include more glute-focused exercises in your routine. 

2Ô∏è‚É£ Inadequate Nutrition or Recovery:

Issue: Not fuelling your body properly and overtraining can hinder your results. 

Solution: Muscles need proper nutrition and recovery to grow. If you‚Äôre not consuming enough calories, particularly protein, your body may lack the essential building blocks for muscle growth. Additionally, inadequate rest and recovery can hinder progress. Make sure you‚Äôre getting enough quality sleep, managing stress and allowing your muscles to recover between workouts.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Not following a structured program 

Issue: Changing your workouts every session isn‚Äôt going to help you build your glutes.It can be tempting to jump on the latest glute building trend or exercise that promises to build your glutes after 1 session but the reality is that building your glutes takes time and requires you to perform the same workouts for at least 4 - 6 weeks, progressively increasing the intensity (progressive overload). 

Solution: Following a program that incorporates progressive overload and has a well structured exercise selection will help you maximise your gains.

In an exclusive with Body+Soul, fitness titan and mother of two Emily Skye (@emilyskyefit) shares about her experience with neurodiversity, hoping to open up the conversation for other women who may be struggling. 

Read her experience at the #linkinbio üîó

Sharing this scares the sh*t outta me, but here goes‚Ä¶üò¨ü´£

I‚Äôve always felt like I‚Äôm ‚Äústrange‚Äù & misunderstood, & have never felt I belong in the world. I‚Äôm super sensitive, think differently, overthink, catastrophize, hyper focus & have multiple thoughts at the same time NON-STOP. Daily tasks at times are impossible for me, & sometimes just stepping out of the house feels terrifying. 

I‚Äôve just been diagnosed with ADHD & RSD (Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria) - which explains why I people-please so much & get so upset when faced with rejection, or even the perception of it - which tends to be my default reaction!

The fear of rejection is paralyzing at times, hindering me from taking action. It‚Äôs likely the reason I place immense pressure on myself to achieve perfection... a goal that is unattainable & often leads to more distress, ultimately resulting in inaction.

Throughout my life, I‚Äôve carried the belief that I am broken, incompetent, & unintelligent, harboring deep self-hatred as a result. üò¢ The burden of guilt & resentment towards myself has been overwhelming.

Living within my own mind for the past 39 years has been undeniably exhausting, at times making me wish I could escape my own thoughts. I‚Äôve long been aware that I don‚Äôt fit the mold of what is considered ‚Äúneurotypical‚Äù & I‚Äôve found relief & validation in officially getting a diagnoses. I can now help myself & show self compassion. üôåüèº

I am so thankful for my family & true friends who accept & love me no matter what. üôèüèº I‚Äôm especially grateful for Dec, who has stood by my side for the past 14 years, despite the challenges of living with me. It still surprises me that he wants to marry me haha! üòÜ

I am also grateful for the decision to start exercising in my 20s, as it is the one consistent factor that helps me tremendously.

ADHD & RSD do NOT define me, nor do they render me broken. I am wonderfully unique, just like every individual in this world. I believe there is no such thing as ‚Äúnormal‚Äù anyway. ü•∞ü´∂üèº

If you feel comfortable sharing, have you received a neurodivergent diagnosis as an adult?

We are not alone. üòò

‚ÄúYou‚Äôre meant to be a fitness professional, but you‚Äôre weak, unfit & pathetic!‚Äú - these are not words from other people, they‚Äôre words from my own head! üò´ Yep, I can be my own worst enemy! üòî Words have great power & we need to be careful what we tell ourselves. 
I‚Äôm actively working on reprogramming the way I talk to myself to be more positive, kinder & more encouraging. I need to believe in myself as I believe it‚Äôs the first & most important step towards achieving success!
This workout absolutely destroyed me. ü•µ But I did it & I‚Äôm proud of myself! üëèüèº
Getting back into my training has been a struggle. I‚Äôm lacking motivation & consistency feels like a distant dream. I‚Äôve been beating myself up over the strength & fitness I‚Äôve lost. Rehabbing injuries for several months has left me feeling discouraged, & it‚Äôs hard not to compare myself to who I used to be.

Fitness professionals like me are not immune to struggles. We may know WHAT to do, but we still have to put in the work for results. The mental game is the toughest part, especially when starting over feels like a never-ending cycle. Life throws curveballs that make it hard to stick with something long-term. But I‚Äôm determined to reclaim my fitness, strength, & get back to feeling incredible again.

Negative self-talk doesn‚Äôt do us any good. Deep down, we know this, but we need reminders. We have to consciously choose to focus on the positive, even when it feels like an uphill battle. It‚Äôs not easy, but it‚Äôs necessary.

Remember; If it were easy, everyone would be doing it. The path to fitness is tough, but it‚Äôs worth every bit of effort. So I‚Äôm taking charge, setting realistic goals, & celebrating every small victory along the way. Consistency is my anchor, & I‚Äôm committed to showing up for myself every single day.

It does get easier, I know this because I‚Äôve done it many times before. Each day I put in the effort, I know I‚Äôll get stronger & fitter. Progress may be slow, but it‚Äôs progress nonetheless. 
Let‚Äôs embrace the struggle, be proud of our efforts, & keep pushing forward. We have the power to transform our lives, & it‚Äôs time to unleash that power. üëäüèº

In today's Note, I explain why I am brow insecure, and how I am trying to fix it! 

Find it at the link in bio!!!

Recently I stayed at a hotel in London designed by Kit Kemp and I found myself loving the feeling of it without liking all of the elements of the decor, and I liked that I didn't like it all because it challenged my sense of taste.

It was an interesting experience about something that's been ringing a bell inside of me for a while-the fact that I could easily settle into a comfortable "pleasing" sense of taste, specifically for interiors. 

I think it's the Pinterest effect, probably a lack of confidence but also the fact that everywhere, homes feel less and less personal and more and more like they're coming out of a catalog and a specific "vibe," such as the "neutral countryside style" or the "LA mid century" or the more recent round shapes and soft colors. 

So now I am trying to build my confidence, because without confidence all we can do is... Sort of become generic. 

I also try to push myself to make "mistakes" and just go with my gut, which is really hard as I HATE being caught in a moment of bad taste üòÇüòÇüòÇ

Anyway here are a few images of what challenges me, and that I therefore should explore...

1/ the mix of prints. I actually love bold prints on sofas but I've always been too scared of regretting them to go ahead.

2/ photos and paintings in the kitchen. I'd love to see that more often!

3/ absolute mix of everything. So personal I love it. The computer shows it's an old image. I think homes in the 90s where quite good at capturing this sense of freedom...

4/ super bold and awesome matchy-matchy moment.

5/ joyfully not aligned plates on the wall.

It's so fun to discover another world, right at your doorstep. Yesterday on our way back from Devon we stopped in Broadhembury for a meal at the Drewe Arms and felt like we had stepped back in time. 

There really a bit of magic in these untouched English landscapes, and true joy in finding oneself in these uncomplicated interiors that look like everything we try to reproduce today. 

And there is also something wonderful about the old pubs, the locals sharing a beer at the bar with their friends (it was packed that day, I just took photos at the rare moments when the tables emptied) their dogs, their muddy boots and the warmth of it all... 

I discovered the Sunday Roast tradition when I moved to England and it's one of my favourite things. For the food, but also for the vibe. I completely forgot to take a photo of the meal because it was so good, but you can see in one of the photos that Lulu was certainly on it!
Really the most important thing when it comes to beauty. Let me know if I was unclear (highly possible! I have the hardest time being concise) and if you have any questions!

The first time I went to Bath, it was just a short visit but I remember vividly saying to Graham that I could see myself live there. He had agreed. A few years later (I tell all that story in my newsletter in the link in bio!) completely by accident, I found and fell in love with a house which turned out to be in the countryside of... Bath. 

So here I am sharing with you my favourite places as a new local. Bath is a bit over an hour train from London, super easy but If you ever visit, take some time to drive around Somerset as well, it's just gorgeous!

It's a very walkable city with a lot of fabulous views, and mentionned in my reel are... 

Locations-

The Royal Crescent and The Circus and a few of the world famous locations that you'll find just by walking around. 

Food

@landraceupstairs , a gorgeous restaurant just above a gorgeous bakery. @beckfordcanteen and @beckfordbottleshop , delicious and welcoming. And our coffee absolute favourite, @colonnacoffee (their cakes and pastries are delicious)

Stores 

@berdoulat_interior_design is a must see, interior decoration in one of the most beautiful settings (it's original too!) I've ever seen. @8hollandstreet is where all my furniture dreams are and we've already talked about the magic of @devolkitchens ! I also love Bartlett Antique Center and still can't believe such beautiful antiques are so affordable. 

A special mention to @toppingsbath , a bookstore I really fell in love with and could spend hours in. There is a very special vibe there, I always leave with a ton of books!

@persephonebooks for r√©√©ditons of books written by women and @magalleriabath for the coolest magazines on the planet, a very passionate project!

In this immersive five-day workshop in Santa Fe with Ed Kashi, the primary emphasis is guiding participants in creating and finalizing a personal project. Students also have the opportunity to complete individual assignments on-location and practice their skills related to research, scouting, shooting within a deadline, and delivering a final product. These projects serve as the cornerstone defining our identity as visual storytellers and artists. Echoing Ed‚Äôs approach, the ultimate goal is to identify subjects that ignite a profound passion and document them using a unique and impactful visual style. 

Drawing from his extensive repertoire, Ed showcases his varied personal projects, collaborations with NGOs and Foundations, and editorial contributions to acclaimed publications such as National Geographic, Time, and The New Yorker. 

Together, we examine diverse visual formats like photographs, multimedia, and short films, exploring the vibrant array of creative possibilities. Engage in an intimate and safe environment to present your work, exploring innovative methods of visual storytelling using available mediums like photography, text, and motion. Conceptual approaches are welcomed. Receive both individual and group critiques on your workshop creations, while also having the chance to seek feedback on other ongoing projects.

Photographs from my personal project documenting Syrian refugee camps in Jordan and Iraq. After having worked in Syria over 7 trips between 1991 and 2009, once their brutal civil war exploded out of the Arab Spring, I was determined to find a way to tell the story of mental health amongst Syrian refugees. This was a story that was dear to me and I had the chance to pitch the idea to International Medical Corps. I spent two weeks in Northern Iraq and Jordan to tell this story, which was ultimately published by Time magazine.‚Å£
Throughout my career personal projects have defined my work and been the lifeblood of my working life.‚Å£

Mirror, Mirror | ‚ÄúMirror, Mirror, on the wall, who‚Äôs the fairest of them all?‚Äù This now ubiquitous English phrase came from a Disney movie, Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs.‚Å£
‚Å£
In photography, mirrors play an important role, serving as a compositional device, and as an element that makes the image more magical, dramatic, mysterious or just visually engaging. The creative use of mirrors in photography gives a poetic license to create imagery that is less obvious or straightforward, but allows for alternative ways of capturing a moment, a character and a scene. It can also be an effective way of avoiding direct contact with a subject or to render a sensitive or difficult situation without direct confrontation.‚Å£
‚Å£
These images from my archive reflect the multitude of ways mirrors serve as visual devices in photography.‚Å£
‚Å£
Captions:‚Å£
‚Å£
1. Donia Remedios, 73, who has pancreatic cancer, spends time at home with her daughter, Orlanda Hernandez Ramirez Remedios, 44, at their family compound. MEXICO 2014‚Å£
‚Å£
2. A Muslim woman is reflected in a car mirror while Christian women are seen walking down the street in Kano. NIGERIA 2013‚Å£
‚Å£
3. Backstage at the Al Fala Theatre in Lahore, actress Nida Chaudrey reflection speaks of the bawdy and racy burlesque shows for which the theater is known. Bombed in early 2009 by extremists attempting to send a message, patrons still attend regularly. The sexual entertainment attracts mostly male viewers who pack the evening shows, but occasionally couples and families also attend. PAKISTAN 2009‚Å£
‚Å£
4. Wealthy young Kuwaitis shop for jewelry at Bulgari. KUWAIT 2000‚Å£
‚Å£
5. Clouds drift in the sky over Bozeman, Montana. USA 2015‚Å£

After the loss of some of our heritage buildings due to the latest city of the dead demolitions, this exhibition depicts the timeless historic area as photographed in 1993 by celebrated photographer Ed Kashi.  You are invited to one of the oldest cemeteries in the world, as curated by Photopia as an immersive experience for the viewers to contemplate and enjoy.

Opening night: 23 February, 2024 &  lasts till 2 March , 2024 
Working hours: 12 pm- 9 pm 
Location: Citadel Cairo 

The oldest continuously used Muslim Cemetery in the world, the City of the Dead, with history tracing back to the seventh century. Cairo‚Äôs vast 13th century cemetery, the only living occupants, were caretakers paid by families to maintain their ancestral mausoleums.
In 1993, over one hundred and twenty thousand people lived, worked, shopped, and went to school in and among the mausoleums. Today, that number is much higher, huts are built around tombstones, between which laundry is hung to dry, and masses of people live and work in dwellings built amongst the grand burial sites of famous religious and political figures of Egypt‚Äôs rich history. This exhibition pays tribute to the historic area, its people & their stories.
This exhibition is sponsored by the US embassy in Cairo.

A recent article in The Economist reported on the issue of stray cows in India and how the right‚Äôs pro-cow policies are doing little to protect the sacred animals. I‚Äôve traveled to India over 10 times on assignment and have seen with my own eyes the way cows are a part of daily life. I‚Äôve always been fascinated by the special position cows have in Hindu society. At first I thought it was unusual, but over the years and many visits I‚Äôve come to not only appreciate the beliefs around a cow‚Äôs sacredness, but also understand that virtually every part of a cow, from their feces, meat, bones, skin, urine, etc, has a value. Whether it‚Äôs using their feces for fuel or building your home, to their skin for clothing and protection, it‚Äôs incredible what overall value, at least from a human‚Äôs perspective of dominion over the natural world, represents. No wonder cows are considered sacred. ‚Å£
‚Å£
But I‚Äôve also seen the downside of this reverence, where cows are left to wander and get sick and literally die on the streets. The ruling conservative party, BJP, has passed several ‚Äúpro-cow‚Äù policies like a ban on cow slaughter, but that has only led to the proliferation of stray cows, now numbering over 5 million. 

Abandoned, they often feed on plastic bags and other garbage, and can cause car crashes and destroy crops. One thing is certain ‚Äì the current situation is untenable and more must be done to protect India‚Äôs stray cows.‚Å£
‚Å£

Visual Riff: Coupling | What does it mean to couple? The dictionary frames it as ‚Äúthe act of bringing or coming together.‚Äù ‚Å£
‚Å£
From the romantic to the traumatic, how do two people hold together and why or what brings them together. In some sense, it‚Äôs the most desired and natural relationship humans strive to attain, yet two people can be brought together for reasons or circumstances that are not positive or romantic or comforting.
‚Å£
There have been couples I‚Äôve met in my lifetime, and I imagine anyone reading this has experienced the same thing, who are so perfectly matched, that if they were to ever break up you‚Äôd think the world was coming to an end. The qualities that I see exemplifying coupling are trust, care, being able to listen and make space for a mate‚Äôs feelings and thoughts, and of course being able to laugh with each other. Yet, some people couple out of desperation, need, economics, lust and social pressures.‚Å£

Santorini, the most magical of the Greek islands. This island of the Cyclades offers a multitude of activities to its visitors.

From discovering its historical heritage to watching the sunset over the Aegean Sea, to black sand beaches and boat trips, there is something for everyone. Here's a rundown of the best things to do in Santorini.

Fira, the capital, is one of the places not to be missed. With its white and blue houses, small cobbled streets, fashion boutiques and luxury hotels with swimming pools, it represents the essence of the island.

The village of Oia is also not to be missed for its spectacular beauty

The archaeological site of Akrotiri is an exciting getaway for history and culture lovers.

The ancient city of Thera is also worth a visit to learn more about the island's history

For food lovers, the Greek cuisine in Santorini is not to be missed, especially the famous souvlaki

Boat trips around the island are a pleasant way to discover the wonders of Santorini. The boat cruise, which allows you to visit the volcanic island and to reach the top of the crater of the volcano Nea Kameni, is a very popular activity

Sea kayaking from the red beach is also a fun activity that allows you to discover the volcanic coast and the fabulous sea caves

To finish the day, the sunset on Oia is one of the most famous activities in Santorini.

However, for those who are looking to watch the sunset from the water, the alignments may be better in Fira or Imerovigli.

Take a voyage back in time to Rothenburg, a medieval German town that is considered the most charming in Bavaria.

Rothenburg has a rich history that dates back to the Middle Ages. The town was founded in 1170 and thrived due to its strategic location on an important trade route. The town's historic buildings have been preserved in their original state and offer visitors a unique glimpse into life in the Middle Ages.

Start by walking through the streets of the old town, admiring the historic buildings and beautiful views.

Be sure to visit the city hall, built in 1250, as well as climb the steps of the clock tower for a spectacular view of the city's rooftops, churches and historic buildings.

Last but not least, don't miss a visit to the medieval fortress called Burggarten, which also offers a breathtaking view of the city. It's the perfect place to take memorable pictures.

1. Sainte Chapelle: This 13th century church is located in Paris and is famous for its spectacular stained glass windows.

2. Saint Germain des Pr√©s: This Parisian church has unique medieval frescoes, a famous organ and a square tower.

3. Sainte C√©cile in Albi: Built in red brick, this gothic church is an architectural gem in the city of Albi.

4. Rouen Cathedral: This Gothic church in the city of Rouen is home to many artistic treasures, including stained glass windows and paintings.

5. Notre Dame de la Treille in Lille: This modern Gothic church is famous for its bold architecture and steel spire bell tower.

6. Saint Pierre de Beauvais: This 13th century gothic church was built with barrel vaults and a facade decorated with sculptures.

7. Saint Maurice de Lille: This Gothic church contains remarkable works of art, including stained glass windows and murals.

8. Reims Cathedral: This Gothic church is famous for its imposing architecture and colorful stained glass windows.

9. Notre Dame de Fourvi√®re in Lyon: This basilica built on a hill overlooks the city of Lyon and offers a spectacular view of the city.

10. Palais B√©n√©dictine in F√©camp: This gothic church houses a collection of religious art, as well as beautiful furniture and colorful stained glass windows.

One of the most exciting shoots I did last year was working with the @eastafricanreptiles & Taylor Ashe Antivenom center in Watamu, Kenya to photograph spitting cobras. This particular snake is a Red Spitting Cobra (Naja pallida). Photographing these snakes is a challenge because they are not only highly venomous but they can be very aggressive/defensive as well. I had to wear a full face shield, which allowed me to avoid getting any of the venom they spit in my eyes, nose or ears.

Snakes are sadly often misunderstood and killed on sight no matter the circumstance, which is horrible because they are such a vital part of the eco systems we all live in. Organizations like East Africa Reptile's focus much of their attention not only on education and safety,  but in helping to safely remove snakes from people's homes and properties around Kenya, further increasing their chances of survival.

This is one of the most unique looking frogs you can find in Costa Rica, known as the Coronated Tree Frog. It's name comes from the fact that at certain angles, it looks as if it is wearing a crown. They can be found in the mountains around the area known as Sarapique, just north of San Jose. It is one of many different species of frogs and snakes that we look for during my Costa Rica wildlife workshops I run each January.

Be sure to swipe left to see this image in its full resolution!

Last September I found myself wandering around the deserts of Dubai in search of the Horned Arabian Viper. Unfortunately for me, it was the wrong time of year as they tend to love the hot desert nights. We did however find a number of these Saw Scaled Vipers (Echis Carinatus). These beautiful snakes are easily the most deadly snake in the UAE, accounting for more snake bites per year than all other snakes combined. They can be aggressive, have a quick strike and a very powerful venom.

Thanks to @wildlifewithnitin for showing me around! Can't wait for the next adventure!

We invite you to join me and authors Rachel Page, Dina Dechmann, Teague O‚ÄôMara and Marco Tschapka, for a public webinar on Wed Dec 13 at 10am Panam√° time. Together, the five of us will discuss our newly published book, BAT ISLAND, taking you on a photographic journey to the rainforests of Barro Colorado Island, Panam√°, to meet the 76 species of bats that occupy this small space, and learn about their stunning natural history, physiology, evolution, sensory adaptations, foraging behavior, and social systems.
 
Join us on zoom at http://www.stri.si.edu/batisland

After years of anticipation, we're thrilled to present our bat book: ‚ÄòBAT ISLAND‚Äô, a tribute to our dear friend, Dr. Eli Kalko. Her visionary work in bat research set a remarkable course for many careers. Collaborating with exceptional authors - Dr. Rachel Page from STRI (Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute) @smithssonianbatlab, Dr. Dina Dechmann @DechmannLab (Max Planck Institute of Animal Behavior) @mpi_animalbehav , Dr. Marco Tschapka from the University of Ulm, and Dr. Teague O'Mara from Bat Conservation International - has been an incredible journey spanning two decades.

Our friendship with Eli and our shared passion for bats inspired this project. Over the last two decades, I've had the privilege of photographing the phenomenal and mysterious night flyers that continue to intrigue and inspire us.

The release of ‚ÄòBAT ISLAND‚Äô marks a milestone, sharing the captivating natural history, ecological insights, and social behavior of Barro Colorado Island's bats.

Published by Insight Editions, with authors from the Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute @smithsonianpanama, this book is an homage and testament to the profound legacy of Eli Kalko, and the impact she has had on tropical bat biology.

ü¶á Looking for the perfect Christmas gift? Look no further! üéÅ 'BAT ISLAND‚Äô is a treasure trove that captures the essence of these night flying wonders. With 160 pages of stunning imagery, BAT ISLAND delves into the captivating lives, diverse foraging habits, roosting secrets, and the fascinating social systems of Neotropical bats.

Ideal for both bat enthusiasts and inquisitive families, this book is more than just pages‚Äîit's an immersive experience into the lives of a remarkable group of animals. Whether exploring their nocturnal adventures or learning about their ecological importance, BAT ISLAND is an ideal gift to inspire awe and appreciation for the wonders of nature. Grab your copy now and gift the magic of bat exploration this holiday season! üåüü¶áüéÑ

Sharing a few more images of this remarkable moment when I encountered a bonobo with a young mongoose. 

I took all these images over about an hour as I watched this individual carry and play with a little mongoose, deep in the tropical forests of Democratic Republic of Congo. 

Big thanks to Dr. Barbara Fruth (Max-Planck Institute for Animal Behavior) and the team of the LuiKotale Bonobo Project for making these encounters possible. Follow me @christianziegler for more wildlife and nature photography!

Back from a very nice vacation, and I'm excited to share more Bonobo moments, starting with this incredible mongoose scene!

I am honored to have won the portrait category in 'Nature in focus' with this image ‚Äì thank you all for your support, especially the jury !

During my adventures near LuiKotale field station in the Democratic Republic of Congo I had a remarkable encounter. I witnessed a young male Bonobo tenderly petting a small mongoose.

This fascinating moment continued as he carefully held the mongoose while enjoying fruit in a nearby tree with the rest of his group.

However, this bond may not be as innocent as it seems. Bonobos occasionally include meat in their diet, and it's likely this young mongoose was caught when its mother was hunted by the group.

Big thanks to Dr. Barbara Fruth (Max-Planck Institute for Animal Behavior) and the team of the LuiKotale Bonobo Project for making these encounters possible. Follow me @christianziegler for more wildlife and nature photography!

Ingredients:

Super Easy 4 Ingredient peanut butter cookies! üç™ Crispy golden edges, gooey peanut butter centers. Bookmark these for your next sweet tooth!¬†

PEANUT BUTTER COOKIES:¬†
1 ¬Ω cups smooth peanut butter¬†
1 ¬Ω cups brown sugar¬†
2 large eggs, at room temp
1 ¬Ω tsp baking soda¬†
1 tsp vanilla paste, optional¬†

Instructions:¬†

1. Preheat the oven to 350 F. Line two medium rimmed baking sheets with parchment paper and set aside.¬†
2. In a bowl with a stand mixer or a medium bowl with a hand mixer add peanut butter and brown sugar. Mix together on medium-high for 2-3 minutes.¬†
3. Add eggs, baking soda and vanilla bean paste if using and mix together for another minute.¬†
4. With a 1 inch cookie scoop, scoop dough balls onto the baking sheet and create a criss cross pattern with a fork. Top with a little extra brown sugar if desired.¬†
5. Bake for 8-9 minutes or until the edges are slightly golden brown. Remove from the oven and leave on the baking sheet for an additional 3-5 minutes. Transfer to a wire baking rack to finish cooling.

‚ÄúLight Walker‚Äù

A self portrait series from just a few weeks ago in Deadvlei, Namibia.  A place I‚Äôve dreamed of visiting for a decade‚Ä¶ and yet being there in person, walking barefoot across the dead marsh under these 600-900 year old skeleton trees, was such a surreal experience unlike what I imagined it would be.  It‚Äôs strange to walk through a place that feels so long dead and forgotten - yet still full of life and wonder.

I originally had an entirely different series of images in my mind for here, involving a couple of different colourful dresses (red and gold) and dance poses mimicking and flowing with these trees‚Ä¶ but when I arrived here, just as the sun rose and lit up my surroundings and as I walked over the last sand dune to see the dead pan valley floor below, all those earlier visions I had simply vanished. Thankfully, tucked away in the bottom of my backpack under my camera gear and red/gold dresses (anyone else cram dresses and chocolate into their backpack as a general hiking norm?), I had also this white dress as a back-up‚Ä¶ and I was so glad I brought it, because all I could actually envision in person here was a balance of death and life, light and dark, a dream walking through decay. 

And so that‚Äôs how I spent the next 3 hours - walking and running around barefoot, feeling connection, contrast and awe, and creating this new series as it came to me. ü§ç What a surreal place.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

‚ÄúThe Heart of Ancient Earth‚Äù

3/100 of my year-long self portrait project. üíô

This was taken at 2am in Iceland - the only time I‚Äôve ever seen this location, Reynisfjara beach, completely empty of visitors.  The basalt columns eerily rose out of the midsummer night fog, and everything was still and silent, even the waves in the ocean right next to these columns - a calm rarity I‚Äôve never seen here before. 

This was my first night ever being high enough in the north to experience no complete darkness, even at 2am.  The light was soft and blue, and the settings and emotions felt in this place all came together to inspire this self portrait‚Ä¶ a moment of connection with the ancient earth. üíô

‚ÄúArise‚Äù

I‚Äôm feeling very ready for a gentle, soft and slow December. This month I want to let my mind rest, let my body feel at ease, and my heart feel opened. After a very busy travel and work season for the last few months, I‚Äôm so excited to take December to slow down and let myself become in tune with my natural surroundings, especially as winter sets in‚Ä¶ letting myself slow down and rest, just like the trees, the animals and the mountains as they become blanketed in snow for this new cozy season. üíï

This image here holds the exact kind of energy I want to embrace this month. üß° This self portrait is already from 8 years ago, which is wild to me!  It‚Äôs still one of my very favourites I‚Äôve ever taken, to this day. ü•∞

‚ÄúA Place to Rest‚Äù

24/100 of my current self portrait project. üíö

I came across this moss-covered boulder in the woods a couple of weeks ago during one of the Rockies super warm Chinooks winds, which melted all the winter snow for a few days. It felt so surreal to wander around the forest and mountains of Banff National Park in what felt like early summer weather!  I haven‚Äôt taken a self portrait in the last several weeks just because it‚Äôs been sooooo freezing cold, so I took advantage of this extra warm day to forest bathe, listen to the birds, rest, soak in my surroundings and to create a new image to remember this feeling of February restfulness this year. And also to remember that spring really is on the horizon, even if it‚Äôs snowing again now. üòÇ

Care to join me in some majestic moody mountain gazing?  I could easily spend hours staring at the mountains (and indeed, I have been)... especially when the fog and clouds dance around between the peaks. üòç 

This month I‚Äôve been having extra fun capturing these scenes with my new lens, the @sonyalpha 70-200mm f/2.8 G Master II. Not only have I been loving the much lighter weight of this lens compared to the previous version, but I also love being able to shoot with a wider aperture at f/2.8, allowing me to easily and clearly capture the darker moody moments. ü•∞

I‚Äôm officially totally entranced by this new closer perspective of these peaks when using this lens... and now I think I‚Äôm hooked on moody mountain timelapses, hehe. ‚ù§Ô∏è #ad

Hi everyone!  Here‚Äôs a little BTS reel made in collaboration with @sonyalpha and one of my absolute favourite lenses of all time:  the 70-200mm f/2.8 G Master II.  I‚Äôm SO excited to finally bring home this lens this month, especially after trying it on loan several times over the last 2 years and absolutely falling in love with it.  I haven‚Äôt had anything with more zoominess (is that a word?) capabilities beyond 85mm, so finally having this lens with a range up to 200mm is gonna be a game changer, ahhhh. ‚ÄúThe Essence of Lightness‚Äù

A self portrait taken at midnight in Iceland last summer (the time of endless light!). üíô

So far every morning this year I‚Äôve been deep diving into my journal, writing out and contemplating what it would be like to live lighter.  To cultivate an ease and lightness in my mind, to be less busy, to be more trusting in the unknown future.  To play more, and let my inner child lead me romping through the woodlands and meadows, inspired by my imagination. 

I thought I‚Äôd share this lil blurb I brain-barfed out onto the pages this morning. ü§ì‚¨áÔ∏è

‚ÄúThis year I want to let go of pressure.  Both the pressure I put on myself, and the pressure the societal world puts on us all. 

I let go of the pressure to be perfect. The pressure to look a certain way. The pressure to post every day. I let go of the pressure I put on myself to create better and better images, videos and paintings.

This year I embrace lightness. I celebrate imperfection, because when I allow myself and my creations to be made imperfectly with my mind open, it creates space for a world of new ideas, opportunities and surprise happenings I never would have dreamed up myself in my ‚Äúperfect world‚Äù.

This year I let my true essence take the seat of my mind and being. I take time to intentionally practice dwelling in my truest state - the state of complete trust, leading to peace and joyful lightness, where I feel the most myself. 

This year I allow myself to live. Not by someone else‚Äôs standards, and not by the standards I once thought I should hold over myself. 

I live by listening. I listen intently to what brings me a sense of joy, rightness and lightness. I listen to what I can give - what I can naturally offer and help bring out in others.

I live by being kind. I live in gratitude for the freedom I‚Äôm so, so, so incredibly fortunate to have access to.

I allow this freedom to be protected, nurtured and loved, to not let this gift be taken for granted or hijacked by the endless hustling pressures of the world.

This year I embrace lightness. I put my heart first, and I let love, trust and wonder lead the way down this path of life. This one chance we have to truly live.‚Äù ü§ç

Oh, 2023. ‚ù§Ô∏è 

There‚Äôs so many thoughts I could share from the past year, the ups and downs, the incredible things I‚Äôve seen and done, the hard struggles, overwhelm and work that came with it, the hopes and dreams for the future, the ongoing quest for a calmer mind, and many precious moments I wish could last forever. 

‚Ä¶but I‚Äôm going to simply end the year by sharing 10 slides that mean something to me in this moment. ü•∞

1. ‚ÄúEver Enduring‚Äù - a self portrait taken during a 400km hike across the mountains of Scotland in April.  One of the hardest and most beautiful experiences I‚Äôve had, and that I‚Äôm most proud of completing this year.

2. Backpacking in the Tombstone Mountains of the Yukon (still with the sword prop for photos, hehe). It felt so special to do a lot of hiking and camping with Pepper this year - he‚Äôll be 13 years old soon, so I‚Äôve been feeling extra aware/grateful for every adventure we have together. ü•π‚ù§Ô∏è

3.  @kristopherandres and I have spent more than half the year on the road, the trails or overseas this year. I can‚Äôt believe I get to share my dream nomadic life with this human. ü•∞

7.  My favourite novel I read this year.  I‚Äôve never empathized with the personality of a main character more - socially awkward but incredibly brave, her strength being kindness. 

8. Meeting @melissa_schaefer (creator of @magazine.mother ) in Copenhagen and seeing the magazine for my first time - with my photo on the cover! ü•∞

9. More precious moments with Pepper. A reminder to stay present.

10. Reflections from @chelseakauai ‚Äòs latest post - thoughts I‚Äôve been heavily deep diving into this past month, and am using to guide my priorities in 2024.  Perhaps these reflection prompts can help you, too. ‚ù§Ô∏èü•∞

Hi all ! I'm back at my editing PC going through the images from Tasmania. In choosing which image to edit first, I guess first impressions count! We were so excited to see snow from the aeroplane as we were flying in and Kunanyi did not disappoint. I hiked up South Wellington on the first dawn of the trip and eventually found my way to the Rocking Stone where I struggled with a frozen tripod and cold hands but managed to get this composition among a few others. It was the first series of shots taken with NiSi s new V7 filter holder of which I had a prototype to try out. Only a polariser was used for this image as I had to resist a temptation to shoot into the blazing sun to the left! 

Stay tuned for more images from our trip :) #nisifilters #nisifiltersanz @nisiglobal @nisifiltersaustralia #australia #seeaustralia #tasmania #discoverearth #discovertasmania #hobart #kunanyi #mountwellington #rockingstone #dawn #sunrise #landscape #nature #winter #everlookphotography

Hope you enjoy these colourful seascapes from Yorke Peninsula as much as I enjoyed waking up early to take them last month. A stunning stretchof coast that I can't wait to get back to in the future :)

#everlookphotography #southaustralia #yorkepeninsula

#everlookphotography #southaustralia #hillocksdrive #coffinbeach #yorkepeninsula #australia

Dramatic light along the south coast road of Yorke Peninsula shot on the last morning of our trip. This shot was taken with the NiSi swift FS ND filter system (3 stop ND) and a blend of several exposures for dynamic range and motion.

#everlookphotography #southaustralia #australia #yorkepeninsula #marionbay #nature #landscape #seascape #nisifilters @nisiglobal @nisifilters @nisifiltersaustralia

The pure sand dunes above the beach at Daly Head were incredible to explore - tiptoeing around o minimise footprints after sunset, I noticed some anticrepuscular rays opposite the post sunset glow!

#everlookphotography #yorkepeninsula #southaustralia #dalyhead #australia #seeaustralia

A dramatic sunset out of nowhere came upon us at Hillocks point while we were staying just up the beach. Times like this I take off all filters to make sure the image is as clean as possible with spray floating around!

#everlookphotography #southaustralia #sunset #australia @hillocksdrive

We've just returned from a 1 week trip to Yorke Peninsula where we experienced all kinds of weather conditions and saw more landscapes and wildlife than we've seen in a long long time! I'm thinking we might need to make this a regular summer escape.

This shot taken from our 3 night stay at @hillocksdrive at an amazing place called Annie's Nursery. This shot was not taken with the FS-ND filter system though many others on the trip were. It was part of the mission of this trip to get some images to base a review and I was somewhat suprised by its utility despite having some doubts.

Things that happen in bed... ü´¶ You spend more time in bed than you think, so why not transform your bed into a tranquil oasis? These are some of the tips that could help you achieve that.
‚Ä¢ Quality Bedding. Invest in high-quality, comfortable sheets that are soft and breathable. My favorite ones are bamboo lyocell sheets from @cariloha‚Äôs Retreat Collection.
‚Ä¢ Aesthetics. Choose calming, neutral colors for your bedding, like white or ivory. Avoid printed sheets to create a serene atmosphere.
‚Ä¢ Pillows. Use memory foam pillows for added comfort, especially if you are struggling with neck pain.
‚Ä¢ Mattress Topper. Enhance the comfort of your mattress with a high-quality mattress topper that will provide extra cushioning.
‚Ä¢ Dim Lighting. Warm-toned light bulbs help to create a cozy and calming atmosphere.
‚Ä¢ Blackout Curtains. These can help block out morning light when you want to sleep in and create a more peaceful sleep environment.
‚Ä¢ Aromatherapy. As for scented candles, pick the ones with calming fragrances like lavender, chamomile, or eucalyptus.
‚Ä¢ Humidifier. It will help with your skin dryness and improve the quality of your sleep as you‚Äôll start breathing more freely.
‚Ä¢ Soft Rugs. Stepping onto a cushiony surface in the morning is a grounding experience that will help start the day on a positive note.
‚Ä¢ Electronic Devices. Limit phone usage before bedtime as the blue light radiated from screens can interfere with your sleep.

The beetle of rebirth ü™≤üåû
At the end of November 2021 we were at a friends house about to leave when a golden beetle posed on my hand. It had been a long time since I saw one or at least payed close attention to it. I feel that many times we experience things often but don‚Äôt really give importance to them until we feel it is needed, then it becomes something meaningful. I started drawing the beetle on my notebook, carefully placed the insect on my finger it was holding my index with his tiny legs and thought about a ring! 
It gave me nostalgia of when the world was different and when we could travel, reminded me of our time in Egypt and in some way gave me hope, Cairo 2019 was also where I first saw a beetle ring from Tutankamon in the museum. I was amazed by Egyptian culture, art and mostly jewelry I thought it was cool but I never really questioned the symbolism of the elements and characters they used back then and why, but that day the golden beetle that posed on my hand made me curious and I started reaserching what it means, the meaning varies depending the culture but what I took from the Egyptians is that: the beetle symbolized the sun, a new day, a new opportunity, a cicle, knowing that the sun rises every day no matter what, rebirth! I thought the meaning was beautiful and felt like the right timing for me to start a process of ‚Äúrebirth‚Äù this was right before 2021 ended, 

which had been a though year, I was not feeling too motivated, my grandma had just passed away a couple months before, and some little struggles that made me feel a bit stuck and not at my best. I didn‚Äôt know it at the time but from that day it was going to take 5 months to have the finished ring in my hands. Not because the actual process takes that long but in a way I wanted to have it ready whenever I felt better with myself, finishing this ring will mean to have a rebirth in a way, learnt the lessons, feel more motivated and in a better mental space.

The truth about ALMOND CROISSANTSü•ê

Croissants go stale so quickly!! So here‚Äôs what you can do when you have a few extra ones laying around :) Or if you don‚Äôt want to pay the almond croissant premium LOL.

‚ú®Ingredients:
‚Ä¢1 cup water
‚Ä¢1/3 cup sugar

‚Ä¢4 croissants
‚Ä¢25 gr unsalted butter
‚Ä¢60 gr cane sugar
‚Ä¢60 gr almond flour
‚Ä¢1 medium egg
‚Ä¢1 tsp vanilla extract
‚Ä¢sliced almonds
‚Ä¢powder sugar for dusting

In a small saucepan, bring water and 1/3 cup of sugar to a boil to make a syrup. Cool down. Preheat oven 350¬∞F and cut croissants in half. In a bowl, combine softened unsalted butter with sugar. Then add almond flour, combine, and lastly add egg and vanilla to form an almost paste. Brush sugar syrup on the inside and outside of the croissant and then spread the almond paste inside. Close the croissant and spread more paste on top and top off with sliced almonds. Bake for 15-18 mins, cool down, and dust with powdered sugar. Enjoy!

EASY SPICY TUNA POKE BOWLSüêüü•£üå∂Ô∏è (full recipe below)

I think spicy tuna bowls are the new hot girl meal. I know raw fish can be a little intimidating, so make sure you buy previously flash-frozen fish from a grocer that you trust! I buy my ahi tuna filets from @Sprouts and eat them the day of.

‚ú®Ingredients (4 servings) // about 60gr protein per portion 

-1 1/2 lbs raw ahi tuna (2 steaks)
-1 1/2 tbsp sriracha
-2-3 tbsp aminos or soy sauce
-3 tbsp Kewpie mayonnaise
-1 cup edamame
-1 hass avocado
-1 cup uncooked sushi rice
-1 tbsp mirin
-1 tbsp rice vinegar
-1/2 tbsp sesame oil
-1 tsp salt
-1 tsp sesame seeds

Pat dry ahi tuna and cut it into 1-inch cubes. Place inside a bowl and add sriracha, aminos, and mayo. Stir until combined, cover, and rest refrigerated for at least 15 minutes. Cook sushi rice according to the instructions on the package. Warm up frozen edamame by pouring boiling water on top and letting it sit for 5 minutes. Slice avocado or mash it; feel free to season it however you like. Add mirin, rice vinegar, sesame oil, and salt to cooked rice. Stir and use it as a base for your bowl. Continue plating by adding about 4 ounces of tuna, 1/4 cup of edamame, and 1/4-1/2 an avocado. Portions are up to you! Top with sesame seeds, and feel free to add any extra sauce and seasonings like furikake. Enjoy immediately and save any leftovers in a tight-lid container in the fridge. Eat the same day.

‚ÄúFurniture‚Ä¶ lots of furniture!‚Äù @klekktic 

The Matrix is one of my all time favourite movies. It came out 25 years ago, inspiring a whole generation of filmmakers, visual effects artists and stunt coordinators. 

This is my take on the iconic ‚Äúguns, lots of guns‚Äù scene where Neo & Trinity enter The Matrix to prepare for battle. I thought this would be a fun and innovative way of showcasing a furniture brand. Having different products from the @klekktic collection flying into the Matrix. 

To execute this @shravanraoo & I shot for a full 12 hours in a studio in Dubai. Heba, the founder of Klekktic, who plays Trinity in this video, helped coordinate all of the Klekktic pieces to be shipped to the studio. We then placed each item one by one filming the product and then removing it. This allowed us to create the effect of different pieces flying into place.

@Klekktic is a beautiful UAE based brand. They have a minimal design aesthetic that is clean and elegant. The best part about their products is they are customizable. For example, the desk at the start of the video I fully customized from a dining room table into an office desk with draws and storage. Bed sizes, table lengths, mirror finishings etc can all be customized to fit your space size and preference. 

My home project is really starting to take shape. It‚Äôs been a long time coming but it‚Äôs been worth the wait. More coming on that soon‚Ä¶

Special shout out to @shravanraoo who helped me film this and then worked on the kick ass visual effects. 

What do you guys think of the video? Drop a Matrix reference comment below if you liked the video!

Showing you the world of @MarinaHomeInteriors 

I love challenging myself, and for this video I wanted to get creative by making a travel inspired piece of content but all from the Marina Home showroom in Dubai.

Travel is a huge part of my life, so when I learnt about the inspiration and international origins of Marina Home‚Äôs furniture it got me excited about making something fun that would highlight those countries and cultures. Setting up a new home is a very personal experience. Product choices and recommendations can come with lots of different opinions.
