What do you know about Venezuela? üáªüá™ 

Back in July I had the opportunity to spend a few weeks in Venezuela creating something special for @beautifuldestinations. 

As 2023 has been the year of AI, I‚Äôve been wanting to innovate and figure out a way to combine new immersive AI visuals with travel content. My thinking was that we‚Äôd be going to a place that not many people have seen before, Angel Falls in Canaima National Park, and if we could combine never before seen AI content with a truly out of this world destination then we‚Äôd have all the ingredients for something special. 

The first person I called was @andras.ra who‚Äôs been diving into short form AI content this year. We‚Äôve worked together a ton over the years and he‚Äôs an editing magician. The idea developed into a FPV Drone only concept where we‚Äôd play with generative AI to add little details into the video. @reme_martyr then joined the team to execute the aerials, he killed it! As the concept got bigger so did the team with @alexislefrene , @shravanraoo , @andres.visual and @bahaamalaeb joining the squad. 

What started as a fun idea turned into a full blown innovation project, looking to create the world‚Äôs first AI supported Tourism Campaign. By tapping into unique visual styles the hope was to create something that would make some noise and spark a conversation about the destination.

What you wouldn‚Äôt know is that 40 years ago my parents lived in Venezuela. At that time, Caracas was a global advertising hub. Ironically, my Dad was working in the same field that I am now. Back then he was one of the few photographers paving the way through dark room visual effects, that‚Äôs before photoshop existed! It was very cool to be there 40 years later trying to do something similar, as Venezuela announces itself as a new and exciting Tourism destination. I love the country‚Äôs new branding ‚Äúopen to the future‚Äù and I hope this video gives you a glimpse of that future as well as the future of content and where I think it‚Äôs going. 

This video is quite the rollercoaster so fasten your seat belt and enjoy the ride‚Ä¶

Puppies & Pilates üêïü¶æ

For the last month I‚Äôve been doing Pilates with the awesome Gaby Noble founder of @exhalepilateslondon, as a way to improve my strength training. Prior to this year I had no idea what Pilates was and always thought of it as a workout for women. I couldn‚Äôt have been more wrong. 

As I wait for Project Apartment to get fully underway I‚Äôve turned my empty home into a Pilates Studio. This is just one of the many brutal exercises that are getting me lifting heavier than I ever have and feeling more recovered each day. 

There‚Äôs a big reason why a lot of elite male athletes, celebrities and performers have added Pilates to their training regimes üëáüèΩ

- Improves your muscle to mind connection. I am so focused on the movements and getting the muscles to do exactly what it needs to do. Something I never think about when weightlifting. 

- Improves core strength. Killer ab workout every single time!

- Helps me lift more, squat deeper, recover quicker, lets the joints and muscles breathe. This is why it‚Äôs been the perfect supplement to my strength training. 

- Limits injuries so I can keep pushing towards my goals without set backs. My flexibility and mobility has completely changed in 1 month. Again, allowing me to lift heavier, get stronger and recover faster. 

- Improves your posture & helps keep a healthy spine. Both are key for the work I do and ultimately make me move better and with more ease.

This is just the start of my Pilates journey but I‚Äôve been loving it so far with Gaby Noble @exhalepilateslondon . If you‚Äôre interested in trying it out shoot her a message. She‚Äôs the best in the space and trained the likes of Harry Styles, Kate Moss, Giancarlo Esposito & Christian Eriksen.

‚Ä¢ 1-2 cups of water
‚Ä¢ 2 tbsp soy sauce
‚Ä¢ 1-2 tea bags
‚Ä¢ 2 bay leaves
‚Ä¢ 1/2 inch stick of cinnamon
‚Ä¢ 1/2 tsp Sichuan peppercorns
‚Ä¢ 1 tsp of sugar
‚Ä¢ pinch of salt

Then boil room temperature eggs for 7 minutes, and then remove and cool in an ice bath.

Crack the shells of the eggs (or remove completely) and place into a container. Pour over the prepared soy mixture (cooled) and set in the fridge for at least 12 hours. 

Serve with noodles or eat them plain - because they are delicious!

BENEATH THE OPERA HOUSE, PALAIS Garnier in Paris there is a lake. Crime reporter and Opera critic Gaston Leroux used it as the background for Phantom of the Opera. The "lake" is actually a tank of groundwater and the Paris fire brigade use it for dive training. I photographed the training and got the rare privilege of swimming through the vaults beneath the opera.

Exploring Close to the Edge Cave
"There was at best a vague plan. It was a true dirtbag trip"
The trip seemed simple enough when Neeld Messler proposed it. Drive north with a car packed full of caving equipment and push the deepest pit in Canada past its 836-foot depth.
The trip was epic, my first true expedition. Equal amounts exhilarating and terrifying.
Follow the link in my bio for the whole adventure. 
Blog>Close to the Edge

Earlier this month, Dustin Mater (@dustign) and I had the honor of presenting our Mural of America work at the @insidenatgeo Storytellers Summit in LA  The project leverages the power of stories told on the landscape to reframe American History to include the first 20,000 years of human habitation of the Americas. Thanks @insidenatgeo @kaityarnall @vincentjmusi for having us out to talk about this work which has just began. Our aim is to have 10 interactive VR experiences completed by 2026. Thanks also to all of our fabulous co-presenters. Your work is an inspiration.

Follow the link in the nonprofit @ancientartarchive bio to learn more about the Mural of America, sign up for our mailing list and to support our work.

I've always had a fascination with the underground world. At first, I was obsessed with being one of the few people who could go into a cave. As my career progressed what caves preserve began to be more important. The underground world can act as a time capsule holding artwork made by people long before us. Those ancient artists are sending us messages from the past. My friend @dustign calls them "love notes in a bottle" from our ancestors. 
Those artists in the past are speaking to us if we let them. They are not just telling us who they were, they are telling us who we all are.

Happy New Year! My hope for this new year is that we all realize there is much more that connects us than divides us. Ancient images prove that point to me.
If one image could sum up all of humanity it would be the hand print. I have photographed them on every continent and across the time span of human history. This one is 36,000 years old from El Castillo in Spain. What the person who made this one meant by placing their hand on a cave wall and blowing pigment around it is lost to time, but how can you look at this image and not feel a connection to them?
For more follow the link in my profile AlvarezPhotography.Com>Blog>Human Hand Print

This week marks the 7th anniversary of the Bears Ears National Monument! It is the first National Monument to be established at the request of a coalition of Native American Tribes. It is also the first to be managed in partnership of the Tribes and the Federal Government. 
Bears Ears serves as a model of cultural resource management that can be applied to other public lands. 
I have been going to Cedar Mesa and what is now the Bears Ears for a long time, here is some work from the area for the nonprofits @ancientartarchive  and @insidenatgeo Thanks to both!

Speaker bio | Empowering the Australian Muslim Community against #Islamophobia | 2nd March 2024 

Born & brought up in the suburbs of Sydney to Lebanese immigrant parents Lina started off her career as a Secondary School Teacher and worked her way up to school Principal of an independent school.
After giving up this career in education, her passion for food as a way to¬†hang on to a special part of her Lebanese heritage flourished. Growing up the daughter of immigrants, emersed in a world of clashing cultures, food became the most ideal way to link both worlds and form an Australian ‚Äì Lebanese identity she was proud of.
Over the last few years, Lina has created content for some of Australia‚Äôs largest brands and companies from Kenwood to ABC Everyday to Woolworths and Ebay Australia. She was chosen as a contributor to¬†‚ÄòNew Voices on Food‚Äô¬†(an anthology of works celebrating the diversity of voices to be found within the Australian food landscape). She has also appeared on Australian TV for cooking segments on¬†Studio 10, a few episodes of SBS Food‚Äôs¬†The Cook Up¬†and appears for regular segments on ABC‚Äôs Weekend Breakfast News to chat all things food.

Salt & pepper

Heat olive oil in a fry pan. Add pine nuts and toast until they just turn a golden brown. Add the onion & saut√© until soft. Add the mince, stir to brown and remove large lumps of meat. Add baharat, molasses & salt/pepper to taste. Stir through. Return pine nuts to pan. Combine well. Set aside to cool.

Once stuffing has cooled, use fingers to gently stuff each zucchini. 

In a large fry pan, melt 2 tbsp ghee. Fry the zucchini, turning frequently, in batches until they just change colour. Return all the zucchini to pan & cover with just enough water. Bring to a gentle boil & leave to simmer for 20 min. (Place a heat proof plate on the zucchini to keep them submerged). 

At 20 min the zucchini should have softened. Remove from water & set aside. Do not discard the cooking water. Strain it & set aside. (There should be about 2 cups of liquid, if less top it up with more water to make 2 cups).

On this day in 2020 I was waking up to snow shoe in Andermatt, Switzerland. Just one of the many adventures as one of two representatives from the United States for their 2-week Global Influencer Summit. I would return home to go speak for my first time at WPPI  just weeks before the world would shut down.

My efforts shifted to caring more for my family, and taking a job that I truly and happily thought would be the rest of my life, but it did not turn out that way. And for the last 4 years I was happy to set down what I knew to focus on what was in front of me even if the breath in my creative lungs was very shallow.

Over the last 4 months I‚Äôve been sorting out next steps. I was recently challenged to put together a reel of my work to share. For all the ways my short memory and impuslivity have served me in moments of needed courage, it hasn‚Äôt always helped me stay organized... so, it took some time. Going back through the work over the last 16 years reminded me how fortunate I have been to do something I loved for so long that has allowed me to see so much of this beautiful planet. For years, whether it was a brand or a fellow creative, I was able to be in very personal conversations with people that wanted to communicate something uniquely their own to the world. The drive to create beautiful things is a bass note in the soul of so many people, and being in that space was much more rewarding than it was work. I‚Äôm hoping photography, creative direction, and making beautiful things is not just a part of my past, but even if it were, it‚Äôs been very formational in who I am now.

I hope you‚Äôll watch, and if it at all makes sense to share it with someone who might want to see it please do. You can find the full resolution version on my bio link

I saw @karlieplace post a bit of this editing style on a reel yesterday and I just thought it was amazing. Shout out to hers, you should definitely go check it out. 

When I see the dodge/burn notes on old film prints it‚Äôs a reminder that the art and intention of the shot doesn‚Äôt end until it‚Äôs delivered. I imagine some people would rather enjoy the magic without seeing how the sausage is made but I LOVE editing and always have.

I came up in this industry at a time where there was this odd mystique and elitism that I thankfully avoided, but I saw it discourage SO many people. And there was a tension because my income was also tied to education regarding editing and presets, and carving out a brand that was uniquely my voice. I‚Äôd much rather contribute to the shared pool of liberating knowledge so that the beautiful thing you were meant to do is not trapped behind something as dull as tone curves and split toning. 

The anchors of journalistic integrity are different than those for eliciting emotion. But you are also free to, and encouraged to, be unashamed about what does and doesn‚Äôt land with your creative preference. Just don‚Äôt make that the primary thing about your engagements with people on the internet. 

As always if you have questions about my process, whether it be gear, software, how I think about what I do, or anything else I‚Äôd so much rather communicate than get a ‚Äòlike‚Äô.

caption:
If Jesus. That‚Äôs the title of a series of teachings I‚Äôve been doing at our church this January. If Jesus is here ‚Äî if Jesus is good ‚Äî if Jesus is Lord ‚Äì then that changes everything. Those three ideas are like a three-legged stool. If any one of those concepts is missing (or even cut a little short), our entire idea and belief in who Jesus is will simply topple over. We need each of these three attributes to be complete and strong if we‚Äôre to grow in our understanding of the true Jesus. And if we do, it changes everything ‚Äî our outlook on life and its challenges, our decisions, our relationships, our purpose, and eventually our eternity.

Which of these three attributes of Jesus do you think are most misunderstood or missing in our lives: his presence, his goodness, or his authority and power as Lord? Take the poll and drop in your thoughts.

The other day was my day for the ‚Äúdreaded Glucose test‚Äù that typically happens between week 24-28 of pregnancy. I went an alternative route during my pregnancy with Rell so I never experienced the glucola drink, BUT this time my doctor offered a natural alternative to the standard glucose drink, called the Fresh Test. (I have no affiliation with this) It ended up not being so ‚Äúdreaded‚Äù of an experience after all.
It still creates that glucose load with 50g of sugar, but it tastes like a refreshing lemonade and it‚Äôs non-gmo, with no additives and preservatives, and I didn‚Äôt feel icky at all. (It does warn that some may experience side effects‚Äî that is a lot of sugar at once!) I was even able to eat a boiled egg before my test as mine was a non-fasting test, but of course follow what your provider suggests! I mixed the powder with some water and drank it an hour before my blood draw. The visit to the lab was easy. And now I just wait for my results! üôèüôè
__
I wanted to share this quick experience and just bring awareness that there is a natural alternative that you can explore with your doctor when it‚Äôs time for your Glucose Test during pregnancy. Obviously this is an important step for mama and baby during pregnancy, so this is up to you and your doctor, but I personally love learning about other alternatives that feel right to me.

SAVE this for a quick Egg Free Breakfast option!
Rell has never liked eggs- never. Which led us to exploring if there was something instinctual behind it and we learned she had an egg allergy when she was a baby. The great news is, she can eat eggs baked into things, and I think she‚Äôs growing out of this allergy BUT she still dislikes eggs. Obviously eggs are an easy and awesome way for quick protein for breakfast‚Äî especially in the form of egg bites! SO it was time to explore a new Quick Protein option for breakfast and she LOVES these Sausage bites! We call them ‚Äúmuffins‚Äù üòâ Wether you‚Äôre catering to an egg allergy in your home or not- this is a great breakfast alternative to keep in your fridge or freezer for when you need a quick and healthy breakfast grab!
*I make these gluten free- and they can easily be made dairy free!
‚Äî
RECIPE
-1lb ground Breakfast Sausage
-1-2 cups finely chopped broccoli florets (optional, but a great way to add greens into breakfast!)
-1 cup your choice of gluten free flour (I used Bob‚Äôs Red Mill Paleo All Purpose mix)
-1 tsp baking powder
-1 cup shredded cheese- I use goat cheddar. You can simply make this dairy free with a dairy free cheese alternative!
-3/4 cup Almond Milk (or your choice of milk)
‚Äî
‚Ä¢Saut√© 1 lb breakfast sausage & finely chopped broccoli florets in avocado oil until sausage is fully cooked 
‚Ä¢In a mixing bowl, add 1 cup gluten free flour, 
1 tsp baking powder, & mix together. 
‚Ä¢Then add 1 cup shredded cheese. Mix all together.
‚Ä¢Add and mix in cooked sausage & broccoli to the dry mix. 
‚Ä¢Add 3/4 cup of Almond Milk. Mix together well.
‚Ä¢Scoop mixture into pre-greased cupcake pan- I use avocado oil spray. 
‚Ä¢Bake for 20-25 minutes at 400 degrees.

Enjoy these!! You can store in the fridge for a few days, or freeze them for when needed! Approved by my toddler‚Äî and my husband and I love them too!

BROWNIE RECIPE ‚ù§Ô∏è
Ingredients:
‚Ä¢ 3/4 cup Coconut Sugar
‚Ä¢ 1/3 cup Raw Organic Cacao Powder
‚Ä¢1/4 cup Coconut Oil (melted)

‚Ä¢ 2 pastured eggs
‚Ä¢ 1 cup almond flour

‚Ä¢ 1/4 tsp sea salt

Instructions
‚Ä¢ Blend melted coconut oil, coconut sugar and vanilla in a bowl.
‚Ä¢ Add in eggs and mix well with a spoon.
‚Ä¢ In a separate bowl combine almond flour, cacao powder, baking powder and salt.
‚Ä¢ Gradually blend into egg mixture.
‚Ä¢ Spread into a greased 9 inch glass pan (I oiled with coconut

Little Life update:
The sun has been shining nearly all Month. I lay like a cat curled in the warm embrace. I notice how different everything is when the sun is out. How sparkly the rivers are. Three black cockatoos soar every afternoon over the forest canopy. 
I Planted a tiny peach tree in the garden 3 years ago and harvested 30 or so juicy sweet peaches üçë this week. 
My best friend rang me to tell me she is falling in love. I love the first moments of love. I live for it. The tales, the excitement, the total ecstasy. I can feel it, experience it just by hearing her through the phone. I have been jogging each day, swimming in the river every second. I‚Äôm trying to figure out a way to also include yoga and meditation into my daily practice again. Sometimes I find it hard to blend family life and one‚Äôs self. It‚Äôs as if I‚Äôm so immersed in one, I completely neglected the other and vice versa. 
Does the mother exist within one‚Äôs self,?
Or is one‚Äôs self seperate to the mother ?
This is something I ask frequently at the moment.
We had to let our rooster go because he kept attacking Zu, but than our friends gave us a new rooster and he is so cuddly and nice.
I find life works better when I just let go. 
My love for flowers keeps deepening and my
plant allies all over this beautiful planet just keep paving the way. Spring smells so good everywhere. 
Multitasking is such a disservice to me, but I keep doing it, how do I stop ? 
My Dad always said ‚Äòyou make your own fun‚Äô and it really is true. 
I‚Äôm learning to re write the word bored and replace it with peace. 
Nothing feels better than a really deep drawn out orgasm.

How much happier would we be if we spent more time moving with the force of life? The Issue üò≠: 
There‚Äôs SO MUCH more content to learn in uni than compared to high-school üìö
Furthermore, lecturers are often experts in their field, with years and years of experience, and when they get excited about what they‚Äôre teaching, they may go way way overboard, and share more than you need to know for your exams.

The Solution ‚ú®: 
Focus on high-yield content. This is the content that will get you the most marks on your exam & assignments, and thus is the best use of your time.

You can find this through the learning objectives (usually at the start of each lecture or in your study guide) or by doing practice exams (as often the same questions/topics are repeated). üìù

An effective method I used was to turn each dot-point in the learning objectives into a question, then look through the lecture slides and other materials to answer the question, rather than reading every single page in the textbook or slides. ‚úÖ‚úÖ

The Hack: Cut your meetings 5-10min short, and use this time to send out a follow up email with actions! üìß 

Let‚Äôs face it. 
Most meetings go for longer than they should. By making your meetings shorter, you‚Äôll be forced to get to the point, and more likely to keep people‚Äôs attention, already improving the productiveness of the meeting (and gaining you brownie points with your coworkers for giving them time back) ü§ùüèΩ
¬†
But the real money-step of this hack comes from the follow up email. By sending this out IMMEDIATELY, you‚Äôre more likely to capture all the important points and it gives your coworkers more time to start working on what they were delegated. üèÜ‚è∞
¬†
In this email include:
üìß Summary of what was discussed
üìß Decisions made
üìß Next steps (and for each next step, WHO is responsible for, and WHEN it should be completed by)

The most IMPORTANT step in exam revision ‚úÖüíØüß†üë©üèº‚Äçüéì
-
WHAT IS TIMED PRACTICE? ‚è∞ 
This is where you do practice exams under full exam conditions (eg without notes, complete silence, reading time if applicable and no breaks).

This is a MUST do when preparing for exams because: 
üìï It helps you learn how to APPLY the knowledge. You could memorise the whole textbook and still do poorly on the exam if you don‚Äôt learn how to respond to questions the way examiners want you to. 
This is why so many students often complain that they get questions on the exams that they weren‚Äôt prepared for or have never seen before.
Exam questions often don‚Äôt ask you to just regurgitate definitions word for word, instead they will present a real world example (and likely a new one every time) to see if you can apply your knowledge to solve the problem! 
By doing practice questions and comparing your exams to the marking scheme, you will develop this skill quickly, and be prepared for ANY question you could get. 

üìï It helps you perfect your exam technique. By replicating the exam conditions, you will develop your own rhythm in terms of what you do during reading time, how long you spend on each questions, what you do for questions you don‚Äôt know etc. 
This is a skill itself, entirely seperate from knowing the content, that needs to be developed. 

üìï It giving you an idea of how much time you have & how quick you need to be!! Exams can be long, and being able to pace yourself and stay focused for the entire duration is something that also needs to be developed with practice. 
-

-
The Hack: SPACED REPETITION üìÜ
This is a highly effective revision technique where you review content at regular, increasing intervals. 

For example: 
Say you learn something in class that day.
You would then review the content‚Ä¶ 
‚Äî> when you get home from school 
‚Äî> again that weekend 
‚Äî> the weekend after 
‚Äî> in a fortnight 
‚Äî> in a month 
‚Äî> in 3 months.

To take it one step further and make it even MORE effective, you should try to review using Active Recall, especially Practice Questions (eg from the textbook, past year papers). 

This will help you start perfecting your exam technique EARLY, help you commit the information to long-term memory, and understand the content on a deeper level.

So that when it comes to exam season, you won‚Äôt even NEED to revise because you‚Äôll know everything!! ‚úÖüèÜüíØ

-
1Ô∏è‚É£ Be willing to give everything a go üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è- if you haven‚Äôt done it before or unsure, don‚Äôt be scared to ask for help! Tell your supervisor that you‚Äôll give it your best shot, but may need to be supervised or taught. 

A ‚Äúcan-do‚Äù attitude and an eagerness to learn is one of the best qualities to have. I constantly remind myself that I grow the most when I‚Äôm pushed out of my comfort zone, so the feeling of discomfort is actually something that I need to embrace. 

NOTE: this only refers to things that are inside the scope of your role & will help you develop. Be more cautious about saying yes to ‚Äúbusy work‚Äù just because your supervisor doesn‚Äôt want to do it.
.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Close the Loop üîÅ- at the end of every meeting or conversation, report back what you understood as actions you need to do & by when. Then, as you complete those actions, report back to inform the person they are done & any other information that might be useful (eg if doing research, what the main findings were. If reaching out to someone, what their response was).

Similarly, if you need help with something/are stuck, or there is something blocking your progress, let them know too (eg ‚Äúthe contact is away on leave and will be back Monday, which is when I will follow up again‚Äù).

Don‚Äôt wait for them to have to chase you to figure out that the task has been done or has been held up.

Closing the loop helps build trust. It lets your supervisor know that you are reliable and they can delegate important tasks to you.

Getting Straight As is way easier than you think ‚¨áÔ∏è‚úÖüíØüë©üèΩ‚Äçüéì
-
HOW TO STUDY EFFECTIVELY üèÜ:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Use Active Study Methods - these are study methods that force you to engage with the content, doing some sort of physical or mental process. ü§ì 

It leads to greater retention of info, understanding, and ability to apply theory! 
It also means that you can learn SO MUCH MORE in MUCH LESS time. ‚úÖ
.
Examples include:
üß† Active Recall (e.g. Flashcards, Blurting, Application Questions)
üß† Mind-Maps & Drawing Diagrams 
üß† Teaching The Material to Others 
üß† Loci Method 
üß† Practice Exams 
.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Eliminate Distractions & Stay Focused - make sure you‚Äôre thinking only about the work in front of you to maximise retention. My favourite ways to do this are:
üíØ Study Timelapse 
üíØ Lofi-Beats & noise cancelling headphones 
üíØ Quiet, low-stimulus environment (e.g. library, dedicated study room) 
üíØ Chew gum (it actually works!)
üíØ App Blockers/Downtime settings on your phone 
.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Plan Your Sessions - by planning your study sessions out before you start, you will be able to prioritise what needs to be done, stay on track, and even get additional benefits without more time studying!
.
To make sure your study session is the best it can be: 
‚è∞ Use time-blocking (allocate a set amount of time for each activity, to create a sense of urgency. Otherwise it will expand to fill the whole time)
‚è∞ Start with a quick-win (easy subject or small homework task)to get the dopamine flowing; then move onto your most challenging topic whilst energy levels & focus is still high 
‚è∞ Interleave your subjects by studying smaller blocks of multiple subjects rather than 1 big block of one subject (e.g. 1 hour each of Math, Science, English rather than 3 hours of Math). This will help you remember MORE and perform better on exams, as proven by research üëèüèΩ

Flew to the land down under few days ago and I finally got to see Canberra. I must say this beautiful city is more quiet and laidback as compared to the vibrant and busy Sydney.

With many things in mind, visiting the National Gallery of Australia is on the top our list. Inside it we saw a lot of amazing masterpieces, but what struck me the most is James Turrell's 'Within without' Skyspace, a viewing chamber (or a "stupa") highlighted by turquoise water that surrounds it. This work shows the way we percieve the sky depending on the time of the day. They say it is at its most dramatic and complex form during dawn and dusk, marking the transition between day and night. Truly a remarkable work of art where nature, art, and architecture meet!

Excited to share more snaps and stories from the many things we saw and learned about this city. Big thanks to my travel partner @bigskynationph for keeping us connected everywhere we go with their travel wi-fi!

Shot with @sonyphinc #Alpha7III, 16-35mm f/4.

Join us in an exclusive behind the scenes tour and discover the stories behind the extraordinary heritage-listed landmark and Sydney‚Äôs longest-serving power station at White Bay. 

The tour will include never-before-seen areas of White Bay Power Station, including the vast and cathedral-like Boiler House and Turbine Hall, as well as some hidden spaces not open to the general public. In addition, you will be able to see remarkably intact equipment and machinery and learn about the last remaining example of a coal-fired harbourside industrial complex in NSW.

Developed by Museums of History NSW as part of the Sydney Open Series in partnership with Placemaking NSW and the Biennale of Sydney, White Bay will once again energise Sydney as part of the 2024 Biennale of Sydney. 

Places are extremely limited for this exclusive free offer, see our link in bio to book now. 

Photo ¬© CBRE

Leading Australian architecture and design practice Gray Puksand has converted a heritage warehouse in Sydney‚Äôs CBD into a creative studio.
 
A series of internal arches reference how the building was once three buildings, now combined. Other reminders of an earlier era include a narrow horse cartway to the back courtyard now occupied by three popular small bars that enliven Sydney‚Äôs hidden ‚Äòcreative precinct‚Äô.
 
Gray Puksand invites the community, especially families and children, to experience virtual reality in architecture and the opportunity to create their own ‚Äòmood boards‚Äô with informal instruction by Gray Puksand designers at Sydney Open.
 
Learn more through the link in our bio
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/gray-puksands-sydney-studio/
 
#SydneyOpen2023 @graypuksand
 
Photograph courtesy Gray Puksand

Built in 1935, St Stephen‚Äôs Uniting Church was designed in the interwar Gothic style by architects John Reid and Finlay Munro junior.
 
The church features Australian materials and work by local craftspeople and designers, including timber panelling in polished Queensland maple, plaster ceilings inspired by the English Perpendicular Gothic style, and leadlight windows by the prolific artist Norman St Clair Carter.
 
Visitors at Sydney Open will be able to walk around the building and get up close to the stained-glass windows designed by Carter.
 
Learn more through the link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/st-stephens-uniting-church/
 
#SydneyOpen2023
 
Photo ¬© Kerry Myers

Australian at heart, with international studios and a global outlook, BVN embraces advancements in technology and makes space for the exploration of new ideas.
 
BVN designed its workspace and design studio to be immersive, with 3D printing robots, model makers, a VR (virtual reality) space and design workshop areas.
 
This Sunday, experience immersive VR with the BVN visualisation team and join BVN model maker Barry Cantor at the model-making station for kids. Learn mor through the link in our bio
 
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/bvn-architecture-sydney-studio/
 
#SydneyOpen2023 @bvnarchitecture 
 
Photo ¬© Josh Robenstone

The Garrison Church, is a unique heritage-listed complex that is also one of the earliest extant ecclesiastical buildings in the state, and the hall is considered a rare and unique surviving example of a parochial school built in the 1840s.
 
The Gothic Revival church and hall were completed in stages between 1840 and 1878. Architect Henry Ginn designed the first stage of the church building, which was constructed from locally quarried sandstone and completed in 1846.
 
Explore the Garrison‚Äôs unique history and architectural beauty on a tour led by members of the church community at Sydney Open. Link in our bio
https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/garrison-church/
 
#SydneyOpen2023 @churchhillsyd 
 
Photo ¬© Joseph Koh courtesy of the Garrison Church

Can you believe we are just five days out from Sydney Open?!
 
Be sure to visit our Plan Your Day page on the Sydney Open website. Get access to the Sydney Open digital map, plan your talk and tour times, use one of our pre-planned trails to optimise your walking routes, and check out the variety of food and beverages options you will have access to at Sydney Open.
 
Link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/plan-your-day/
 
#SydneyOpen2023

The Nightingale Building ‚Äì today known as the Nightingale Wing of Sydney Hospital ‚Äì was the site of the first nursing school in Australia. On the request of colonial politician Henry Parkes, British nurse Florence Nightingale sent Lucy Osburn and five other nurses to NSW to establish the school of nursing.
 
Architect Thomas Rowe designed the sandstone and polychrome-brick Gothic Revival building with Nightingale‚Äôs input.
 
Visitors on Sydney Open will see the Lucy Osburn-Nightingale Museum, which has a collection of medical equipment, records, implements and pathology that provides a look into the history of nursing and medicine in Australia from 1788.
 
Learn more about the Nightingale Wing through the link in our bio https://www.sydneyopen.com.au/program/building/nightingale-wing-sydney-hospital/
 
#SydneyOpen2023
 
Photo ¬© Katrina James for MHNSW

Built for funeral trains running between Sydney and the Rookwood Necropolis, Mortuary Station is the only surviving example of purpose-built Victorian railway funerary architecture in Australia.
 
Opened in 1869, Mortuary Station was the terminus for a funeral train service that transported the deceased, mourners, clergymen and visitors to Rookwood Cemetery.
 
Join the hourly tours at Sydney Open as a Transport for NSW heritage specialist talks about the history of Mortuary Station and the site.‚ÄØ

üòû This is difficult for me to write. Last week I stepped outside my comfort zone and shared a very personal goal of mine to have my book make the New York Times Best Seller list. üò± The list isn‚Äôt released until this Sunday but my editor at NatGeo said publishers find out a few days early and she would call me right away. üíõ I want to make it clear that above all, I‚Äôm extremely proud of my book and don‚Äôt want this to cast any sort of shadow over the past 4 years that were nothing but a positive experience of writing and creating this treasure for families all around the world. üåé The quality of my hard work is definitely more important than the accolade of New York Times Best Seller. But I think, if I were to try my best to explain why I‚Äôm feeling so sad and even slightly embarrassed it‚Äôs because 2 things: I‚Äôve never wanted anything like this for myself. I‚Äôm going to keep my head up and focus on the positive. There‚Äôs still chance I may make the list in future weeks so I‚Äôll keep trying my best. Positive reviews of my book on Amazon and Goodreads help so much. ‚≠êÔ∏è I want you to know that I screenshot your thoughtful reviews and every time you share my book on Instagram in such cute creative ways and add it to a journal I‚Äôve been keeping of this book publishing journey. SOMETHING GREATER
For those who have lost something this week; an opportunity, a relationship, a belief, a job, faith or motivation...your next season is going to be greater!
-
What no longer serves you will eventually be cut, pruned or trimmed away from your life.
-
This hurts in the moment. That moment can last from minutes to months. And that‚Äôs entirely upto you. Own it, experience it, feel it.
-
Then there becomes a time when new life starts growing from the very area of your life that has been removed. New life that holds the promise of new opportunities, new memories, new relationships, new jobs and a renewed faith and motivation.
-
A word for anyone going through this right now...your next season is going to take further than your last one.
-
God never removes unless there is something far greater He has planned for our next season. The pruning is just the first step of new opportunities!
-
Believe in the hope of tomorrow, while you experience whole-heartedly and learn from today.
-
Your next season is going to be greater than your last. Have faith in knowing God will replace.

üìåWhy is joint mobility important? (Read bellow‚¨áÔ∏è) Video is speed up 3x for reels let me know in the comments if you prefer this format or would like to see normal speed as a carrousel format.üé• 
 
The way I see it, ‚ÄúMobility‚Äù Is kind of like a collaboration effort between our muscles and joints.
 
When our joint mobility is limited, we might be missing out on opportunities to be stronger, more athletic, and more efficient.
 
The ability to move our joints through their full range helps our muscles work more optimally, and when our muscles can do their work, they can also get stronger and help keep our joints healthy in return.
 
üí™üèºHaving a good balance between strength and joint mobility helps distribute the stress more evenly through the body instead of overstressing our joints (back, hips, knees, ankles, etc.).
 
üö™Our joints are kind of like the hinges to a door; if that door remains unopened for long periods in addition to environmental decay, the hinges in that door will start creaking and get rusty overtime. In our case, it will be arthritis, bursitis, inflammation, and things like that.
 
So you see, just as with the door example, maintenance and movement were keys to extending the life and function of it, in our case, MAINTENANCE and MOVEMENT are also keys to a BETTER QUALITY OF LIFE.üôåüèº

STAY ACTIVE!üí™üèº

Some days there is no plan. I just wanted to move a little so I did and it ended up being a light weight mobility exploration day.

Energy levels where on the low with some #Adenomyosis aches and pains in the mix. I wasn‚Äôt looking to exhaust myself in a long workout and risk feeling super tired afterwards. So I just moved for a bit, worked on some areas that I wanted to target and moved on with the rest of my day.

At the end I was feeling accomplished and still had energy to do other things the rest of the day. 

The are days I push and days I back down, IS MY BALANCE. As long as I am making positive progress is a win for me. I just try my best to be consistent with it.

Don‚Äôt compare your journey with anyone else‚Äôs. 

FIND YOUR BALANCE ü§úüèºü§õüèº

Setelah 8 tahun, Alhamdulillah gue akan kembali ke Jepang tapi kali ini dengan sebuah misi yang masyaAllah banget.

This month marks 20 years since one of the most impactful moments of my life when a shark took my arm while on a surfing off the coast of Kauai, my birth place. Many people could look at the incident back in 2003 as a major setback for me, but God had so much in store for the future! ü§ôüèº

It‚Äôs absolutely wild to think how my life started and where it is now and all the amazing yet challenging things in between. I didn‚Äôt wake up in the hospital thinking I was invincible and was gonna get back to surfing. After getting a hint of inspiration,¬†¬†I had to dream it up, flip my mindset and be willing to do what I had not seen anyone else do.¬†¬†This was a challenge to live in faith. And I am so glad I was willing to try and give it my best shot! üôèüèº Now I get to surf with my two eldest sons Tobias and Wesley and my hubby! I get to enjoy these sweet moments with my newborn daughter. There is so much to be grateful for, and these past 20 years have been filled with incredible moments and huge overcoming seasons. üíõ

When you have your ‚ÄúShark Attack‚Äù moments in life. I hope you‚Äôre willing to try, and give life your best shot! You too CAN OVERCOME!

Changing your mindset is free. Doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs an easy or fast fix. It‚Äôs up to you to be honest with yourself and start working on it. 
It‚Äôs wild to me that some people still think surfing with one arm is not possible. I am a living example and there are soooo many other amazing adaptive athletes and people out there doing incredible things that people perceive as impossible. 
What is it about some who are willing to adapt and make the most of what they‚Äôve got? 
MINDSET. It may take time to switch it up and we may have to be forever workin at it. But I promise you, that you won‚Äôt regret continually flipping your mind to be more grateful, more optimistic, more of what and how can can I do this life to the best of my abilities‚Ä¶ More of - I don‚Äôt need easy I just need possible. üß†‚ú®üí™üèΩ Hope this pushes you today and onward to adapt in your life. YOU CAN. 

Comment what‚Äôs helped you to have a healthier mindset?! üëáüèΩ let‚Äôs spread the ‚ù§Ô∏è

Your encouragement to make the most of each day! I know some day are tough.. But I hope this is a reminder to keep your attitude in check with gratitude. Let‚Äôs‚Ä¶ Love well. Serve well. Look for what we are grateful for every day!

Do yall struggle with motivation? 
Getting a workout in as mom can be a beast! But what I be found that works for me is adjusting my expectations. 
I‚Äôve lowered my expectations to know that I will be interrupted and I may loose my flow here and there. 

Buttt in exchange, I invite my children into the space! They get to see mom taking care of herself and getting filled in a way. And they move too! We play a lot in the yard as well.
I really like having strength and it satisfies a need that I have. And it helps me to be more efficient in motherhood and in surfing! 
Motivation may come and go but having your ‚Äúwhy‚Äù can help carry you through the years. Also making sure your eating enough and getting proper rest so that you can have energy to stay motivated at whatever it me be that you do! 

Also when it comes to fitness and movement you do not need a fancy gym. Just a bit of motivation and creativity. There is so much free info online now days or get hiking in nature!

When you bring children into the world, you start to see things in a whole new perspective. ‚ú® You begin to get a glimpse of what it is to love someone as our Father in heaven loves, you start to experience joy that can only come from seeing your little one smile for the first time, the joy and contentment that rushes on you when they snuggle and fall asleep on you, or when they get older, the sense of pride you get when they share out of their own will, or help their brother get up after a gnarly wipeout.
Children are some of the most cherished blessings in our lives. I love seeing @Everylifeco encouraging families and moms-to-be, to choose a path that honors life, and protects these little miracles! I love seeing their message that encourages married couples to make more babies! üë∂ üòç‚ù§Ô∏è

thrilled to announce the fourth iteration of aureta x @bienendavis - to collaborate with people i love and respect has been one of life‚Äôs greatest joys - bienen davis founded in new york city in 1931, and included in the permanent collection of metropolitan museum of art, merged american design with Italian craftsmanship and soon found their bags on the sets of movies and television shows, adorning the arms of some of hollywood‚Äôs most iconic stars - fast forward 90 years to our fourth collaboration and another american treasure enters the conversation - artist @rayhowlett was the inspiration for my latest capsule collection with the brand - in the words of meredith german, creative director of BD: 

‚ÄúRay Howlett (born 1940) is an American artist primarily associated with the light and space movement. He is known as one of the pioneers of infinity light sculptures.
Howlett‚Äôs sculptures are hand ground glass geometric sculptural shapes of coated glass and electric light that create an abstract optical space larger than the piece itself, what he calls an ‚Äúoptically expanding space‚Äù. In his structural forms, illuminated graphic images appear to be floating within transparent sculptures. The internal composition and colors shift and change as the viewer moves around it using highly reflective thin-film coatings to make color shift with different angles of view. The color is dichroism.
Aureta met Ray in LA in 2018 and has been continuously inspired by his innovative body of work, becoming a leading patron of his art in hopes of maintaining his brilliant craft for generations to come.
The Ray Howlett X Aureta collaboration for Bienen Davis consists of The Kit Bracelet Bag and The R√©gine Minaudiere hand crafted in Italy and embellished with over 5,000 Swarovski crystals to reflect Ray‚Äôs incredible vision‚Äù link in bio

TOMORROW our film INHERITANCE (@inheritance_thefilm) will have a second showing at Slamdance Film Festival in Park City, Utah.

INHERITANCE tells the story of an often overlooked America and a family caught in the grips of intergenerational trauma and addiction. Filmed over 11 years in one Appalachian town the film follows a boy as he grows up from age 12 to 18 surrounded by chaos, addiction and powerful love.

We want the film to fuel conversations, provide space for empathy and break stigmas around substance abuse and mental health.

We are so appreciative to our Editor Curtis Whitear (@curtiswhitear), our Composer Kyle Scott Wilson (@kyle_scott_wilson) and our Executive Producers Morgan Pehme and Daniel DiMauro (@dan__dimauro), Sam Cullman, Erik (@e1heyer) and Leslie Heyer, and Dave A. Liu (@liucrative). 

If you would like to support our film:

JOIN US: at Slamdance! INHERITANCE is in competition for a Grand Jury Award so please come out and support us! 

FOLLOW US: keep apprised of our future showings, sign up for our email list on our website (www.inheritancethefilm.com) and follow us here on Instagram @inheritance_thefilm

SHARE: spread the word and share this post and our mission. Let‚Äôs build a more compassionate world, one story at a time

SCREENING INFORMATION:
Slamdance Film Festival in Park City, Utah
Tuesday, Jan. 23rd, 2024 at 9:15 p.m. MST at The Yarrow - Theater B

Tickets can be purchased at the link in our bio. 

For viewers interested in the virtual showings, please visit slamdancechannel.com, or the link in our bio under ‚ÄúVIRTUAL TICKET.‚Äù

FROM MY ARCHIVE | Monhegan Island Post 05 (final):: I got my start at @natgeo in 1999 as a photo intern when I did my first story for the magazine. I was asked if I had an idea for a project and I proposed Monhegan ‚Äì a small island 10 miles off the coast of Maine. I am from New England and had lived on the Maine coast as a young adult. I had always been curious about the 2 mile long and ¬Ω mile wide island. In the summers the place overflows with tourists, but the year round population is only about 60-70. The islanders‚Äô de facto fishing territory became the Monhegan Lobster Conservation Area in 1996 with a limited season starting in October. The island‚Äôs windswept landscape, quirky community and the dramatic cliffs have inspired artists like Robert Henri, George Bellows, Rockwell Kent, Edward Hopper, Lynn Mapp Drexler and three generations of the Wyeth family to name a few. ‚Å†
‚Å†
The community took me in and sometimes chewed me up. My time and experiences there changed and shaped my life in profound and beautiful ways that continue to impact me almost 25 years later; working with photo editor Susan Welchman who took me under her wing and has been my mentor and dear friend since and within days of arriving to the island, I also met one of my best friends @tralice_pooltoyphotos ‚Å†
‚Å†
Image 01 ‚Å†
Morning fog lifts off the meadow behind the Josiah Starling house, the oldest house on the island, built in 1784.‚Å†
‚Å†
Image 02‚Å†
The island gardener works on the flower beds around the Island Inn.‚Å†
‚Å†
Image 03‚Å†
Lobsterman Bryan Hitchcock‚Å†
‚Å†
Image 04‚Å†
Tulips in the moonlight‚Å†
‚Å†

10 years ago today I bought my first camera. 
I was 24 at the time, finishing my second degree in Biotechnologies. 
Didn‚Äôt know anything about photography, didn‚Äôt have any connection or any real reason to start, out of the simple, uncontrollable need to express myself. 
I started so many things trying to find my way, always ending into dropping the latest idea after some months. 
Photography hit me like a bolt and never left me. 
Of all the things I heard during these 10 years, the most important one that kept pushing me in improving over and over again, was probably this: ‚Äúyou can‚Äôt‚Äù.
You can‚Äôt live with photography, you can don‚Äôt it without connections, you can‚Äôt work without expensive gear, you can‚Äôt make it without a specific degree, you can‚Äôt work with this ‚Äústyle‚Äù, you can‚Äôt do it because you‚Äôre not good enough. 
After 10 years at 34 years old, after years of absolute dedication and an insane will to improve still pumping in my veins, I‚Äôm living with photography the best life I could have imagined. 
I‚Äôm so grateful to all the people that believed in me and helped me trough this process; of course believing in yourself is the most important part, but without all the persons I met, I don‚Äôt know if I would have been able to make it trough the hardest times. 
This is just a small selection of some fav pictures shot during these years. 
I didn‚Äôt include the FaceTime series, even tho is probably one of the biggest steps for me in terms of improving my vision. 
Thanks to all the people involved, hope we‚Äôre gonna be able to meet in person soon again, to create, have fun and keep inspiring each other. 
If you have any question about the making of any particular photo, or the process in general, I‚Äôd love to talk about it here in comments.

Hey üëãüèº It‚Äôs me. I know there‚Äôs a lot of new faces around here so I thought I‚Äôd do a little ‚ÄòTen Random Facts About Me‚Äô: 

1) I am 31. Born in Red Deer, Alberta. I‚Äôve been here my entire life and don‚Äôt think I ever move. My husband is stuck here now üè° 
2) I have both my Social Work and Education degree. I‚Äôve been working in schools for 14 years now. Currently as a substitute teacher. My second SW practicum placement was in an alternative school, and I just fell in love with it. 
3) Before dogs I raised bunnies. My last bunny was 7 years ago, Peanut. He lived in my school office. The students loved him! 
4) I have travelled to 25 countries: Canada, US, Mexico, Nicaragua, Chile, Peru , Bolivia, Argentina, Italy, France, Spain, Czech, Greece, Vatican City, Iceland, Sweden, Ireland, Switzerland, Indonesia, Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam, Laos, Tanzania, and Egypt. Next up is Scotland!

5) I have naturally very curly hair but haven‚Äôt worn it that way in 4 years. My husband hasn‚Äôt even seen it. I wash it every 5-7 days depending and it‚Äôs just easier to straighten and curl it. 
6) I had a MASSIVE Beanie Baby collection, thought they‚Äôd be worth millions and I‚Äôd be able to retire on it. Turns out they ain‚Äôt. 
7) I have 3 sisters, none of us look anything alike and yes we have the same parents üòÖ 
8) I am allergic to horses, cats, and dogs that shed. Growing up I always wanted to be a veterinarian, but allergies would‚Äôve got in the way of that haha. They never went away. 
9) I had a paper route growing up. I did the same route every day for 7 years. Grade 3-10. After all those years of delivering papers we don‚Äôt have a single photo to show for it. I was out there in all sorts of weather. On my bike in the summer or head to toe in my snow suit. It was outside the city and driveways were long and far apart. 
10) I fear the ocean and drowning. I hate waves. Along with avalanches. These fears keep me from surfing along with backcountry skiing. I also hate small spaces. Claustrophobia is a real thing ü´£

As a traveler it can be hard to tell whether or not an attraction or activity is harmful to any animals, or we may be too caught up in the excitement of the experience to recognize the reality of what indeed is happening. 

Here are a few things you can ask yourself to avoid cruel attractions: 
1) Are the wild animals kept in cages that do not have all of the following: food, clean water, shelter, ample space, privacy and enrichment?
2) Are animals forced to perform tricks in shows?
3) Are you able to ride, touch, hold, walk or swim with wild animals? 
4) Does the tourist attraction sell parts of products from wild animals? 
5) Does the tour company chase or lure wild animals closer with food or bring people too close to wild animals so they can see them better?

 If you answered yes to any of these, it is not an animal-friendly attraction. Also if the attraction claims to have rescued the wild animals under their care, you can use @worldanimalprotectioncanada‚Äôs checklist, to determine if it is a genuine sanctuary.

A couple of points pulled from the checklist are:
1) Does not take animals from the wild (unless they are injured) or breed animals 
2) Does not keep wild animals to make a profit
3) Keeps animals in enclosures that closely resemble their natural habitat and give them enough space and opportunities to move and behave naturally
4) Have veterinarians available at any hour to treat the animals that become sick or hurt. 

 I have linked the checklist in my bio, along with in my stories if you‚Äôre wanting to read more. 

You can join the movement by following @worldanimalprotectioncanada, and by sharing this message, which will help us keep wildlife in the wild and end cruel wildlife entertainment‚Äô ‚ú®

Three $20,000 fellowships will be awarded by @amplifierart to photographers and photo-based artists to work on projects addressing threats to democratic institutions in the US in the lead up to the 2024 election. We are looking for photographers to go beyond the minimum of wrapping up a quick photo essay for publication. Fellows will need to be open to collaboration and able to pivot to add layers throughout the year to address the dynamic landscape of 2024. This is an incredible opportunity to work with our advisors and partner orgs (and myself!) to make a real impact! 

‚ÄúAs threats to our democracy continue to evolve, so must we! In the spirit of that evolution, we are launching the Amplifier Democracy Fellowship! Link in header! Returning to our roots in photojournalism and community storytelling, we are merging our extensive networks in editorial journalism with insights from museum and art institution advisors, and building on a foundation of advising from leaders in nonprofits dedicated to safeguarding voting rights and other foundational elements of democracy. With the support of this incredible team, we are committing to working with at least 3 photographers and photo-based artists in 2024. Each fellow will be awarded $20,000 for the year. We aim to expand this fellowship with a kickstarter in February to launch additional rapid response grants and assignments throughout the year, showcasing work across new platforms, major media networks, and through our tried and true public interventions. 

Though nonpartisan, this project is not about simply bearing witness. Fellows will be expected to wield lenses and light, composition and concept, as tools of transformation. We are not here to merely observe democracy‚Äôs trials from the sidelines, but to engage deeply, to utilize our art to reinforce and protect the pillars of our democracy from decay and outright attack. There is no application fee! >>> www.amplifierfellows.org

Kenya is establishing a vital breeding population of 21 EASTERN BLACK RHINOS rhinos at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century. Moving a black rhino, an animal weighing over a ton, is a Herculean challenge fraught with danger at every turn. It begins with the risky task of sedating the massive creature, a procedure that requires precision and caution to ensure both the rhino‚Äôs safety and that of the vets and handlers. Once subdued, the real test begins as the sedated rhino must be carefully revived and maneuvered into a sturdy crate, a task made all the more daunting by the animal‚Äôs immense size and strength. Every step of this delicate operation underscores the inherent risks involved. Watch the sheer force of these creatures and imagine doing it over 21 times over the course of 2 weeks. The teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication. In an ideal world, we wouldn‚Äôt have to go through these extreme measures but with approximately 80% of the world‚Äôs remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya‚Äôs efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures.

I want to sincerely thank all the people you see here and their partners and encourage you to follow @nature_africa @nature_org @loisaba_conservancy @kenyawildlifeservice @olpejeta @sandiegozoo @spaceforgiants @earthrangertech @elewanacollection @lewaconservancy @dr_mathew_mutinda_ @nikonusa

I am humbled to share another remarkable conservation story from Kenya: the resurgence of eastern black rhinos from the brink of extinction. In a pivotal moment, Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for these creatures, establishing a vital breeding population at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century mainly due to poaching and long ago,  trophy hunting. This first image shows the moment a rhino was resuscitated after it stopped breathing and quickly released. The arduous tasks of tracking, darting, and relocating 21 of these critically endangered giants, each weighing over a ton, posed formidable challenges, yet the teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication. Their efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures. The final image shows the skull of the last rhino poached in the 1970s resting beneath a celestial canopy, symbolizing this hopeful shift as Kenya now stands  as a nation that is expanding habitat and bolstering rhino populations. With approximately 80% of the world's remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya is safeguarding endangered populations for future generations. 

I want to sincerely thank all the partners and encourage you to follow @nature_africa @nature_org @loisaba_conservancy  @kenyawildlifeservice  @olpejeta @sandiegozoo @spaceforgiants  @elewanacollection @lewaconservancy

An international team of scientists and conservationists achieved a groundbreaking milestone in their mission to save northern white rhinos from extinction. They successfully conducted an in vitro embryo transplant in a southern white rhino, resulting in a pregnancy‚Äîa crucial proof of concept. However, the joy was short-lived as unforeseen tragedy struck due to heavy rainfall and flooding, unearthing Clostridia bacteria spores and leading to a devastating infection that claimed both the mother, Curra, and the 70 day old fetus.

Despite this profound loss, the team remains determined, having worked tirelessly for years to create 30 embryos with Avantea lab. Follow along on the extraordinary journey of these incredible people and follow @biorescue_project, @safariparkdvurkralove, @leibnizizw, @olpejeta, #avantea, and @kenyawildlifeservice as we share more news.

This awe-inspiring creature was a 70-day-old rhinoceros fetus, an embodiment of perfection in its miniature form. While a typical southern white rhino can tip the scales between 3,080 and 7,920 pounds and 11-15 feet, this little one only reached a delicate 6.4 inches. His life was cut short when his surrogate mother, Curra, a southern white rhino, succumbed to an unforeseen tragedy triggered by heavy rainfall and flooding that unearthed Clostridia bacteria spores, leading to a swift and devastating infection.

The news of Curra's demise struck the team with profound grief. These dedicated individuals have been tirelessly working for years to rescue the northern white rhinos from the brink of extinction. Their journey brought them to Kenya, where they were on the verge of confirming the success of creating the world's first rhino pregnancy through embryo transfer at the Ol Pejeta Conservancy. In a bittersweet twist of fate, the entire team received word of the successful pregnancy by implantation of an embryo using in vitro fertilization (IVF). However, this moment of joy was tinged with the somber acknowledgment of the journey's cost. The next pivotal step is to transfer northern white rhino embryos into a surrogate mother.

I'll be sharing more of this extraordinary story in the coming weeks.  Stay connected with the @biorescue_project, @safariparkdvurkralove, @leibnizizw, @olpejeta, #avantea, and @kenyawildlifeservice for more insights into this pivotal moment for northern white rhinos.

From playful antics to tender moments, elephants flow with emotion. While the calves at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) have traumatic pasts, the love and companionship of the other elephants and the dedicated keepers help them grow and heal.

Looking back at my pregnancy journey - started taking these on week 20 (since there were no point before that because you could barely tell I was pregnant) and last one was taken on week 39 - and I gave birth 2 days after.

I think the pregnancy started off really tough emotionally, but as soon as we heard his little heartbeats for the first time and knew he was doing good in there - I could finally start enjoying my pregnancy. I type this 1st log entry from Barcelona - ~ 2.000 Km into our 8.000 #iberitron road trip

Short summary how things went down till now:
* Austria is HPC heaven - except in Villach (see the drama in @audidriven story iberitron 02)
* Italy is getting better - although after our 3rd visit to @ionity.official Portogruaro - this location is definitely a dump (stinking trash containers next to the chargers, littering, not appealing at all
* @ionity.official France has a serious problem (1st station 4 stalls: 1 of 4 working = 1 broken - where I parked 1st, 2nd working - where I reparked, 3&4 only charging with ~35kW / 2nd station 6 stalls: 2 out of six delivered the full speed (150kW for the e-tron), the other ~35kW. Again lucky as I got the 2nd working one after reparking) Got lucky
* Spain üá™üá∏ - a little to early to tell but was already pleasantly surprised, as proven by this picture. In the middle of nowhere - Figueres - I found this working (!) HPC charger. Biggest challenge was to get the operator app working as it does not accept any of the charging cards
* A general not surprising rule: try to always charge before the night (like in this case) or even better over night as currently in our Barcelona hotel. For me the charging stops are part of the adventure (now locations, new experiences) but apparently my family thinks differently üòÇ. Yesterday we had zero charging stops (‚Äúboring‚Äù for me, enjoyable for family)
.
When we arrive at my moms place near Malaga I will try to do a more detailed day by day posts if desired üòâ

Angkor Wat and park in Siem Reap, Cambodia. This is my second time here and it still feels as mystical as the first time. At the beginning of our tour, our guide overwhelmed us with all the mathematical calculations and engineering ingenuity that went into building Angkor Wat. Certain points of the structure lined up perfectly with the Draco Constellation and the sun positioning at sunset. Although there are educated speculation from experts archeologists saying this dates back about 900 years ago, It‚Äôs all a mystery.

On the other hand, Spiritual channelers have mentioned this to be older than 5000 BC. It‚Äôs a place to activate the pineal gland (third eye) through frequencies, it‚Äôs also an informational point for earth to funnel data to and from other planets/galaxies. It‚Äôs like another access point of information like the great pyramids. The art carvings hold a lot of relations to Hinduism on many of the Angkor Park structures. But personally, I see a lot of psychedelic reflections on some of the temples. They almost look like what I see as the crossover realm between the mind and other outer dimensions. It‚Äôs like the level where you have to overcome the ego before connecting with your higher self. Very interesting place to walk around and wander off into. 

#southeastasia #cambodia #angkorwat #spiritualjourney

Winter in South East Asia, Thailand editionüìç My sister was wondering my whereabouts so this is for her üòÑ I‚Äôm past my posting era days, and a bit rusty but I love hearing from some of you who still see how I‚Äôm doing. I always appreciate your messages and enjoy hearing your side of the world as well. 

My bf and I are currently running away from the cold and enjoying some sun this year. Last winter was so brutal, all we did was shovel snow on top of snow üò∞ This winter we decided to do something different. We‚Äôre exploring the warmer region in Asia üòÑ Something I learned about myself on this trip is that regardless of being Vietnamese blood, the mosquitos will always attack me. I also thought I can handle the tropical heat too but I‚Äôm dying while my Minnesota bf is thriving in the sun ü•µ. Maybe I‚Äôm not who I think I am after all üòÜ

#travelthailand #thailand #KohChang #Asia

üòâ At first I smelled ripped jackfruit but walked by the tree on the way to see the waterfall, but on the way back I saw this massive fully grown jackfruit tree! I‚Äôve seen the smaller trees before but never this large! These huge fruits hang off high branches and can fall on anyone unlucky üôÑ Jackfruit is so delicious and sweet! 

#thailand #jackfruit #solotraveler #hiking

If Saigon is to write a love poem in the form of a coffee shop, this would be it ü•Ä A once historical abandon building, now the hot spot for the kids. In the daytime it looks deserted but at night it becomes alive with local art studios, cafe, music, and mystery. 

If you‚Äôre not familiar, the boutique cafes in Saigon are endless. Each has its own charismatic touch in the best possible way. Vietnam is the second largest coffee exporter in the world, therefore it‚Äôs no surprise that every cafe ‚òïÔ∏è will deliver in strength and caffeine! Vietnam truly runs on coffee.

#saigon #cafe #coffeeculture

Memories in Saigon! üß° It‚Äôs so chaotic here but I appreciate this city so much more than I did before. Maybe a few weeks more, I will probably come out frazzled and rough around the edges looking like weird Barbie üòµ‚Äçüí´ This place definitely spit me out feeling a little tougher üí™ To be honest, I did not enjoy my last visit as an adult. I didn‚Äôt feel much of a connection back then. It‚Äôs funny how we can come to appreciate things that we once overlooked. Traveling again also helps me to appreciate people. Sometimes our environment and people we see often can take away from us, switching up our environment a little can help us enjoy people again. They say the grass is always greener on the other side, but really it‚Äôs just getting away from the same stale energy that was taking and not giving. #vietnamtravel #saigon

Make sure to save this info if you‚Äôre thinking about visiting Vietnam. We‚Äôre in Ben Tre, Vietnam and this has got to be one of the most underrated places we‚Äôve learned about. I hope people keep going to Bali and leave this place for us üòÜ

This town is 2 hrs south of Saigon - which around $40 Grab ride.  The town itself is pretty developed as in roads and sidewalks, but this is where you can relax from the crazy traffic and roads of Saigon. I think Ben Tre fits the criteria of what many people think of Saigon. It‚Äôs a growing city, with no crazy developments, or high rise.  Many restaurants or stores here cater to the locals, so you will get more of an authentic experience. The locals are pretty friendly as long as you are respectful. The kids like to say ‚Äúhello‚Äù to my bf because they want to use their English. They get a good chuckle when he says ‚Äúhi‚Äù in Vietnamese. We usually greet and thanks in the language of the country we‚Äôre in, many folks seem to appreciate it.  The young locals speak English well, older people usually don‚Äôt. 

We did 3 tours here with @mrbikerbentreboattour , Troy found him on TripAdvisor. We highly recommend his tours. After doing our first private boat tour, we came back for another tour of the town, and then rented bikes from one of the eco lodges/homestays. @mrbikerbentreboattour has been extremely punctual and helpful with us. His tours gives you a sample of the local lifestyle and Vietnamese tradition. We‚Äôve got to visit the small canals off the Mekong river, and private roads of the locals. We did not experienced any upsell, pressure to buy, or nonsense stops on the tours. It felt more educational and you can see the aunties and uncles on his team working diligently to make a good impression for us. We really appreciated our stay here. It‚Äôs so walkable around and the local people love coming out after the sun set but that‚Äôs when we are asleep üò¥ #travelvietnam #b·∫øntre

Ben Tre, Vietnam

Last year, I was in total hermit mode. I was so eager to build my homestead, I couldn‚Äôt focus on anything else. I think that is why I am walking everywhere I possibly can in Vietnam. However, today is a biking day! We rented some bikes at an eco homestay through @mrbikerbentreboattour and it was exactly what I needed. It was so much fun  going around the town on our bikes. There were so many fun fruit shops and Sugarcane juice stand. üç∫ We both got a delicious drink off one of the stands for 50 cents and it was absolutely divine! 
Also, I had one of the most amazing Banh Xeo of my life. We found a random farm that also runs a restaurant and they made us the most incredible Banh Xeo.  I‚Äôm already sad to think how much I will miss today ü•≤ #vietnamtravel #bentre

Today we decided to check out a park in Saigon. Creating a little reference point gives us a little mission to embark on and get our steps in üòä This is  always a nice way to discover small gems or see places you would not be able to read or watch about. On our walkie walk, we were able to see the contrast in the city. One of my pics shows the old way of living off a stream (how my parents described their life growing up), and behind it are the new skyscrapers. 

As we walked, we discovered more street foods, mini restaurants, and cafes. I got some sugarcane juice off an auntie from a side stall and then stumbled into a little oasis off a super busy bustling road. It was a little coffee stale with lots of unique and local plants surrounding it. Great place for coffee and plant enthusiasts ü™¥ There were little tables and seats hidden around an array of hanging plants. Later I found out it was a plant shop too! This was a nice little break stop for another refresher. Troy got his iced coffee and so we got to sit amongst all these pretty greenery. Everything is such a contrast in Saigon. You see old vs new everywhere, the crazy busy hustle of traffic, and Vietnamese taking their naps in the mist of all the chaos in the streets. I really enjoy observing üëÄ and wondering how people adapt to the places they live in. 
.

caption:
My Barbie moment at a super pink church in Saigon! It‚Äôs incredibly hot here but I heard it‚Äôs -25 back home, so we‚Äôre not complaining! I‚Äôll take this heat and over stimulated city for the time being üß° 

I thought that crowded places gives me anxiety but what I learned is that the environment and people affect me. Crowded places don‚Äôt give me anxiety, the collective energy of the same things do. Sometimes my environment can feel like a drag. People talking about the same things, focused on career, status, gossip, politics, limited beliefs, problems after problems. And when I‚Äôm around it too much, it sucks the life force out of me, so I retract. Exploring helps me break free from that. Any sort of traveling, mini trips, or taking off on a plane helps me break free from monotony and repetition. Walking in places is also very grounding for me. I‚Äôve noticed that I need a balance of both worlds, the chaotic city and being in nature. When I become extreme in one, I definitely can feel the lack of balance in my overall energy. We are all different and I‚Äôm learning more on how to listen to my personal inner guide. #saigon #vietnam

Anthony Bourdain made a lot of videos  in Vietnam. He definitely created a pathway for international foodies to embrace it‚Äôs unique culture. A lot has changed here in development but some of his recommended stops are still around. This place specializes on one of my favorite dishes, Banh Xeo! Banh Xeo looks like an omelette; but it‚Äôs not, it‚Äôs rice flour, turmeric gives it the yellow color, some people add coconut milk, and beer to the batter making the outer crepe shell crispy.  It‚Äôs a nicely light dish and can make a great appetizer. It‚Äôs often served with a heaping plate of fresh lettuce and herbs. You roll everything up in a big leafy bundle of lettuce and dip it into a sweet tangy fish sauce üòò Then embrace the explosion of crunch and savory flavor in one bite, it‚Äôs so delicious! ü§§ 

My verdict with this place, doesn‚Äôt compare to mom‚Äôs Banh Xeo. However, their version is still delightful but not the best I had üëå It‚Äôs on the lighter side in flavor, maybe good for westerner to train their taste buds. üëÖ #vietnamesefood #saigon

caption: Jan 2024: Ok so we sort of made it out alive crossing the busy streets of Saigon today üòÖ If you‚Äôre someone who easily gets anxiety in crowds where you live, I suggest you travel to Saigon. Because once you come here, I think you‚Äôll be able to handle any chaotic city. Saigon will slap the wimp out in you, it‚Äôs a tough love sort of place. You will have to learn about trusting strangers, I don‚Äôt mean by handing anyone your wallet. I mean if you want to cross the roads, you will have to steadily walk out into traffic and flow with the chaotic rhythm, trust yourself and the drivers that will move around you üòÜ It‚Äôs very mental. ‚ÄúResiliency‚Äù is the vibe of this place.

All I can say is thank you. I‚Äôm honored to see such positive responses to the first announcement reel. This is going to be interesting. I didn‚Äôt know there were so many fans of folk music here! 

This album was tracked live in a small room, which is not the norm in for a studio session. (Either is actually building a pop-up studio in a cabin in the woods). 

There is an undeniable adventure in recording this way. You get what you get, mistakes and all. There lives a certain beauty, and honesty, in these songs because of it. Wear your scars. 

This is the final chorus to Full Moon Fight, the title track to the EP. I hope you enjoy it. I‚Äôve fought a lot in the dark. Big thanks to this band for helping bring it to the light. @eliandwest @mgonigle @forrestliketrees 

Let me know what you think! EP release coming soon. - AM

I‚Äôve never been quite sure what to do with words. Maybe that‚Äôs why I‚Äôve lived my life behind the camera. In an effort to make some sense of this, I‚Äôm walking this project into the light. I sure hope it‚Äôs okay to branch out here. I trust that it is. Storytelling has many forms. I hope it inspires you to tell yours. Full Moon Fight is my first EP (6 tracks) and I‚Äôm preparing the release for fall. Entirely too much information and ramblings to soon follow‚Ä¶ Thanks for listening y‚Äôall! @eliandwest @mgonigle @forrestliketrees @dblay.sounds

How big of a wave will your contributions to SeaLegacy generate on today‚Äôs #GivingTuesday? The ocean‚Äôs impact rushes far beyond the sand, so when you support the sea, you send a ripple of hope throughout the world. This year, thanks to an anonymous donor, your gift to the ocean doubles with every donation matched! 

Every organism on Earth relies on the ocean‚Äì many as a home, but all for its services. To advocate for it, and defend its ability to carry out invaluable interactions, our team works with scientific experts, coastal communities, global leaders, and influential figures to generate waves of change. We and our partners know that our interconnected planet survives and thrives as one. So together, we help establish ocean solutions that compound with every ecological interaction. Just this year, our team:

- Helped expand and announce a Panamanian marine protected area that added 90,000 sq km (~35,000 sq mi) of protected waters in the Banco Volc√°n Area of Managed Resources.
- Shared the ocean‚Äôs impact and encouraged its protection to global audiences with co-founders @paulnicklen and @mitty‚Äôs feature on CNN‚Äôs ‚ÄúCall to Earth‚Äù series.
- Completed a Rapid Assessment Visual Expedition (RAVE) in Chilean Patagonia, where we amplified the importance of maintaining the waters holding the largest continuous kelp forest in the world.
- Released new episodes of our ‚ÄúA Sea of Hope‚Äù series‚Äì capturing and uplifting the realities facing our ocean, while inspiring its protection. Our work was recognized by prestigious peers, and we accepted two finalist nominations at the @jacksonwildorg Media Awards!
- Took over the @UNbiodiversity Instagram to share the importance of the ocean and our unique approach to protecting it through the ‚ÄúRebuilding Life Roadmap.‚Äù
- Amplified the role of South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands to our global community while urging protections that would maintain the Southern Ocean‚Äôs stability.

And so much more! Thanks to you and your donations, we can continue to shape a brighter future for our ocean and every individual who relies on it. Visit the link in our bio to support our work!

Today we have the honor of wishing our co-founder, @paulnicklen, a very happy birthday! To celebrate Paul and his infectious passion for conservation is simple, but to express his immeasurable impact on our organization and its mission is impossible.

Each day, as we work to amplify our ocean‚Äôs stories and restore its health, we do so with Paul‚Äôs reliable voice and commitment to change, helping to steer the ship. While not all have the opportunity to encounter Paul‚Äôs prowess for leadership firsthand, his unreplicable ability to capture and create resonant stories can be experienced much more broadly. Fearlessly exploring every corner of the world, he brings unreachable scenes vividly and candidly to our fingertips, opening the door to worlds that may otherwise go unseen. Paul engages us with charismatic creatures and their realities. His love for the ocean and its wildlife radiates through his work, and, with his artistic voice, proximity becomes negligible, and action is inspired. 

Share in the celebration, and help Paul and our team continue to bring our ocean‚Äôs stories to life by signing up for the Tide. Together, we can echo our ocean‚Äôs voice and work toward a rich, biodiverse future for our planet. // Link in Bio
