Moon salutations from the new moon in #capricorn last night. Do you practice moon salutations? Most of us are familiar with Sun salutations but I‚Äôve needed a more gentle, soothing option this season and have always liked moon salutations. It‚Äôs also no secret the moon and I have a good thing going. üåïüåñüåóüåòüåë
üåô Teaching this flow for my subscription babies. 
Head over to join us. 

There‚Äôs so many ways to tap into our power and connectivity - with and in our bodies, with nature, with the sensory body, with the universe. 

Here‚Äôs a few things about moon salutations: 

üåô Less stimulating than sun salutations 
üåô Said to prepare the body for rest and practiced in the evenings when the moon is out (but can be practiced anytime) 
üåô Practiced facing the side of the map 
üåô Ideally you do 3-7 rounds (which would be left and right side back to back as 1 round)

Not sure how we are well into December but here we are. Q4 has been a season of tuning in more to what matters most. We learn so much about ourselves in the process of change. As always, holding onto my practices and excited for year end reflections. ‚ú®

October came & went so quickly. 9+ flights, a birthday and a sprinkle of birthday dinners, lots of hugs, different skylines, so much jet lag and even more collective grief. I‚Äôll be honest, showing up online has been strange for the past three years. It seems the horrors of reality continue existing in macro and micro ways every day, for me and for many of you, which leaves these little squares feeling vapid. I continue to hear the strain and unrest many are feeling and have been feeling. 1) You‚Äôre not alone, And 2) we really can‚Äôt grow weary, and I do align with the belief that when things are the hardest is when artists, healers, and all of us who can must get to work. Share as we can. Hold each other as we can. Love as we can. See one another and humanity as we can. So I haven‚Äôt been online as much but I am starting a newsletter (come say hi on substack,) I am writing a book I‚Äôm very proud of, I am moving thru my daily practices and rituals with more intentionality this season (happy to share those if y‚Äôall would like,) and I am seeing my lovely people in real, present ways. How is everyone else feeling? ‚ù§Ô∏è

we officially moved to Spain until summer while our apartment is being renovated, and that will take some time to say at least. It probably seem spontaneous, but we have actually been planning this trip for a while. I‚Äôm that type of person that just goes for it if I want something, and I woke up one day telling myself, no I don‚Äôt wan to do this anymore. sometimes I feel that the winter just take the breath out of everything I cherish. and you just kind of stop.. living sometimes. you stop dressing up for yourself, to take care of yourself, to live your life to the fullest. whatever that is. for me it is to wake up and and be excited about a new day. that feeling is priceless. I woke up today thinking, this is someone‚Äôs winter, I see the palm trees in the wind. I hear different birds singing, and the sound of the crashing waves.. this is also a life, someone‚Äôs winter. and I‚Äôm beginning to realize that I‚Äôm choosing this üñ§

Daniel Robinson is one of those rare artists you meet that are just the real deal, as in: artist to the core‚Ä¶ smart dude, inspiring words, no bullshit, master of his craft, living a humble life in rural Fossil, Oregon with his family, guitar, and a tiny messy backyard studio to paint at night. I‚Äôve known Daniel for a long time, we shared gallery representation at Charles Hartman Fine Art in PDX for 16 years and I always admired him for his dedication to his craft. We were so fortunate to photograph and film him for our latest @dannerboots Go There series. My hot wife @alynicklas directed and shot this video but it took a village to create the video and stills. Huge thanks to our team below!

Coyotes have infiltrated pockets of open land in San Francisco that are completely surrounded by multi-story flats. Incredible how bold some of these families have become due to an attitude that is mostly friendly toward coexistence with urban wildlife in SF. But, it‚Äôs not all rosy for both parties.  Urban coyote populations are mostly kept in check by car strikes, and pets are increasingly preyed upon. Survival techniques are on a spectrum from extreme stealth to extremely bold, and both seem to be working for the coyotes.  #urbanwildlife #onassignment #natgeo #coyote @natgeo #sanfrancisco shot for the story ‚ÄúWhy Cities are going Wild‚Äù in @natgeo magazine July, 2022

Was a great honor to speak at the #natgeostorysummit in Washington D.C. last month and tell the stories behind the images for our ‚ÄúWhy Cities are Going Wild‚Äù story for @natgeo written by the talented @christinedellamore After spending nearly three years tracking coyotes, bears and raccoons through the pandemic, the births of my daughter and son, a marrriage to @alynicklas, the death of my father, and a move out of Portland to the countryside, it was a great to spend time recapping what just happened on that Apocalypse Now style journey, to build this presentation, and reconnect with the National Geographic community. I emerge inspired and humbled and ready for more üôèüèº Thank you for the opportunity: @alexa_keefe @whitneycatherinejohnson @sadiequarrier @roseleen @insidenatgeo @laurel_braitman @kaityarnall Greg McGruder #natgeo #urbanwildlife

King for a Day, by @cedarwright 

People compare Paragliding to chess in the sky.¬† I think this analogy is faulty. I once¬†heard, ‚ÄúParagliding is like playing chess with dice that are a round.‚Äù ¬†Closer to the truth?¬†¬†I think chasing XC records is a little bit like fishing.¬†¬†You cast your line and hope you catch a big one.¬† Really, Paragliding is closer to poker than chess... a game of skill and chance. ¬† 

This winter in Roldanillo I played my cards and launched my line into some absolutely epic weather. I arrived with the pie in the sky goal of breaking the FAI record for what is probably the most popular winter paragliding destination in the world.¬† Success was unlikely, but I‚Äôve been working on my delusional self-belief.¬†

¬†On the 25th of January I realized an unlikely dream and put myself and the USA flag at the top of the Roldanillo x-contest score! I pushed, I believed, and I closed a 219 Km magical mystery tour of the Valle de Cauca.¬†¬†Elated and exhausted, I rested.¬† My glory was short-lived. The next day Bogdan Bialka took his record back pushing it to 230!¬† And‚Ä¶ the next day Kevin Phillip took to the sky with a vengeance setting a new record of 236 km‚Ä¶legend.¬† The Roldanillo¬†FAI record was beaten 3 days in a row!¬† I spent the next two weeks in an absurd version of paragliding Groundhog Day trying to reclaim the record.¬† On three separate occasions, the dream was within grasp but shut down by the unpredictable Pacifico winds and a pace that just wasn‚Äôt fast enough. It‚Äôs fair to say that this was a historic season for Paragliding in Roldanillo.¬† 

Of the top 50 scored flights on x-contest, 46 of them were from this year!¬†¬†It‚Äôs more the journey than the destination, and I‚Äôm grateful for the motivation that being a record chasing psychopath gave me.¬† Epic scenery, wild low saves, thousands of kms, and almost 200 hours of full-bar obsession on my Enzo and Sub.¬†While the Rolda. FAI record is more elusive than ever, I‚Äôm grateful that I got to be king for a day, and learned a ton about paragliding and the power of delusional self-belief.... ¬†which is why I‚Äôll be taking the record back next year.¬†

Not all goes to plan! Dirt Bag Fund recipient @etaiveaho had a proper epic in Washington!  Legendary trip report from Emilio here!  Next round of dirtbag fund applications opening soon! In Emilio‚Äôs words: ‚ÄúThis summer i got lucky enough to be one of the recipients of Cedar Wright‚Äôs dirtbag fund! this was the only time being a dirt bag paid in money as well as experiences. For a while now  I‚Äôve been going into the backcountry every summer‚Äîmountaineering, climbing, and eating homemade dehydrated eggs for weeks (sometimes months) at a time. Outside of that I‚Äôve been maximizing a dirtbag life by living in an RV in rural North Carolina, splitting my time between grad school and climbing, honing my trad skills and getting repeated tastes of humble pie at Moores Wall and Stone Mountain. This spring I used up the last of my cash to buy plane tickets to fly out to Washington and was ready to be completely broke until the dirtbag fund came to my rescue! Crisis averted: Thank you Cedar!! As soon as I arrived in Washington, my climbing partner Mo and I hit the road towards the Olympics, where we repeated Wayne Wallace‚Äôs ‚ÄúSawtooth Ridge.‚Äù Sawtooth was one of the best climbs I‚Äôve had the privilege of doing, with some cerebral and delicious leads. The choss got the best of us, though, and Mo and I both ended up in the hospital.. Mo for a shoulder injury and I for a rectal prolapse and sphincter incision after a fall. While we were able to walk ourselves out of the Olympics, these injuries kept us out of the pickets for the season. I used up more of the dirtbag funds to pay for the hospital bills, some salmon, and a ride back to NC. As I was healing in NC, I was climbing as much as possible and getting some exposure therapy. Eventually I was able to bum around and climb in West Virginia and was comforted by bulletproof rock... I drained the fund on gas money, and got to climb all over the Linville Gorge. 
Although my main objectives were put on pause because of the injury, the stoke for dirtbaggery is at an all time high!!!‚Äù

Product development is long and often frustrating. When you watch my videos, you see the sketch then you see the final result in a matter of 60 seconds but the truth is often my designs take anywhere between a year to sometimes 3 years to go from concept to real thing. 

Why?

It all begins with finding the right fabric for what I‚Äôm trying to achieve. If I‚Äôm lucky, I may already have a fabric I love that I‚Äôve used before that I wanna use again! But often the fabric sourcing bit itself can take months.

The sampling process can take anywhere from a few months minimum to almost a year, sometimes more! During this time, fabric can change, design may change, the perfect fit will always be obsessed over, and I‚Äôll sample over and over and over again until it feels just right. I‚Äôll won‚Äôt stop until it feels ready, and I‚Äôm happy.

Then there‚Äôs the actual production which includes the weaving of the fabric, the dying of the fabric, the cutting of the pattern pieces, the careful sewing of the garment etc etc‚Ä¶

Good things just take time. 

They seem to always do, don‚Äôt they?

HANDSTANDS FOR BEGINNERS ü§∏üèΩ these can be a tricky (and sometimes scary üòµ‚Äçüí´) skill to learn‚Ä¶so here are some beginner exercises you can try to help you build:

‚úÖ Confidence upside down
‚úÖ Body awareness when things get flipped upside-down
‚úÖ Good handstand body position
‚úÖ Strength in your shoulders, core & hands

üêå Start sloooowwww üêå 
‚ñ™Ô∏èThe first time you try, just spend 5minutes having a play. You can do this everyday but have a rest day if you start to feel any pain in your wrists (‚ùóÔ∏èRemember your wrists & shoulders need to build strength in this new position‚Ä¶this takes time!)
‚ñ™Ô∏èIncrease the time you spend on your hands slowly each week. Maybe add a minute or 2 to each session. (Add that rest day when needed!)

‚ú®Key tips‚ú®
‚ñ™Ô∏èTry to build a straight line from your hands to shoulders to hips (in both exercises). A training buddy can help you find this position if you can‚Äôt feel it!
‚ñ™Ô∏èFingertips spread wide & pressing down into the ground
‚ñ™Ô∏èShoulders squeezing ears & push the ground A W A Y

There are a MILLION more tips that I can share so it‚Äôs important to remember handstands are a skill and they are complex! So it‚Äôs ok if you don‚Äôt get it straight away ‚ò∫Ô∏è Take it slow and have fun!

MOBILITY FOR TIGHT HIPS üí´ These are some of my favourite hip releases üëåüèº Perfect to do as part of your warm up, before a run, on a recovery day or when you are feeling a bit sore/tired from training‚Ä¶ I sometimes get lower back tightness and these also help release tension & pain! ‚ò∫Ô∏è

‚ñ™Ô∏è1. LOW SQUAT
- lower your hips to any position that is manageable and where you can keep your heels on the ground & elbows inside the knees (Level 1,2 & 3 shown in order in the video ‚ò∫Ô∏è)
- if you can reach level 3, aim to pull your belly & chest forward at the bottom, spreading the knees wide.
AREAS RELEASED - Groin, hamstrings, low back

‚ñ™Ô∏è2. LOW LUNGE RAINBOW DIVE
- as you reach back open your chest as much as possible & sink the hips.
- guide the elbow toward the ground reaching as low as you can.
AREAS RELEASED - Groin, hip flexor, glute, hamstring, low back

‚ñ™Ô∏è3. GLUTE SLIDE
- foot rests close to the opposite hand as knee slides through the arms as far as you can.
- for a deeper release, slide the back knee further back into a longer lunge.
AREAS RELEASED - Glutes, hip flexor, hamstrings, low back

MORE GLUTES IN YOUR DEADLIFT üçë OR MORE HAMSTRINGS üçñ Here‚Äôs how you get your aim right‚Ä¶

GLUTE FOCUSED DEADLIFT üçë
This requires more STRETCH of the glute muscle to occur because more stretch = increased tension = more activation & work required to contract the muscles again. And more work = MORE GROWTH!
üëâüèº so what do you need to do? 
Increase the amount of knee bend and lower the hips more. This creates a deeper fold at the hips (and also less tension in the hamstring) increasing the recruitment of the glutes üëåüèº

HAMSTRING FOCUSED DEADLIFT üçñ
The same principle applies. You need to create more stretch & length in the hamstrings compared to the glutes.
üëâüèº so what do you need to do?
Less bend in the knees (bust still a slight bend üòâ) and keep the hips higher as you lower the bar. 

üé• WATCH MY FULL YT VIDEO FOR A DETAILED & VISUAL EXPLANATION ‚ò∫Ô∏è (link in stories)

It‚Äôs important to note that both muscle groups will be active in a deadlift, no matter which variation you do. This technique tip helps you shift more or less tension into each muscle group depending on what your training goals are üòé Hope this helps! Let me know what exercise you need help with next! üëáüèº #deadlifttechnique #deadliftform #gluteexercise #hamstringexercise

PILATES FOR RUNNERS üëü If you‚Äôre a runner, sprinter, or even walker, you should be doing this!

Building strength in the glutes, stability in the hips & maintaining active feet is so important for efficient & injury free leg driven km‚Äôs (or miles!) üèÉüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüí®

I‚Äôve sped these videos up a little bit so remember to do each exercise slowly and with purpose!

TRY BEFORE RUNNING:
1-3 rounds depending how much time you have (the more often you do these, the better results you will get üí™üèº)

‚ñ™Ô∏è1. CLAM SEQUENCE
x10 each side

- do all 3 exercises in a row, making sure you don‚Äôt collapse in the bottom ribcage between each exercise.
- keep the hips still (like there are in concrete) 

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min - important for good lower body gait & hip stability

‚ñ™Ô∏è 2. SL TUCK CIRCLES
x10 each side

- keep belly button pulled in as you hold hips high & aim to keep hips still.

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min / hip flexors / abs - helps build hip stability during leg movement

‚ñ™Ô∏è3. SL EXTENDED RDL
x10 each side

- standing leg always has a slight bend
- fold at the hips & keep spine long (sit into standing leg a bit deeper)

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min, quads, hip flexor - improves balance, hip stability & foot strength

‚ñ™Ô∏è4. HIP HIKES
x10 each side

- move slowly & through full range on every rep (full up - full down)

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min / obliques - improves hip stability & lower body gait

‚ñ™Ô∏è5. FOOT SEQUENCE
x10 each side

Heel-Toe
- as you lean back pick up all 10 toes. Spread them as wide as you can as you roll foot forward then rise to toes.

Outdide-Inside
- slight bend in the knees & aim to find edges of your feet while spreading toes.

üí•WORKS: Calves / Smaller foot muscles - important for good foot biomechanics and strength (our feet become weak as we are constantly in shoes!)

We didn't know it at the time this photo was captured, but this special leopard ‚Äì her eyes alive with curiosity and wonder ‚Äì would have a massive impact on our lives and careers. This is Legadema, the star of our film Eye of the Leopard. We spent over three years filming and documenting her growth from wide-eyed cub to confident huntress. She let us into her secretive world and helped fuel our passion to protect Africa's threatened wild cats. Although Legadema is no longer with us, her legacy lives on. This #WorldWildlifeDay, we're reflecting on the special time we spent with her, and renewing our dedication to protect our planet's precious wild species and spaces.‚Å£
‚Å£
#WorldWildlifeDay #wildlife #nature #leopard

Battles between lions and buffaloes are unpredictable, brutal and intense. Adult male African buffaloes can weigh over 900 kilograms and they are notoriously belligerent. It takes careful coordination, acute timing and immense courage for lions to successfully hunt these massive animals. Often when the fight appears to be nearing its conclusion, a final show of strength from the buffalo ‚Äì sometimes backed by the rest of the herd ‚Äì can swing the odds in its favour. Sadly, for this bull, his resilience was overpowered and the lions succeeded.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
#lion #wildlife #nature #bigcats #bigcatsofinstagram

Open mouth, insert foot.‚Å£
‚Å£
This young male was surprisingly tolerant of the rough-and-tumble games initiated by the pride's smallest members. For the cubs, playtime ‚Äì which is most of the time ‚Äì is an opportunity to learn and discover. For this subadult male who became the unwilling victim of their exuberant pouncing, it's a lesson in patience.‚Å£
‚Å£
#lion #wildlife #nature #bigcats #bigcatsofinstagram

Wildebeest may not be the most conventionally handsome antelope, but catch them in the right light ‚Äì their beards glowing red in the afternoon sun ‚Äì and they take on a certain distinctive quality. These somewhat ungainly animals are hardy survivors. They face an onslaught of threats during their annual migration across the predator-rich plains of the Serengeti and, for many, its sheer resilience and mettle that see them through the journey.

#wildebeest #wildlife #nature

I've always been in awe of the sheer power and presence of elephants. While spending time with these giants you learn to appreciate the delicate application of that immense strength. A carefully directed blast of water from a trunk provides relief from the scorching African sun, while pillar-like legs are used to dig into the sand when rivers run dry. Their movements are purposeful and intricate fuelled by an intelligence and social cohesion that we are yet to fully understand. Although, we don't speak their language and can only deduce the motivations for their behaviour, we can respect and admire their sentience. And do everything we can to protect them.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
#elephant #nature #wildlife

Trees are more than just resting spots for leopards; they provide cover from danger and a safe place to stash a kill where it's beyond the reach of eager scavengers. This cat hastily hauled her warthog kill into the safety of the boughs, but kept a lookout for any rivals on the horizon. Competition for food is tough in the African bush, and wily predators like leopards are only too aware of the looming threat of losing a meal.‚Å£
‚Å£
#bigcats #bigcatsofinstagram #leopards

A lion's roar commands attention. Specially adapted vocal folds allow these cats to muster up a reverberating bellow that can be heard from kilometres away. If you're close enough, you'll feel the vibrations of the call rolling through your bones and likely triggering the hairs on the back of your neck to stand up straight. It's a sound we've come to love and appreciate during our time documenting these apex predators. Sadly, we have also witnessed this iconic sound fading from more and more corners of the African wild. We stand to lose so much more than just a roar if we allow these cats to vanish.‚Å£
‚Å£
#lions #bigcats #bigcatsofinstagram #bigcatconservation #wildlife #wildlifelovers #conservation #nature

There's a special elegance and grace reserved for giraffes. That silhouette, unmistakable against a golden sky, floats with purpose and poise across the savannah. Their unique form has awed visitors to Africa for centuries, but like so many other species, giraffes are in trouble. Populations have plummeted by 40% in just the last 30 years, and there are now fewer than 70,000 mature individuals left in the wild. We know what must be done to save them: prioritise conservation efforts, safeguard habitats, address threats like illegal hunting. If we don't act now, we stand to lose these iconic creatures forever.‚Å£
‚Å£
#giraffes #giraffeconservation #wildlifeconservation

#Repost from @natgeo

Intensely focused, this cheetah gives a piercing gaze across the plains of Kenya‚Äôs Masai Mara. Among Africa‚Äôs iconic big cats, cheetahs stand out as perhaps the most stark example of threats converging to imperil a species‚Äîfrom shallow gene pools to habitat loss to the illegal trade. New and emerging issues, including some related to climate change, are adding to the pressure‚Äîand often unfolding in unexpected ways. Recent research, for example, shows that rising temperatures are pushing cheetahs to shift their hunting habits to the cooler night hours, a behavior that not only complicates their survival strategies but also intensifies competition with other carnivores. In the face of these complex challenges, it is crucial for us to recognize the urgency of conservation efforts for both cheetahs and precious ecosystems like the Masai Mara.

Spotting a pangolin in the wild is rare. In all our years documenting wildlife, often spending weeks embedded in the bush, we've only seen a handful of these elusive mammals in the wild. They're often more active at night, shuffling through the undergrowth in search of termites, ants and larvae, which they dig out of nests and burrows using their impressive claws. Once they've carved an opening in the dirt, a long sticky tongue goes to work sucking up insects en masse. ‚Å£
‚Å£
They are profoundly unique animals. But they are also under threat. All eight species of pangolins found throughout the world are threatened by the illegal wildlife trade and populations are rapidly declining. Despite their shy nature, they remain one of the most trafficked mammals in the world and are illegally trapped in their thousands to feed a growing demand for their scales and meat. Without strict regulations and enforcement, these remarkable animals may be pushed to extinction. This #WorldPangolinDay, let's join forces and pledge to never let that happen.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
#pangolin #PangolinsDay #wildlife #nature #wildlifeconservation

So much hope rests on those wobbly legs. It‚Äôll take at least 10 years for this elephant to reach maturity. Ten long years where the youngster may encounter shrinking habitats, altered landscapes, and malicious humans. If the calf makes it, he‚Äôll have an important role to play in helping nurture the next generation of elephants ‚Äì a generation that may face even greater threats. These giants need safe space to roam in protected landscapes where they can live in harmony with humans. ‚Å£
‚Å£
@DereckJoubert and I recently hosted a number of speaking events in Florida where our goal was to share the urgent need to protect wild spaces and species and safeguard them for future generations. An African savannah without elephants is something we cannot  fathom. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Visit www.greatplainsfoundation to find out more about what we are doing to protect our planet and how you can get involved.‚Å£
‚Å£
#wildlifeconservation #elephants

It's astonishing to witness the speed and agility of hippos. Although they spend the majority of the daylight hours basking, semi-submerged, in rivers or ponds, hippos venture out of the water at night or when the weather is cooler to feed on grass. Those dainty ankles are carrying around a ton and a half of territorial hippo and, despite his size, he can turn on a dime. Deeply scarred from territorial disputes ‚Äì the wounds of which were likely made more severe by opportunistic oxpecker birds that feast on blood and parasites ‚Äì this male clearly means business. Hippos are famously possessive over their pools and will aggressively defend them, sometimes even charging at innocuous animals like impalas. A herd of buffalo ventured a bit too close, and the enraged hippo voiced his displeasure at their presence. Although buffaloes can definitely hold their own against an aggressive hippo, this herd thought  better of taking on the challenge and instead watched the angry behemoth from a distance.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
#HippoDay #WorldHippoDay #hippo #Okavango #wildlife

Pre & post menopause has been a rollercoaster! I‚Äôm 49, and I‚Äôve been navigating this ride for the past 9 years. (Peri menopause started at age 40ü´†)

One thing I forgot to mention in this video is that SLOW weight loss is the BEST kind of weight loss! There is no rush. Be consistent even if it takes years because the slower it comes off the better for long term success.

It‚Äôs taken me over 2 (maybe more) years to lose the belly fat. Before I get comments about how I looked great before and didn‚Äôt need to lose the weight‚Ä¶ here‚Äôs the deal:

Visceral fat is fat around your organs & can lead to many health complications. When I started gaining weight around my belly, it wasn‚Äôt subcutaneous fat that you could pinch. It was hard, and felt so uncomfortable.

I knew that I had to figure out why this was happening or rather what I could do to stop & reverse the weight gain.

I‚Äôve written several blogs about my discoveries from diet to exercise & exactly the changes I made so please check them out for more info.

I get messages from women every day about weight gain, specifically belly fat, & I‚Äôm posting this content for them.

When our hormones decline, we are at much greater health risks like heart disease, osteoporosis, and diabetes.

I recommend talking to your doctor & getting a full blood work up. Vitamin, mineral, & fiber deficiencies can make menopause even worse so it‚Äôs always good to know how well (nutrient-wise) you are eating.

With exercise, resistance based workouts to help build muscle will help protect your bones and increase your metabolism.

Consistency is hard for a lot of people. My only advice is to not make it a choice. 

Just like brushing your teeth, doing your laundry, or cleaning your dishes, you do it because it just has to get done.üôåüèª

‚ÄúI know I‚Äôm a handful baby‚Äù, part of the new series ‚ÄúRelationship status:‚Äù, where we (@wheresaddie and @aialahernando) use self portraiture as a means of translating/exploring the private as public female experience. 
The artists use site specific real floral arrangements, alongside contemporary artifacts within the artists‚Äô lived experiences; the personal objects strewn across the works serve both as a portrait of the modern women but also of the artists themselves, to create a feeling of longing in the work- to see what is concealed, to understand who is attached. As we approach the end of year, I wanted to share a quick update on all things @honnoldfoundation.¬†I know I say this every year, but, really, it‚Äôs pretty incredible to see how HF‚Äôs work has evolved over time.¬†I got a chance to read through a report that highlighted some of our Partners‚Äô impacts in the last few years, and it got me fired up.¬†Just one example ‚Äì in the last three years, our projects have built solar infrastructure in¬†245¬†communities¬†with the potential to impact¬†over 180,000 people.¬†

Meanwhile, the solar infrastructure we‚Äôve helped install is enough to cover 9 acres worth of rooftops, which is honestly quite a bit.

But maybe the most eye popping stat was this: In the last three years, we‚Äôve received far more projects than we could fund. If we had funded every single project submitted to us, we‚Äôd have brought solar to nearly¬†1.8 million people.

I‚Äôm proud of the work we‚Äôve done, and I also know that there‚Äôs plenty more to do.

To everyone who supports our work at the Honnold Foundation, thank you! It‚Äôs really making a significant impact for people around the world. ‚Ä®‚Ä®And, if you‚Äôre considering and able to make an end of year donation towards climate action and social justice, I‚Äôd really appreciate you thinking of us at the Honnold Foundation. My own giving supports our team‚Äôs overhead, so every dollar that you give goes directly towards the communities we support ‚Äì and all of those impacts I just mentioned.

Whether you can afford a little or a lot - all I ask is that you approach it a bit like a climbing project: make a gift that challenges you ‚Äì something not too easy, but don‚Äôt go bankrupt or anything, either. Just make a gift that you can be proud of.

Anyways, hope you and your family have a nice holiday season!

I‚Äôve also built a few companies such as @stayandwander (creative agency) and @wildistco (online photography school). I struggle with scheduling because I am interested in a lot of things. I also struggle to make the time to go shoot more outside. Also, I‚Äôm a pretty bad handyman.

It‚Äôs wild to consider the amount of life these mountains have witnessed throughout different chapters in the history of the world... Hannibal leading the Carthaginian army across the alps in 218 BC to the development of alpinism and years of brave people ticking off first ascents with only rudimentary gear and a strong will. Every time I set foot in them.. it invites a way of life that encourages constant awareness without distraction. You have to pay attention to your surroundings but you also feel at peace with that rhythm of life - something I find harder to achieve surrounded by man made structures. These images come from 2016 on a perfect day in the Swiss alps.. gazing down at Lake Ritom with a bit of disbelief at our luck finding a glassy lake with a backdrop more like a painting than reality‚Ä¶

A couple of weeks ago, I shared a collection of some commercial work that I‚Äôve done over the years and I thought I‚Äôd share another round of some old favorites. It‚Äôs so common on Instagram to only see highlights or just the final product and I think it‚Äôs really important to show a larger scope of what it takes to be successful in the creative industry - and commercial work has been a huge part of that for me. My approach was always to combine inspiring, landscapes, and adventure with companies that I worked with - taking what I knew how to do well and finding a way to integrate their product in.. some thing I think aspiring photographers to ask themselves‚Ä¶ how does your style and expertise mesh with a brand that way that makes sense?

We always sought out this angle‚Ä¶ hoping to get fisheye perspective that usually resulted in you going over the falls. Luckily the sand was soft. I was on a a long overdue trip with my wife in California after weeks of being gone for work and I got this call that this swell was coming to a remote section of the Caribbean‚Ä¶ I remember kinda weighing out the decision to stay or go - eventually making the decision to go and left halfway through our once in a blue moon vacation. Life was so volatile‚Ä¶. being on call for these trips meant I had to drop even a special trip with family at times. The trip was a success, I scored a cover on Surfer Magazine but I always thought back to how much the career asked of me 

Caribbean, 2013. Zander Morton üèÑ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

As long as I can remember, holding a camera in my hand, it was a dream to be a staff photographer for Surfer Magazine. My years spent shooting for these publications were truly an honor and profoundly shaped the direction of my career and perspective in storytelling. During my tenure, the epitome of success was getting a cover and I look at those covers as some of the highlight moments of my life‚Ä¶ 
This short piece paying tribute to some really iconic and influential magazines was a walk down memory lane for me - making me relive some of those little moments.. it‚Äôs super meaningful to be featured here and the book that my friend @grantellis1 put together is pretty special & an incredible way to see the evolution of surfing & photography over the years‚Ä¶

This cut of the movie contains some of the footage that inspired me the most... what documented the aerial perspectives of the glacial rivers that had been in my dreams for so long, this time immersing myself and traversing their lines.

Iceland‚Äôs highlands have long been a playground for both locals and newcomers.. offering the ability to connect with an astonishing variety of natural features all within close proximity to each other. You might be crossing glacial rivers, moving past steaming geothermal vents, or traversing colorful ridge lines that look as if painted by nature‚Äôs brush. This part of the world always sparks imagination and rejuvenates me every time I return... offering a little more perspective on where my next expedition could be or what creative project might capture it‚Äôs beauty for those to see who are unable to make the trip. Last fall I was lucky enough to share some spectacular weather in the highlands on a ride with the @maap.cc ALT-ROAD crew - traversing from hut to hut and scoring some of the best views Iceland has to offer... couldn‚Äôt think of a better way to spend a few days with friends.

I‚Äôm not a wildlife photographer - I leave that to my good friends @paulnicklen & @mitty who‚Äôve spent many years & countless hours perfecting the craft‚Ä¶ but occasionally, if I‚Äôm lucky, an animal gets in the way of my camera. 
To me, whales cresting the ocean‚Äôs surface remains as one of the more special human experiences. The two orcas shown above swam just off the shores of the Kurils - a chain of islands located between Russia and Japan. Besides the sound of disturbed seagulls and the creaking of our boat, all outside distractions and sense of time seemed to fade away as I witnessed these beautiful creatures breach‚Ä¶ fortunately having the presence of mind to haphazardly hold up my camera and try to capture one of the purest wildlife moments I can remember. During this expedition in 2019 with @renan_ozturk & @taylorfreesolo - we shared a piece of what we found in an environmental documentary called ‚ÄúFrom the Kurils with Love‚Äù which you can find on YouTube

This are images from an old project from 2002.
The project was born out of one of the most traumatic experiences I had as a journalist - and it is - in a way - the beginning of my career.

In the Summer of 2002 I traveled to Israel and the West Bank and Gaza - fresh out of school hoping to find my way into the industry. I did whatever naive kid did back then, and parachuted my way into a story that I had little nuanced appreciation for. 

In the midst of trying to document life in Hebron between the Jewish settlers and Palestinian residents, I was beaten by a mob of 20 Jewish settlers during a violent funeral/riot in the center of the city. Interestingly enough an Israeli soldier was also beaten by the settler mob. 

I lost all my photography equipment I had saved up for, driving the ‚Äúdrunk bus‚Äù route in school, and dislocated my shoulder, and fractured my elbow and knee.

My mentor at the time - James Colburn (the DC bureau photo editor for Time Magazine) told me I couldn‚Äôt leave. That if I left - ‚ÄúI would always be scared‚Äù 

So I stayed - and he shipped me some old Nikon F3s he had lying in his office.

I spent the next month looking for a different story, and I found it in the most cliche place - A mental institution.

There was an old geriatric wing of this psychiatric facility in Bethlehem. For patients from all over the country. The doctors said some were Jewish, some were Muslim, some were Christian. No one knew for sure, many had been dropped off as infants. The facility had originally been administered by German, then British, then TransJordanian, then Israel and at the time I was there - the Palestinian Authority. 

And it was filled with many patients. They were all psychologically damaged or impaired. But interestingly enough - they got along with each other.

They were insane. But at peace.
And everyone outside was sane, but waging war.

Makes you think about who is really in their right minds. 

#photojournalism #palestine #israel #reportage #documentary

I don‚Äôt always know how to write a humanist caption for what I report on. I was down on the border in #eaglepass TX covering hopeful and desperate migrants crossing the Rio Grande. Most were coming from Venezuela. Many had been on the road for over a year. The infant had been born while on the road. The definition of a stateless refugee. 
And the last leg of their desperate trip was a raging river, and a shore filled with concertina razor wire and armed National Guard. 
The US border patrol would cut the wire that the National Guard put up to let people in. Children and women first, then men. 

My dad came through Ellis Island as a child, and never had to face what these people have. 

#onassignment  #photojournalism #reportage #immigration #politics

Eagle Pass, TX : A US Border Patrol agent holds a wailing child after helping several adolescent migrants - those already on US territory - cross large swaths of razor concertina wire set out by the TX National Guard. The wire is meant to dissuade and keep migrants from coming ashore and claiming asylum, a right enshrined in current American law.

#politics #immigration #migrants #eaglepasstx #migration

More hopeful migrants cross the Rio Grande River towards Eagle Pass, TX. All hoping for a better life and more opportunities in the US. But many face the harsh realities of an overloaded and broken American immigration system. Many apply for asylum before crossing, but often find themselves the victims of criminals, or the lack of adequate housing forces them into a desperate decision to cross into the US. 

#politics #immigration #eaglepasstx #photojournalism #reportage #migrants

Eagle Pass, TX - A migrant mother and daughter embrace after making it across the Rio Grande and past a riverbank lined with razor wire and TX National Guard. 
With all the political rhetoric these days - many forget these are actual human beings struggling to find a better life. 

#photojournalism #reportage #politics #eaglepass #migration #immigration

One of the other projects I did in Yemen were these portraits of Yemenis that played into the assignment I was working on, along with people I met during wanderings around different cities. 

This project could be the indirect reason I was detailed when I came back to the US. 

The second image is a portrait of the leader (at the time) of Al Qaeda‚Äôs political wing in Yemen.  He really liked the image and asked if I could send it to him. We used the old ‚Äúbump‚Äù iPhone app to exchange the image. And I‚Äôm pretty sure my phone was compromised from there on out. 

To make matters worse - we were meeting in a large cafe for safety - the next interview subject came in to meet the writer and I a bit early. The third image is a portrait of the last Rabbi in Yemen. Obviously the head of Al Qaeda and the Rabbi kept their affiliations on the DL - so neither knew who each one was. They actually exchanged pleasant greetings and traded places - as the rabbi stayed for an interview and portrait.

The fourth image is a former Guantanamo prisoner who was returned to Yemen after serving a few years in the prison and found either not guilty or not worth US efforts to interrogate him. He was unemployed and trying to figure out how to continue a life cut short. 

#portrait #photojournalism #reportage #onassignment #documentary #yemen #tintype

Snippets from the woodworking studio with Yoshida-san @monkeyhold_japan in Â§ßÂû£ (Ogaki), Japan over the summer. 

Shaping these holds was a lesson in allowing the medium lead to the final form rather than having the mind dictate the outcome. The practice was about inhibiting the urge to mold the wood into a shape I had pre-envisioned; instead, surrendering to the wood, imagining how best to reveal its beauty and unique form. 

To hold something is gratifying, but the more I climb, the more curious I become about the entire ecosystem that holds the boulders. When examined more closely, the ‰æòÂØÇ of the wood is unveiled through the imperfections of the gnarled knots, the layers and swirls of age lines that hold the stories of the tree the wood came from ü§ç üå≥

Shibori w mom and friendsü™Å 
üå±I‚Äôve been fascinated by this form of textile art for quite some time but never took the initiative to experiment w it till this year. In a conversation w my mom about folk art in Japan, the topic of this ancient method of manual resist dying came up and her eyes instantly sparkled with excitement as she shared her story of working with dye in her youth. As a child to immigrant parents who are reserved in speaking of their past, i have a hazy idea of what they were like in their youth and the environment in which they grew up in. Anyways, I love how shibori became a catalyst to paint a more vivid picture of my mom‚Äôs past üåøIt felt extra special to learn some shibori techniques from my mom with dear friendsüíñ 

Some quotes I love from master dyer Fukumi Shimura: 

‚ÄúI have received color without limit from the natural world in the years since I entered the dyer‚Äôs way. It has poured down on me endlessly, too much for this meager vessel to hold. Joyful as a child with a new set of paints, I have woven and woven yarn dyed by the grasses and trees‚Äù. 

‚ÄúI don‚Äôt tell the acorn or gardenia seed pod or plum bar what color I want ‚Äì I listen to the voice of the plants.‚Äù 

Hope I get the chance to practice and learn from the shibori masters in Japan soon üé®

Malibu is also a word of Chumash origin, which is the name given to groups of California Indians that lived around the south-central coast. Chumash is derived from Tc√∫-mac, a word used by the Coastal Chumash to refer to Santa Rosa Island natives. Before the Spanish arrived, Chumash natives lived along the coast from San Luis Obispo to Malibu Canyon, and as far east as the edge of San Joaquin Valley.

November is Native American Heritage Month in the US and a time to celebrate and honor the rich and diverse cultures, traditions, histories and to acknowledge the important contributions of Native people. It‚Äôs also a great time to learn more about Native people and how tribal citizens are working to move beyond these challenges. I‚Äôm grateful to be part of the collective effort of the #arcteryx athlete team to share the stories of the original caretakers and names of places that are special to each of us. We are hoping that by acknowledging the first stewards, amplifying the past and current impact of Indigenous stewardship, we can help to begin to undo the erasure caused by the renaming of important places.

The rocks, ever-evolving, are shaped into curved and glacial looking sculptures by the water. 
Lao Tzu once said, ‚ÄúWater is fluid, soft, and yielding. But water will wear away rock, which is rigid and cannot yield. As a rule, whatever is fluid, soft, and yielding will overcome whatever is rigid and hard. This is another paradox: what is soft is strong‚Äù. 

Water being soft and strong reminds me of the soft power of storytelling. Here‚Äôs one story: 
before Los Angeles was even a word on a map, it was called Tovaangar, the territory of the Tongva, Chumash and Kizh, who were then enslaved to build the San Gabriel Mission and San Fernando Mission. It may be unsettling to realize but urban areas that have become so ingrained in our collective consciousness as ‚ÄúAmerican‚Äù were once native land, too.

One of the things I‚Äôm most thankful for is the ability to explore West Coast nature, like this spot: Malibu Tunnels‚õ∞üï≥

It‚Äôs a windy channel of conglomerate rock that acts like a barrier from the turbulence of civilization. There‚Äôs a canopy of cottonwoods and live oaks scattered about. Rattlers basking in the sun. A honeycomb mounted in a hueco. A flow of creek water cascades down and through the rock piles. Further down the stream, a face of cobblestone rocks- purple, green, brown, red- protruding upon a beige sandy looking canvas.

There‚Äôs a busy road a hundred feet above; honking and roadside noise remind us that this respite is in close proximity to a bustling city. But then the gurgling water overwhelms the sound of motor vehicles emanating from above, dislodging you from the constraints of spatial and temporal associations, you can almost close your eyes and forget where you are.

Union Station is Canada‚Äôs busiest, multi-modal passenger transportation hub, a designated national historic site and a significant part of Toronto‚Äôs history and identity.

Located 14 stories high - 200 feet above ground, lies an outdoor urban oasis, where @fairmontroyalyork garden grows. On any summer's day, @chef_jwfoster and the Planet 21 Team can be seen nurturing and tending to the vast variety of organic produce and herbs that are cared for without the use of herbicides and pesticides.

Fairmont also houses six beehives. It is the first of the Fairmont hives and is often noted as being the first rooftop apiary found at any hotel in the world. It was also the first to install a pollinator bee hotel in 2014, paving the way for more to follow in the following years. 

At its summer peak 350,000 honeybees reside in six beehives to produce an average of 450 pounds of honey per year. 

For almost 30 years, Fairmont Hotels has been committed to proactively protecting its local environments. 

A commitment to minimizing its impact on the planet.

Once upon a time there were some colors and lines: @DJIglobal has invited me to be a judge for their SkyPixel photography contest. The theme is story, which feels timely. I‚Äôm overwhelmed by the amount of incredible images being created these days. Beauty at every turn. Flying above and beyond aesthetics, the challenge is sorting out what is meaningful and why - to appreciate work through its quality of insight. Like nav lights in the peripheral, meaning and story glow as if buttons, dials, numbers and arrows, guiding us to an altitude of even greater appreciation. If you‚Äôre keen, check out the SkyPixel website. The submission deadline is at the end of January, and there are some really cool Hasselblad prizes.

And it‚Äôll continue Brooks, you lover of books, that‚Äôs natures fury. The Joad‚Äôs fight grows with a multiple factor, everyone is the central actor. Max making, max burning, minds fire for acquisition and yearning. Dopamine hums under hovering thumbs. Adrift between islands of conscious attention, look over here, check your mentions. Hal 9000, opening pod-bay doors of perceptions, to drones of addicts feeding on hidden mathematics. Beyond the infinite was an algorithmic prediction. The gravitational pull of artificial diction. Search the core for meaning and value, it‚Äôs beyond transaction, seeking infinite growth of the material is malefaction, the fruits of the reality tree are revealed in transcendent inaction. But apples are tasty, so a bite of genesis can shipped to your door if hasty.

Spring in the quilted hills, and the perennial question. Where to go next, or perhaps better stated, how to grow next? I really enjoy the notion, that ideas are alive and independent, like butterflies flittering about. There‚Äôs two ways to catch ‚Äòum. You can run yourself ragged chasing. Or you can chill and enlarge the net.

Wyoming has quickly become one of my favorite backpacking destinations. Two years ago I spent a week in the Wind River Range, then last summer I joined @elisabethontheroad as she documented our climb up Cloud Peak in the Bighorn Mountains for @visitwyoming

I‚Äôve followed the work of plein air painters from this state before I ever picked up a camera. It‚Äôs been fun growing familiar with the language of the landscape first hand, to see the peaks and valleys that translated to such inspiration. 

Finding beauty can be straightforward, it shines unabashed, but exploring what you have to say about a place takes time. It may even be through the creative process itself that you discover it. I often learn as much during a week on the computer with a digital paintbrush, as a week on the trail. Wouldn‚Äôt trade the epiphanies provided by either.

If your curious about the specifics of our climb, you can find Elisabeth‚Äôs article at TravelWyoming.com. #ThatsWY #WYresponsibly
Exploring an idea. One-new, two-an update, three-from a few years back.

‚ÄúUnlike Earth, the atmosphere of Mars is dominated by micron-size dust aerosols, and the sky during sunset takes on a bluish glow.‚Äù From: Applied Optics Vol. 53, Issue 9

I‚Äôve been experimenting with the public domain images available on the NASA website. What you see here are constructed entirely from that source. It‚Äôs been strange, and wasn‚Äôt until I found the article referenced above that I realized why. The light on Mars is ‚Äòweird‚Äô because the atmosphere is different. Go figure.

As I worked, the project became as much about understanding this unique light as playing with Martin landforms. The images here explore a few ways to bridge a blue light source - with golden/orange scattering, across a few different angles and times of day in a variety of atmospheric dust. It‚Äôs definitely not accurate, and surely exaggerated. (Check out the article, lots of math above my ability) The science was simply a point of departure for experimentation. The main gist i held in mind, is that blue can transition through purple & red or green & yellow to get to orange. Just walk your way around a color wheel. Fun. After a month tho, I‚Äôm ready to go look at some foliage.

There‚Äôs a balance between surface and substance, the aesthetics of an image and its meaning. I tend to think craft is important, but offers diminishing returns. In contrast, the possibilities for conceptual exploration are endless. It‚Äôs the difference between learning a language and finding what you have to say with it.

My favorite time in art history was between the late 1800‚Äôs and the early 1900‚Äôs, when the method used to create something started gaining awareness of its contribution to content. An interest in the mechanics of light and sight created the dappled visual color mixing of the impressionists. An interest in the mechanics of time and space gave birth to the multiple overlaid perspectives of cubism. I keep thinking about this as I flew about the mountains, collecting images from multiple moments and perspective.

Does any of this matter to the viewer and the final? Maybe. There are plenty of images I‚Äôve enjoyed for their ideas, and plenty for aesthetics alone. But on this side of the image, the one of discovery and creation, building something with a conceptual foundation makes all the difference between a meaningful process and a simply stylish one. It‚Äôs powerfully good to stay in touch with that little kid inside, who endlessly asks ‚Äúwhy?!‚Äù

@DJIglobal #mavic3 #imageaboveeverything

One of my favorite fascinations is searching for repeated patterns in scale, micro and macro. Maybe it has to do with searching for something fundamental in the nature of things, or maybe it‚Äôs just fun to pretend you‚Äôre giant or very very small. 

This digital painting came together with shots from the mavic3 while climbing, and macro shots of rocks collected along the way.

Matching light and atmosphere is the most important factor to make a realistic scene, but texture is one of the biggest scale giveaways, so drones are the perfect tool to marry the two. 

@DJIglobal #mavic3 #imageaboveeverything

Migratory interests. I‚Äôve been taking a little break from pixel painting and posting,  exploring a few new fascinations.  Then last month, DJI asked me to try out their Mavic3. Always happy to see through a different lens, I spent a couple weeks dodging fall storms in Idaho. (Really digging the extended battery life BTW.) Ironically, I‚Äôm now realizing my artistic process; harmonizing an eclectic array of images (somewhere around 30 here), isn‚Äôt so different than life process; harmonizing an eclectic array of interests. I really think the key is remembering to identify with the fascination, not the subject of it. Trust that single source of light, and the rest will sort itself in time, or Photoshop.

@DJIglobal #mavic3 #imageaboveeverything

The clam diggers. A rainy day conversation with, James Abbott McNeill Whistler, and Idris Khan, perhaps a drop in by Todd Hido...

I don‚Äôt know any of these cats. Idris and Todd are making powerful work today, but James was born in 1834, so it might be a challenge for us to get together. But, that‚Äôs the cool thing about art. We can dialogue with anyone throughout time.

This one finds me curious about their feelings on substance vs style. Inspiration vs appropriation. The relationship between how we make something, and why. 

Idris created a seminal series that appropriated the work of Bernd and Hilla Becher, with (it appears) the intent of adding meaning. Todd‚Äôs style is highly copied by other contemporary photographers, who arguably don‚Äôt add additional meaning. And James was a big proponent of art for aesthetics alone - meaning be damned (and fought over in lawsuits.) Of course his stance was taken in an age when images were relatively rare and filled with allegory, which to him might have made this fight feel - quite meaningful. üôÉ

American badlands. 

There is freedom being an outsider, to see culture in memetic terms, languages modular and mutable. To identify, simply through that which you happen to be appreciating. Right now, there is blue sky and sunlight on the hills.

Rock arrangement in sea minor. I grew up on this beach, playing with toy boats, pretending boulders were islands. Things haven‚Äôt changed much. My fascination with scale is the same as it ever was. The large central rocks are actually just close up photos of the same stones from the beach. I built a small pool and arranged them separately in still water.

Some of my favorite experiences with art started in boredom or confusion, then - after learning about the ideas behind a work, continued in appreciation. How cool is it that we can dialogue with anyone throughout history by responding to them with a few ideas of our own.

This scene may just be a simple sunset (or a boring one), but in addition to memories and scale, here are a few of the random things I was musing on while working:

Six Persimmons - The classic Chinese painting by the Buddhist monk Muqi. (An image that‚Äôs taken me years to understand).

Zen gardens and stones - They‚Äôre often used as a cliche representation for dreamy, sleepy relaxation, spa treatments and the like, when the reality of Zen practice can be quite serious and ardent effort towards waking up. I‚Äôm fascinated by the popular culture misunderstandings, perhaps because I held them so long myself.

Music - Visual spacing and rhythm, horizontal bars and notes; the staccato feeling of eye movement related to musical spacing and rhythm and spacing and rhythm and spacing and rhythm.

Two photos of Common Terns bringing back fish for their chicks that tell a story of climate change in the Gulf of Maine ‚Äì
¬†
As seawater temperatures increase, native fish species that sustain seabirds become scarce, forcing parents to bring their chicks fish that they cannot swallow.
¬†
In the first image the parent returns to its nest with a Sand Lance ‚Äì a slender-bodied silver fish that the chicks can easily swallow.
¬†
The second photo shows a tern parent with a Butterfish in its mouth, a meal the baby birds cannot eat.
¬†
The result is an increase in chick mortality rates.

Cats rule dogs drool

Don‚Äôt shove your cat in their pet carrier right before their vet appointment / traveling causing Meowing and anxiety.
Start acclimating them to their pet carrier now by‚Ä¶
Step 1 Pet carrier near feeding area. Bowl of food placed a few feet from carrier. 
Step 2 Every 2 to 4 days (or at your cats comfortable pace), move food bowl a tadbit closer to carrier.
Step 3 eventually place bowl right inside carrier 
Step 4 Bowl inching its way (every 2-4 days) towards the back of the carrier. 
Step 5 once your cat is comfortably eating the food in the back of the carrier, move the door to see how your cat responds, little by little to desensitise them from the strange and scary sound the door can make closing. Do this a little bit each meal eventually closing and opening the door. 
once you can close it open it and your cat is still eating and comfortable, once closed gently pickup carrier and set back down opening up the carrier. Repeat a few times each meal before carrying it to another room. 
Tips: Use higher value food to speed up the acclamation process. 
Don‚Äôt move to the next step until your cat is comfortable. You can also incorporate toy games in and around the carrier for a positive experience. 
You want to use the same incremental desensitisation  process to acclimate them to your vehicle.
